Template)","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2015-10-31 19:33:34 UTC","updated_at":"2015-10-31 19:33:34 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-british-columbia-generic-template--108","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":2853,"title":"INKE 2.0 Partnership for Open Social Scholarship","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2015-11-02 16:33:54 UTC","updated_at":"2015-11-02 16:49:29 UTC","slug":"inke-2-0-partnership-for-open-social-scholarship","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"The goal of the INKE 2.0 Partnership for Open Social Scholarship is to model, facilitate, and implement a culture of open social scholarship in Canada. Open social scholarship involves the creation, dissemination, and engagement of research and research technologies that are accessible and significant to a broad audience that includes the public. Growing up from its roots in movements associated with open access and public scholarship, open social scholarship involves 1) developing and sharing research in relevant ways for diverse individuals and organizations; 2) theorizing, operationalizing, and implementing that work with consideration of the needs and interests of both academic specialists and communities beyond academia; 3) providing opportunities to co-create, interact with, and experience human, cultural, and scientific data in context; 4) exploring, developing, and making public tools and technologies that serve these ends and bring academic and non-academic researchers into active and productive dialogue with each other.\r\n","principal_investigator":"Raymond G. Siemens ","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Alyssa Arbuckle, 604.880.0384, alyssaarbuckle@gmail.com","funder_name":null},{"id":2854,"title":"My plan (University of British Columbia Generic Template)","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_