t":"2016-04-08 07:25:09 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-british-columbia-generic-template--183","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":3430,"title":"Photvoice Study (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2016-04-08 20:53:48 UTC","updated_at":"2016-04-14 16:59:19 UTC","slug":"photvoice-study-portage-template","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Improving the information literacy skills of international students in the School of Public Health (SPH) is essential not only for their own academic success, but also the health of the communities they will serve as they transition into careers in health-related institutions, public health or medicine. SPH faculty, librarians and practicum supervisors note that these information literacy skills are especially weak or lacking in the international students enrolled in the program.     Although studies have been done with international students that identify their challenges and barriers to finding and using research, to date no study has focused on discovering strategies for mastering these skills.  It is essential to find out what strategies have been successful, and to share these strategies with incoming students at SPH, and perhaps the broader international graduate student community at U of S.\t\r\n\r\nThe research questions are: what academic background are the students coming from, and what was their experience with libraries like?  how do students familiarize themselves with the U of S Library and its services; how do students learn about the process of doing research here?  How do they begin the research to complete their literature search? What strategies have been successful for them?  This project will be a qualitative study using photovoice to stimulate discussion at focus groups.  The transcripts of the focus grou