"slug":"dakota-pipeline-protester-what-is-behind-the-controversy","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Members of the Standing Rock Sioux Tribe and their supporters have protested against the pipeline at a North Dakota site for months, arguing the multi-billion dollar project would contaminate drinking water and damage sacred burial sites. \r\n\r\nThis paper will be examined and answer, what is behind this controversy? and what advantage and disadvantages can bring in the local economy? \r\n\r\nThe objective of this study is to give a unique and broad perspective of this situation trough sentiment analysis and determine how can impact the society. \r\n\r\n\r\n","principal_investigator":"Olga Gonzalez","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":4131,"title":"test","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2016-12-12 19:05:38 UTC","updated_at":"2016-12-12 19:05:47 UTC","slug":"test--13","organisation_id":14,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Dina Shafey","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":4132,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2016-12-12 20:43:41 UTC","updated_at":"2016-12-12 20:43:41 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--756","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"gabriel","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":4135,"title":"TEST (Portage template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2016-12-13 16:37:11 UTC","updated_at":"2016-12-13 16:37:56 UTC","slug":"test-portage-template--2","organisation_id":23,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Test to better understand questions asked in the application. ","principal_investigator":"Janaki Jayanthan","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":4136,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2016-12-13 21:09:44 UTC","updated_at":"2016-12-13 21:09:44 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--760","organisation_id":27,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Joanne Paterson","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":4137,"title":"My plan (University of Alberta Template)","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2016-12-13 21:27:37 UTC","updated_at":"2016-12-13 21:27:37 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-alberta-template--558","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Karen Lara","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":4138,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2016-12-13 22:05:29 UTC","updated_at":"2016-12-13 22:05:29 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--761","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"jojo a-gogo","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":4139,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2016-12-14 13:11:42 UTC","updated_at":"2016-12-14 13:11:42 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--762","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"gabriel","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":4140,"title":"Computational Research on the Ancient Near East: An Archaeological Data Integration, Simulation, and 3-D Visualization Initiative","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2016-12-14 15:54:43 UTC","updated_at":"2016-12-14 16:06:50 UTC","slug":"computational-research-on-the-ancient-near-east-an-archaeological-data-integration-simulation-and-3-d-visualization-initiative","organisation_id":20,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"The Computational Research on the Ancient Near East (CRANE) initiative seeks to build an international multidisciplinary research collaboration, comprised of archaeologists, computer scientists, and paleo-environmental specialists, with the capacity to leverage a burgeoning corpus of data to fundamentally transform our knowledge of the civilizations of the ancient Near East. This deepened understanding will provide insight into a wide range of contemporary concerns, including the ecological impact of anthropogenic changes to the physical environment, the socioeconomic and political impact of climate change, the long-term health consequences of human dietary practices and subsistence strategies, and the role of cultural conflict in affecting social and political change. The CRANE initiative proposes to undertake this by creating a sustainable, scalable, user-driven vehicle for large-scale data management and cross-project data integration that fully integrates the diverse interdisciplinary range of archaeological and humanistic scholarship without requiring that individual data sets, and their existing taxonomies, be forced into a single, uniform format. The CRANE initiative will focus initially on the combining archaeological data from research projects in the Orontes Watershed in southeast Turkey and northwest Syria, which has produced one of the foundational cultural sequences for the Near East. As a cohesive geographical unit, and a cultural microcosm of the broader Near East, it represents an exceptional initial test case. CRANE will provide a model for large scale data-based collaboration among groups of cultural heritage researchers that is interdisciplinary in scope, and transcends any particular time period, cultural region, or subject area.","principal_investigator":"Timothy Harrison","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Stephen Batiuk, 647-470-8164, stephen.batiuk@utoronto.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":4141,"title":"My first DMP","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2016-12-14 17:47:31 UTC","updated_at":"2017-09-11 20:58:17 UTC","slug":"my-first-dmp","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"CU#7524","identifier":"20170731","description":"","principal_investigator":"Jane Fry","principal_investigator_identifier":"9235","data_contact":"jane.fry@carleton.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":4144,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2016-12-14 20:44:54 UTC","updated_at":"2016-12-14 20:44:54 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--767","organisation_id":27,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Elizabeth Hill","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":4146,"title":"My plan (University of British Columbia Generic Template)","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2016-12-16 03:57:55 UTC","updated_at":"2016-12-16 03:57:55 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-british-columbia-generic-template--237","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Arlene Manuel","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":4150,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2016-12-18 22:42:57 UTC","updated_at":"2016-12-18 22:42:57 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--769","organisation_id":10,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"McMaster RDM","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":4151,"title":"My plan (University of Alberta Template)","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2016-12-22 19:12:11 UTC","updated_at":"2016-12-22 19:38:13 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-alberta-template--559","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":"","identifier":"HealthPromoThesis","description":"This cross-sectional observational study will examine the effects of fast food and convenience stores around schools on the food behaviours of junior high school students. This data is being created in partial fulfillment of MSc. thesis requirements and to provide evidence for the Report Card.","principal_investigator":"Jacqueline Burt","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":4152,"title":"Phonetic and Phonological Documentation of Kalasha, an endangered Indo-Aryan language","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2016-12-23 14:58:10 UTC","updated_at":"2017-01-04 17:44:16 UTC","slug":"phonetic-and-phonological-documentation-of-kalasha-an-endangered-indo-aryan-language","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Jeff Mielke","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":4153,"title":"Grub Street Project data management plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2016-12-23 17:20:03 UTC","updated_at":"2016-12-23 17:52:03 UTC","slug":"grub-street-project-data-management-plan-portage-template","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"410-2010-2682","identifier":"","description":"My project creates a digital edition of London (1660-1830) comprised of digitized 17th- and 18th-century \"zoomable\" maps and a database of information concerning the city's writers and booksellers, works, trades, and places. By mapping the city's print culture, literature, and trades, the project aims to create both a historically accurate visualization of the city's commerce and communications, and a record of how its authors and artists portrayed it.\r\n\r\nGrub Street, now subsumed by Milton Street, was both a real place and an abstract idea. For authors such as Alexander Pope and Jonathan Swift, it represented base commercialization, hack writing, and the prostitution of literary ideals. Its historical record, however obscure, presents a more complex scene, and one that is difficult to trace. Where, exactly, was \"over against the lower Pump in Grub-street\" (where one might find the printer John Clowes) or \"in Grub-street neer the upper pump\" (Bernard Alsop) or \"near the Upper-Pump in Grubstreet\" (Elizabeth Alsop)? What is left to us are the traces of this topography in maps, in texts, and in images. Both location and metaphor, this now-vanished street represents what is largely invisible to us now, the print culture of eighteenth-century London (both high and low), and the construction of eighteenth-century London as a network of textual representations. The Grub Street Project examines new possibilities that digital mapping provides to better understand the city as topography and as \"social text.\"\r\n\r\nPhase 1 of this project received funding from SSHRC from 2010-2013. The project creates an accessible publication for members of the public to research the history of the city, its inhabitants, and its literature. It will also create new opportunities for literary and cultural historians to visualize the circulation of ideas (in the form of the physical topography of print networks, and in the less tangible networks of literary discourse). As historians and literary scholars, we regularly imagine dimensions of interpretation ranging from the history of an individual at a specific time and place, to the multifaceted forces and influences of cultural relationships extending over time and space, but digital mapping provides us with a new tool to visualize the spatial particularities of these relationships. It provides a way to navigate physical and mental spaces of London in a synthesis of cultural, temporal, and topographical information in order to create new interpretations.","principal_investigator":"Allison Muri","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":4154,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2016-12-27 06:26:28 UTC","updated_at":"2016-12-27 06:26:28 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--772","organisation_id":14,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Ellen 