ns de recherche, à quelle fin données recueillies)","principal_investigator":"Rachid Belkouch","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0002-4328-3771 (orcid)","data_contact":"Personne-ressource","funder_name":null},{"id":4176,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-01-10 14:34:46 UTC","updated_at":"2017-01-10 14:34:46 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--785","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Suzanne van den Hoogen","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":4177,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-01-10 22:49:30 UTC","updated_at":"2017-01-10 22:49:30 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--786","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Marlene Wagner","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":4178,"title":"Thesis Data","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-01-12 03:28:58 UTC","updated_at":"2017-01-12 03:35:24 UTC","slug":"thesis-data","organisation_id":9,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Discourse analysis of instances in which the eagle feather is deployed throughout interactions between Indigenous peoples and non-Indigenous state representatives or publics. \r\nHow and when is the eagle feather deployed? How it is described and classified in media sources, official documents, and in interviews? What does it's deployment and these descriptions reveal about relations between Indigenous and settler groups?\r\nData collected will be used as examples of events, statements, and photographs that provide evidence for deployments of the eagle feather. This data will be used to theorize how \"religious\" and \"secular\" symbols relate to broader politics in the context of settler colonialism, Canadian governance, and Indigenous sovereignty movements.","principal_investigator":"Stacie Swain","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"780-918-0248","funder_name":null},{"id":4179,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-01-12 16:10:54 UTC","updated_at":"2017-01-12 16:10:54 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--788","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Jane Fry","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":4180,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-01-12 22:14:57 UTC","updated_at":"2017-01-20 21:40:44 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--789","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"435-2016-1555","identifier":"91424","description":"Our SSHRC project, \"Kinship influences on fertility and longevity: a comparative study of two historic founder populations\", studies demographic responses to socio-economic shocks and pressure in pre-demographic transition Quebec and Utah (1800-1900), exploring the mediating role of kinship networks on fertility and mortality outcomes.  We will ask whether Quebec and Utah families reacted to demographic changes and subsistence crises (and their abating) in the same way, for example, by delaying the onset of reproduction or spacing births.  Or, despite similar demographic regimes in terms of founder populations and high fertility, will we detect widely different responses to pressures and crises because of varying cultural practices? We are using existing historical longitudinal and cross-sectional microdata sets to operationalize this study, creating new variables which measure kinship networks and kinship availability in a comparable way across the two regions.\r\n\r\nWhile our study uses data from both Quebec and Utah, the data are managed separately at three institutions: the Université de Montréal, the Université du Québec à Chicoutimi and the University of Utah.  **This DMP focuses on the data managed at the Université de Montréal, as we are unable to provide extensive technical information for the data managed at the other two universities**","principal_investigator":"Lisa Dillon","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":4182,"title":"Young Parents Study (YoPS)","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2017-01-13 20:56:07 UTC","updated_at":"2018-01-17 21:45:56 UTC","slug":"young-parents-study-yops","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"MOP-126032 and GIR-127079 (CIHR)","identifier":"F12-03616 and F12-05593","description":"In 2009, approximately one of six children born in British Columbia (BC) was born to an early-age mother (<25 years of age), with a total of 1,430 live births recorded among mothers younger than 20 years old (an additional 6,201 births occurred in 20-24 year olds). Although overall rates of early-age motherhood have declined during the past three decades, young people who are engaged in parenting (e.g., young women and men ages 15-25 years) continue to face significant health and social challenges in light of social and structural inequalities. Many interventions intended to address the needs of young parents focus on individual-level factors (e.g., enhancing knowledge regarding parenting). While these are important, they do not adequately account for the influence of social context (e.g., ageist social relations that stereotype young parents and their children; gendered power relations) and structural inequalities (e.g., unemployment or income generation opportunities; poverty). Thus, the Young Parents Study aims to:\r\n\r\n\r\n1. Examine the experiences of a cohort of young parents (ages 15-24 years at the time of recruitment) in relation to policy and programming interventions, including those directed at their sexual and reproductive health.\r\nH1.1: Mothers’ and fathers’ experiences with health and social service delivery and policy interventions differ according to the ways in which power relations intersect with their social positions and geographic locations.\r\nH1.2: Power relations amongst mothers and fathers differ across subgroups of the early-age parent population, with elevated power differentials amongst those who are socially-excluded, street-engaged young people as well as racialized youth, including youth who identify as Aboriginal and/or who use illicit drugs.\r\n\r\n\r\n2. Examine the perspectives of service providers, decision makers and community leaders regarding service delivery and policy interventions to address the needs of young parents and their children.\r\n\r\nH2.1: Rural and urban perspectives of service providers, decision makers and community leaders differ, particularly in the ways in which they describe the impacts of physical geography and local social norms and mores on the implementation and uptake of program/policy interventions.\r\n\r\nH2.2: The perspectives of service providers, decision makers and community leaders regarding their capacity to tailor their efforts to address the needs of young parents vary according to the perceived effectiveness of linkages between the health system and other relevant sectors (e.g., child and family services; education; housing).\r\n\r\n\r\n3. Evaluate how young parents’ knowledge, beliefs and practices are influenced by structural factors, including programs/policies.\r\n\r\nH3.1: Withdrawals or reductions in program/policy offerings for young parents (e.g., ageing out) are associated with increases in self-reported concerns and problems pertaining to their health and that of their children.\r\n\r\nH3.2: System-wide program/policy initiatives to address the needs of vulnerable first-time mothers (<25 years of age) and their children (e.g., BC Ministry of Health’s new Nurse Family Partnership Initiative) are associated with changes in young parents’ knowledge, beliefs and practices, although these changes may differ depending on various factors, including: mothers’ age, cultural identity and geographic location.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe five-year study uses longitudinal ethnographic methods (fieldwork; interviews), complemented by policy analysis techniques, to capture and track over time the parenting experiences of a cohort of young people (ages 15-24 years). The study incorporates the perspectives of key disadvantaged subgroups (e.g., those who are socially-excluded, drug-using, and/or racialized). The study includes ethnographic fieldwork and interviews with 150 young mothers living in Prince George, Quesnel or Vancouver (British Columbia), as well as socially significant participants in young mothers lives (e.g., biological fathers of young mothers’ children; step-parents; grandparents). The research examines the experiences of service providers and community leaders (n=60) who undertake and/or support many interventions to address early-age parenthood in the face of important structural inequities (e.g., levels of unemployment and poverty). We also examine the policy discourses underlying the programming and policy interventions that affect early-age mothers and fathers in BC by examining policy documents (released since 2000) that are relevant to early-age parents in BC.\r\n\r\nNote: This five-year ethnographic study is funded by two CIHR grants (UBC BREB # H13-00415):\r\n\r\n1. \"Investigating the influences of social context and structure on young people’s parenting experiences.\" Funded 1 January, 2013 to 31 March, 2018. \r\n\r\n2. \"Population health information interventions: Examining the perspectives of young parents.\" Funded 1 March, 2013 to 28 February, 2015. \r\n\r\nData from this study has been used in two graduate research projects: \r\n\r\n1. Greyson, D. L. (2015). Health-related information practices and the experiences of young parents (T). University of British Columbia. Retrieved from https://open.library.ubc.ca/cIRcle/collections/24/items/1.0166526. \r\n\r\n2. Mniszak, C. (in preparation). Exploring the Information Contexts of Young Fathers in Two British Columbian Cities. MLIS thesis. ","principal_investigator":"Jean Shoveller","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Cathy Chabot; ph. 604-822-3791; cathy.chabot@ubc.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":4183,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-01-14 19:36:18 UTC","updated_at":"2017-01-14 19:36:18 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--791","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Barbara Znamirowski","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":4184,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-01-16 04:57:36 UTC","updated_at":"2017-01-16 04:57:36 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--792","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Reagan Maniar","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":4185,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-01-16 18:31:39 UTC","updated_at":"2017-01-16 18:35:35 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--793","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"895-2015-1002","identifier":"","description":"The eQuality Project is a partnership of academics, community groups, educators and policymakers that maps the ways in which e-marketing analytics sort youth into categories that often reproduce real-world patterns of discrimination and set up young people for online conflict. We’re also using our research findings to create educational and outreach materials that will help young Canadians push back against online harassment, racism, homophobia and misogyny, and make the most of their digital media experiences.  \r\n\r\n","principal_investigator":"Valerie Steeves","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Sarah Heath, 613-562-5800x1541, sheath@uottawa.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":4186,"title":"Young Worker Co-Design","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-01-16 19:58:37 UTC","updated_at":"2017-01-16 20:01:56 UTC","slug":"young-worker-co-design","organisation_id":10,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Sandra Moll","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Biljana Vasilevska","funder_name":null},{"id":4187,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-01-16 20:55:13 UTC","updated_at":"2017-01-16 20:55:13 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--795","organisation_id":20,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Jane Fry","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":4188,"title":"My plan (University of Alberta Template)","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2017-01-16 20:59:06 UTC","updated_at":"2017-01-16 20:59:06 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-alberta-template--561","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Jane Fry","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":4189,"title":"","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-01-17 00:52:36 UTC","updated_at":"2017-01-17 15:13:08 UTC","slug":"--2","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Barbara Znamirowski","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":4192,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-01-17 22:02:05 UTC","updated_at":"2017-01-17 22:02:05 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--799","organisation_id":13,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Matthew C. Hunter","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":4194,"title":"Open Badges for Demonstrating Open Access Compliance: A Pilot Project","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-01-18 18:05:35 UTC","updated_at":"2017-01-25 19:37:31 UTC","slug":"open-badges-for-demonstrating-open-access-compliance-a-pilot-project","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"","identifier":"REB17-0110","description":"This application describes a planned pilot project to develop and test Open Badges, a form of micro credential, to recognize researchers’ compliance with the Tri-Agency Open Access Policy on Publications in a streamlined, visually-appealing manner.  We will develop an open badge, using existing infrastructure at our institution, which indicates compliance with the Policy (University of Calgary, 2015b).  We will then integrate the badge with DSpace 5.5 and explore the feasibility of this integration project using in-house resources.  Additionally, we will explore potential integration of the badge with external sites such as ORCID and the Canadian Common CV.  This development project will allow relevant authors to demonstrate their compliance with the Policy in a portable, open, and attractive fashion, and may increase the perceived value of PRISM, our institutional repository.\r\n\r\n\r\nTo test the utility and perception of the badge system, we will conduct user experience sessions with University of Calgary authors who have implemented a badge on their publication(s) during the pilot period.  Additionally, we will compare the volume of research outputs deposited into PRISM to deposits in similar institutional repositories during the same time period to assess whether the badges were effective as an incentive.\r\n\r\n\r\nIf our pilot project demonstrates success in encouraging compliance, the results of our work will be very relevant to other CARL libraries, particularly those using the DSpace platform to power their institutional repositories.  We are committed to documenting all code, processes, and results in an open access environment, to ensure wide dissemination of our work to others.\r\n","principal_investigator":"Christie Hurrell","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0002-6286-5005","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":4196,"title":"Data Management Plan","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-01-18 20:47:05 UTC","updated_at":"2017-01-27 18:28:35 UTC","slug":"data-management-plan--2","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"5678","identifier":"1234","description":"The nature of this project is to create a data archiving system to be used by the soil moisture research group. \r\n\r\nSome questions that need to be addressed include: where is this research data? How can this research data be more accessible to persons who are seeking it out? How can we keep proprietary data secure and control who sees/uses it?\r\n\r\nData is being collected/created to archive it in a secure repository so that it is not lost at the time of graduation/retirement. Also to ensure data we have collected is more easily distributed and stored. ","principal_investigator":"Chloe Papalazarou","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Aaron Berg","funder_name":null},{"id":4197,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-01-19 05:06:17 UTC","updated_at":"2017-01-19 05:06:17 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--803","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Patrick Neuberger","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":4199,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-01-19 17:11:23 UTC","updated_at":"2017-01-19 17:11:42 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--804","organisation_id":23,"grant_number":"","identifier":"001","description":"","principal_investigator":"Sarah Eaton","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":4200,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-01-19 18:46:43 UTC","updated_at":"2017-01-19 18:46:43 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--805","organisation_id":18,"grant_nu