 16:17:31 UTC","updated_at":"2017-09-13 16:17:31 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-alberta-template--611","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Amber Mosewich","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":4960,"title":"SAMMS (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-09-13 20:28:08 UTC","updated_at":"2017-09-13 20:31:31 UTC","slug":"samms-portage-template","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"SAMMS: Sub-Arctic Metal Mobility Study\r\n\r\nTo address the need to examine legacy metal pollution from mining with changes in DOM and hydrology due to climate change in the NWT, the Sub-Arctic Metal Mobility Study (SAMMS) will undertake six work packages. These have been designed to comprehensively trace the transport and behaviour of DOM and metals through terrestrial and aquatic ecosystems in headwater catchments along a 200 km transect between Giant Mine and Whatì, an area of concentrated mining activity. Work packages include: 1) terrestrial stores of historical metal deposition and transport to aquatic ecosystems, 2) DOM quantity and quality, metal binding, and toxicology, 3) modelling DOM quantity and quality in cold regions, 4) metal depositional history, pathways, and processes in lake sediments, 5) paleo-ecotoxicology and ecosystem structure, and 6) climate change effects including permafrost thaw. Findings will inform improved decision-making by multiple stakeholders in the NWT, including Indigenous peoples, about the legacy of mining activities on past, present, and future water quality","principal_investigator":"Jason Venkiteswaran","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0002-6574-7071","data_contact":"Jason Venkiteswaran","funder_name":null},{"id":4961,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-09-13 20:49:50 UTC","updated_at":"2017-09-13 20:49:50 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--1276","organisation_id":21,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"daniel B","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":4962,"title":"Elise Chenier","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-09-13 21:14:51 UTC","updated_at":"2017-09-13 21:15:12 UTC","slug":"elise-chenier","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Bridging the Gap","principal_investigator":"Elise Chenier","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":4963,"title":"My plan (University of British Columbia Generic Template)","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2017-09-14 01:18:43 UTC","updated_at":"2017-09-14 01:18:43 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-british-columbia-generic-template--291","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Eunice Chan","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":4964,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-09-14 06:40:36 UTC","updated_at":"2017-09-14 06:40:36 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--1278","organisation_id":23,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Eunice Chan","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":4965,"title":"Bearwatch","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-09-15 00:05:36 UTC","updated_at":"2017-09-15 00:13:53 UTC","slug":"bearwatch","organisation_id":33,"grant_number":"10404","identifier":"300142","description":"The Bearwatch project will develop a non-invasive, fecal-based biomarker toolkit and a community-based monitoring program for polar bears. The project will combine leading-edge genomics with comprehensive social science, developed and implemented within a framework of collaboration with northern communities, indigenous organizations and territorial and other levels of government. It will result in a database that combines IQ and other indigenous traditional ecological knowledge with polar bear genetic identity and ecological and physiological measures that permit assessment of bear health. The community-based monitoring program will provide ongoing data for tracking changes in polar bear populations.\r\n","principal_investigator":"Stephen C. Lougheed","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"lough@queensu.ca, 613-533-6128","funder_name":null},{"id":4966,"title":"Test OAC workshop (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-09-15 19:02:07 UTC","updated_at":"2017-10-25 19:17:24 UTC","slug":"test-oac-workshop-portage-template","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Carol Perry","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":4967,"title":"Test plan","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-09-15 21:51:12 UTC","updated_at":"2017-09-15 21:51:43 UTC","slug":"test-plan--7","organisation_id":28,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Test RDM plan","principal_investigator":"Ashley Haughton","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":4968,"title":"Six Seasons of the Asiniskow Ithiniwak: Reclamation, Regeneration, and Reconciliation","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-09-18 14:45:41 UTC","updated_at":"2017-09-18 14:48:40 UTC","slug":"six-seasons-of-the-asiniskow-ithiniwak-reclamation-regeneration-and-reconciliation","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"895-2017-1002","identifier":"","description":"The overall goal of this project is to move forward the ongoing work of reclaiming Aboriginal languages, histories, and knowledges among the Asiniskow Ithiniwak (Rocky Cree), work that is taking\r\nplace now in the context of the calls to action by the Truth and Reconciliation Commission of Canada\r\n(2015) for, among many other things, the revitalization of Aboriginal cultures, the \"relearning of\r\nCanada's national history,\" and the reconciliation between Aboriginal and non-Aboriginal people. The\r\nobjectives and activities of the project are to undertake collaborative, community-directed archaeological\r\nresearch in order to advance the understanding of the Rocky Cree during the protocontact period of the\r\nmid-1600s; to build a rich historical understanding of the people of the region at the time; to create a\r\ncycle of stories about the life of the Rocky Cree that is grounded in the archaeological and historical\r\nrecords and set during the six seasons of the Rocky Cree year; to translate the oral stories into a series of\r\npicture books directed to young people, into a series of digital texts that invite players to actively engage\r\nthe Rocky Cree world, and into travelling and permanent museum exhibits; to develop teachers' guides\r\nto support the curricular use of the narratives and to provide training for educators in culturally\r\ncompetent pedagogy; to document, analyze, and assess the methods of collaborative, participatory, and\r\ncommunity-based research used by project researchers; and to mobilize the results of this meta-analysis\r\nfor the purpose of advancing public policy and programming for reconciliation.","principal_investigator":"Mavis Reimer","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Larissa Wodtke, 204-786-9351, l.wodtke@uwinnipeg.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":4969,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-09-18 19:11:13 UTC","updated_at":"2017-09-18 19:11:13 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--1283","organisation_id":29,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Marie-Eve Dugas","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":4970,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-09-18 19:31:48 UTC","updated_at":"2017-09-18 19:31:48 UTC","sl