s in surburban schools and urban schools.  The research collected shows the disparities between suburban and urban schools, and as a result the urban schools are in extreme poverty. The research collected explains some stereotypes and consequences of urban schools and teachers, and some strategies and policies that have been used to create equal educational opportunity for low funded schools and their students. ","principal_investigator":"Kristy DePierro","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Kristy DePierro kdepierr@uwo.ca or kitra21@hotmail.com 519-719-0810","funder_name":null},{"id":5208,"title":"Engaging people living with dementia in product design and testing - a case study toward best practice","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-11-14 20:47:33 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-20 03:08:38 UTC","slug":"engaging-people-living-with-dementia-in-product-design-and-testing-a-case-study-toward-best-practice","organisation_id":27,"grant_number":"AGE-WELL Strategic Investment Program","identifier":"Not available","description":"This project explores how entrepreneurs can engage people with dementia meaningfully and respectfully in the design and testing of information communication technologies (ICTs) intended for their use. Increasingly, people with dementia want to be involved in the development of products and services that impact them. However, few resources exist to support entrepreneurs looking to engage people with dementia on technology projects.\r\n\r\nFor this research, we will monitor and document the engagement of people with dementia in design and testing of MemorySparx One, a digital memory aid that is currently being developed by Emmetros. Data collected during this study will inform practical resources for entrepreneurs and people with dementia looking to collaborate on technology projects. Ideally, increased engagement of people with dementia will improve the usability and usefulness of products intended for their use, enabling them to live independently and with dignity.\r\n\r\nProject collaborators: University of Waterloo (UW), Murray Alzheimer Research and Education Program (MAREP), Emmetros, Ontario Dementia Advisory Group (ODAG)","principal_investigator":"Lisa Loiselle, Associate Director of Research, MAREP","principal_investigator_identifier":"Not available ","data_contact":"Jennifer Krul, jkrul@uwo.com","funder_name":null},{"id":5210,"title":"My plan (University of Alberta Template)","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2017-11-15 19:12:41 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-15 19:12:41 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-alberta-template--626","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":5211,"title":"Accessing Food, Considering Culture: Sociocultural Elements of Immigrant Food Access Choices in Toronto's Inner Suburbs","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-11-16 02:07:12 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-16 02:13:30 UTC","slug":"accessing-food-considering-culture-sociocultural-elements-of-immigrant-food-access-choices-in-toronto-s-inner-suburbs","organisation_id":27,"grant_number":"not applicable","identifier":"12113","description":"This research project examines food access practices of immigrant households within the Flemingdon Park neighbourhood of Toronto Ontario. \r\n\r\nThe research questions addressed are: \r\n\r\nWhether the conventional conception of food access being about geographic proximity is empirically accurate in the real world.\r\n\r\nWhat challenges are faced by immigrant households in acquiring culturally important foods?\r\n\r\nThe data are being created in order to better understand cultural food access patterns within and around the Flemingdon Park area of Toronto, and the challenges faced by its residents.\r\n","principal_investigator":"Jim Seale","principal_investigator_identifier":"No ORCID","data_contact":"226-504-1002, jseale3@uwo.ca ","