ll join the discourse on the availability of high-speed Internet access for rural and remote residents of Canada by examining who owns the licenses for valuable wireless data transmission frequencies across the country. ","principal_investigator":"Kris Joseph","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":5225,"title":"Information Practices in World of Warcraft","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-11-20 17:08:47 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-24 01:50:42 UTC","slug":"information-practices-in-world-of-warcraft","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"This research seeks to explore the ways in which information is sought, used, and shared in the Massively Multiplayer Online Role Playing Game, World of Warcraft. Information is ubiquitous within video games, as it is essential for both game design and play. Information is incorporated into World of Warcraft through interface design, the dissemination of information for player progression, and the information practices of players. Information practices include all activities present in information seeking, including what people do and say, as well as how they engage with others while seeking, using, and sharing information. This research project will answer two key questions: (1) how do World of Warcraft players discover the information they need in order to play and successfully progress through the game; and (2) what are the information practices of and between World of Warcraft players? This data is being collected by the principal investigator in order to complete her dissertation for her doctoral degree. ","principal_investigator":"Caroline Whippey","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"cwhippey@uwo.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":5226,"title":"Domna Kapetanos (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-11-20 17:57:19 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-25 00:55:04 UTC","slug":"domna-kapetanos-portage-template","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"","identifier":"Domna Kapetanos research proposal","description":"The overall objective of my research will be to determine the role of the modern library, in the context of measuring research impact for new, non-traditional modes of scholarly communication. \r\n\r\nData collected for the purposes of identifying what efforts are being made by research libraries today to successfully transition to the use of alternative research metrics for the evaluation of scholarly research in the changing information landscape. ","principal_investigator":"Domna  Kapetanos","principal_investigator_identifier":"Domna Kapetanos","data_contact":"dkapetan@uwo.ca; ","funder_name":null},{"id":5227,"title":"UROP","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-11-20 19:52:18 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-20 19:54:25 UTC","slug":"urop","organisation_id":9,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"A textual analysis of newsletters published by the Educational Computing Organization of Ontario. The goal is to understand who was contributing to the conversation about computing in education during the 1980s in Ontario, and to consider how excitement at the time might inform similar efforts today.","principal_investigator":"Lucas Cherkewski","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"519-577-1865, lucas@lucascherkewski.com","funder_name":null},{"id":5228,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-11-20 20:42:44 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-20 20:43:58 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--1441","organisation_id":33,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Courtney Matthews","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":5229,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-11-20 21:25:39 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-20 21:25:39 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--1442","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Christine Picken","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":5231,"title":"Humanitarianism & Its Histories: Building Cross-Sectoral Partnerships in Canadian Humanitarian Aid and Development Work","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-11-21 05:13:27 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-24 12:44:49 UTC","slug":"humanitarianism-its-histories-building-cross-sectoral-partnerships-in-canadian-humanitarian-aid-and-development-work","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"Someday?","identifier":"XXXXXXX","description":"Humanitarian aid and development work have become highly visible and controversial expressions of the increasing interconnectedness of the global community since the end of the Second World War. As one of the first developed countries to become involved in governmental and not-for-profit development work, Canada is an important component of this history. Aid organizations have served as training grounds for generations of Canadian diplomats and civil servants, as well as many Canadians’ first and only point of engagement with the “global South.”  Yet scholarship that examines Canadians’ past contributions to international humanitarian aid remains marginal. The Carleton University-based project “Humanitarianism and Its Histories: Building Cross-Sectoral Partnerships in Canadian Humanitarian Aid and Development Work,” led by Dominique Marshall, draws together scholars, archivists, and aid workers in collaborative scholarship. As secondary aims, the project will build a network of Canadian scholars studying humanitarian history, and develop teaching resources in the field. The major goal of the project, however, is to support aid organizations in identifying, collecting, preserving, and making accessible their (non-active) historical files and artifacts. These materials will be used as research data by the scholars attached to the project, resulting in the production of scholarly articles and conference papers, as well as timelines and historical exhibits for the aid organizations’ own websites. Beyond these present-day research outputs, the harvesting and preservation of aid organizations’ historical documents for the benefit of generations of scholars and practitioners to come is, in and of itself, the primary goal of the project. These valuable materials have a history of being lost or destroyed in the face of the organizations’ limited and fluctuating resources, high rates of staff turnover, and frequent moves of headquarters. A concerted effort to harvest and preserve these materials in publicly-accessible venues will enable historians and scholars of many disciplines to analyze and disseminate the history of Canadian humanitarian work. In turn, those scholarly research outputs will better enable present-day aid practitioners (whose work inherently requires them to focus their resources intensively on the present emergency, with little time to reflect on the past) to learn from the challenges and build on the successes of their predecessors. ","principal_investigator":"Dominique Marshall","principal_investigator_identifier":"XXXXXXX","data_contact":"Sarah Glassford","funder_name":null},{"id":5233,"title":"Evaluating the Rural Hotspot Lending Programme in Southern Ontario","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-11-21 18:04:23 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-24 14:09:41 UTC","slug":"evaluating-the-rural-hotspot-lending-programme-in-southern-ontario","organisation_id":27,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"This project aims to look at the effectiveness of the Rural Hotspot Lending programme in the County of Wellington Library. It will be ongoing so long as the programmme is running. The data will be collected though circulation counts, online surveys and voluntary interviews by members of the county. The data collected will be used for the library and for other libraries looking into creating a similar programme.","principal_investigator":"Ailish Farrelly","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":5234,"title":"Projet Observatoire","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-11-21 20:42:26 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-21 20:43:23 UTC","slug":"projet-observatoire","organisation_id":32,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Tommy Chevrette","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Tommy_Chevrette@uqac.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":5235,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-11-21 22:48:01 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-21 22:48:01 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--1447","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Nicola Oddy","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":5236,"title":"MLCS 795","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2017-11-21 23:45:52 UTC","updated_at":"2019-11-20 00:56:20 UTC","slug":"mlcs-795","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Doris Wagner","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":5237,"title":"Persons who jump from the bridges of the lower mainland","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2017-11-22 06:02:27 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-22 06:17:53 UTC","slug":"persons-who-jump-from-the-bridges-of-the-lower-mainland","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"","identifier":"H16-02263","description":"The project looks to understand the response to people who jump from bridges in the lower mainland. The Canadian Coast Guard (CCG) works in conjunction with the Vancouver Police Department (VPD), Royal Canadian Mounted Police (RCMP) British Columbia Emergency Health Services (BCEHS), volunteer Search and Rescue groups, and the coroner to respond to suicides from the bridges of Vancouver. Preliminary statistics suggest that 20 to 40 people jump each year in the Lower Mainland. An unknown, but significant number of persons also threaten to jump each year, but are detained by police prior to jumping. The survival rates and long term outcomes are not known, and not well represented in the literature. The project's primary goal is to establish what factors significantly influence patient outcomes following a jump, and tailor response protocols to these factors. The projects’ secondary objectives include: building a picture of the population that jumps, uncovering trends in time or location, and study communication between partner agencies. The project proposes to address this question using a multi-agency retrospective chart review to build a complete picture of patient care and outcomes from the time they jump to hospital discharge or death. ","principal_investigator":"Jeffery Brubacher","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Dylan Stephanian","funder_name":null},{"id":5238,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-11-22 14:09:13 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-22 14:09:13 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--1448","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Xiaohong Yang","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":5239,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-11-22 14:09:18 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-22 14:09:18 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--1449","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Xiaohong Yang","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":5240,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-11-22 14:09:24 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-22 14:09:24 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--1450","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Xiaohong Yang","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":5241,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-11-22 19:39:21 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-22 19:39:21 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--1451","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Tejomayee Singh","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":5242,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-11-22 23:27:45 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-22 23:27:45 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--1452","organisation_id":14,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Georgina  Rae","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":5243,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-11-23 18:49:41 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-23 18:49:41 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--1453","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Lise Matzke","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":5244,"title":"Donation after Cardiocirculatory Determination of Death (DCD):  A Multicenter Study of Current Practices and Outcomes ","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2017-11-23 19:03:51 UTC","updated_at":"2017-12-04 18:37:55 UTC","slug":"donation-after-cardiocirculatory-determination-of-death-dcd-a-multicenter-study-of-current-practices-and-outcomes","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"The study aims to report on initial experiences with DCD across Western Canada and determine whether characteristics of controlled DCD organ donors can be linked to pertinent outcomes in DCD organ transplant recipients.  Through retrospective case review, DCD donor and recipient characteristics, as well procurement and transplant management, will be investigated in order to inform future DCD practices. ","principal_investigator":"Sean Keenan","principal_investigator_identifier":"George Isac","data_contact":"Kerry Holliday, Project Manager,  Alberta Health Services. Kerry.Holliday@ahs.ca, (587) 223-5550","funder_name":null},{"id":5245,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-11-23 23:21:13 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-23 23:21:13 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--1454","organisation_id":27,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Delaney Brown","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":5246,"title":"To Snap or Not to Snap? Snapchat in Libraries","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-11-23 23:27:46 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-24 01:25:17 UTC","slug":"to-snap-or-not-to-snap-snapchat-in-libraries","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"This research project looks at the use of the social media application Snapchat in libraries using an ethical framework. While seemingly harmless, there have been many concerns regarding Snapchat's privacy policy, especially in terms of the storage and use of users' data and metadata. This project strives to address the ethical implications of using Snapchat in libraries, through an in-depth analysis of Snapchat's privacy policy and case studies of libraries that have integrated Snapchat into their regular programming. The theoretical framework of rule utilitarianism which adheres to the Principle of Utility was applied throughout this research. This project addressed the major research question: \"Is it ethical to incorporate Snapchat into library programming, services, marketing, and public outreach given the large number of privacy concerns it poses?\". The major research question was then deconstructed into four minor ones: \"To what degree does Snapchat jeopardize patron privacy?\", \"To what degree do library stakeholders benefit from the use of Snapchat?\". \"Does the library's use of Snapchat create greater happiness or harm for library stakeholders?\", and \"Should libraries promote the use of Snapchat?\". ","principal_investigator":"Sydney Crombleholme","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":5247,"title":"Walking and its effect on sleep efficiency among office workers in a multi-age group","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-11-24 00:14:21 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-24 21:34:40 UTC","slug":"walking-and-its-effect-on-sleep-efficiency-among-office-workers-in-a-multi-age-group","organisation_id":27,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"This project is aimed at studying before and after effects of walking and its impact on sleep duration and efficiency among office workers aged 20-50.\r\nThe project will address the question whether moderate physical activity can be regarded beneficial for humans sleep quality.\r\nThe data collected will describe people's workout and sleeping habits before and after they walked 10000 steps every day for 2 moths.","principal_investigator":"Marina Mikhonova","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"mmikhono@uwo.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":5248,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-11-24 00:23:21 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-24 00:23:21 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--1457","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Amanda Gaucher","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":5249,"title":"The Library as Collaborative Learning Space: a Needs Assessment of the Brescia Community ","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-11-24 02:33:44 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-24 16:50:50 UTC","slug":"the-library-as-collaborative-learning-space-a-needs-assessment-of-the-brescia-community","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"N/A","identifier":"N/A","description":"The research project with gather data on how Brescia University College students, staff, and faculty use and view the Beryl Ivey Library services, spaces, and resources; what the barriers are to using Library services, spaces, and resources; and what a future 'collaborative learning space' looks like for the Brescia community. Feedback from the Brescia community will allow the Library to identify and clarify service priorities and allocate resources so that Library services, spaces, and resources are in strong alignment with the evolving needs of our community. Further, data gathered will support Brescia's strategic plan five-year outcome for the Library which states that “The Beryl Ivey Library is a fully functioning, flexible, collaborative learning space that supports high impact learning, teaching, and research.” \r\nThe study combines multiple methods of inquiry in order to collect both qualitative and quantitative data through survey, focus groups, observational data, and 'pop-up' display feedback. ","principal_investigator":"Kate Norton","principal_investigator_identifier":"N/A","data_contact":"519-432-8353; kate.norton@uwo.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":5252,"title":"My plan (University of British Columbia Generic Template)","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2017-11-24 15:03:15 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-24 15:03:15 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-british-columbia-generic-template--327","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Jeff Moon","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":5253,"title":"Data Management Plan for Dr. Brent Else","dmptemplate_id":28,"created_at":"2017-11-24 16:42:41 UTC","updated_at":"2017-11-25 16:08:46 UTC","slug":"data-management-plan-for-dr-brent-else","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Adrienne Colborne","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_c