re severe. The patients will\r\nthen be asked to report how they felt after using the medication each time. The study will assess: time to onset\r\nof headache relief, headache severity 2 hours postdose and whether or not patients became largely symptoms-\r\nfree (including associated symptoms), and when they were able to resume normal activities","principal_investigator":"Kathy Szigeti","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0003-1790-9790","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":5266,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-12-01 18:00:43 UTC","updated_at":"2017-12-01 18:00:43 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--1466","organisation_id":23,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Research.Data @UCalgary.ca","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":5267,"title":"Indigenous Women and Youth Resilience Archive","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-12-01 20:11:13 UTC","updated_at":"2017-12-01 20:12:40 UTC","slug":"indigenous-women-and-youth-resilience-archive","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Tracy Bear","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"tracybear@ualberta.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":5268,"title":"Observing and Responding to Pressures on Arctic Marine Ecosystem Services","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-12-03 19:03:01 UTC","updated_at":"2017-12-03 19:08:37 UTC","slug":"observing-and-responding-to-pressures-on-arctic-marine-ecosystem-services","organisation_id":23,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Dr. Brent Else","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":5269,"title":"RDM Format Lifecycle Analysis Plan","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-12-03 21:55:46 UTC","updated_at":"2017-12-08 06:02:42 UTC","slug":"rdm-format-lifecycle-analysis-plan","organisation_id":20,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"This project entails the preservation of the Research Object \"RDM Formats Lifecycle Analysis\" created by Christoph Becker & Kresimir Duretec as a result of their studies into digital objects' format popularity of use and potential obsolescence over time.\r\n\r\nAs this study contains relevant research data into the study of format obsolescence and is relevant to UofT's data preservation guidelines, this plan is created to document the actions undertaken.","principal_investigator":"Cristoph Becker and Kresimir Duretec","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Catherine Orr (cathy.orr@mail.utoronto.ca) & Chris Dillon (chris.dillon@mail.utoronto.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":5270,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-12-04 03:00:15 UTC","updated_at":"2017-12-04 03:00:25 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--1470","organisation_id":15,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Brian Lesser","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":5271,"title":"Addressing Sexual- and drug-related HIV risk among young gay, bisexual and other MSM","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2017-12-04 18:54:19 UTC","updated_at":"2020-04-28 16:48:09 UTC","slug":"addressing-sexual-and-drug-related-hiv-risk-among-young-gay-bisexual-and-other-msm","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"392517","identifier":"","description":"This five-year implementation science study uses a mixed methods approach to address the dual harms associated with the sexualized use of substances among young gay and bisexual men who have sex with men (gbMSM). Two key interventions have been identified as both innovative and promising in their ability to address both the sexual- and drug-related HIV risk among young gbMSM: Mpowerment and Health Initiative for Men (HIM). Five key knowledge partners have also been identified, including: YouthCO, HIM, BC MOH, BCCSU and BCCDC. The aims outlined for this research team include: 1. Develop and use harmonized data systems to monitor and inform key intervention implementation\r\ndecisions to reduce sexual- and drug-related HIV risk among young gbMSM.\r\n2. Identify new actionable strategies for adapting and scaling up interventions to reduce sexual- and\r\ndrug-related HIV risk among young gbMSM in BC. \r\n3. Launch new training and mentoring opportunities and build multi-sectoral capacity to inform\r\nintervention implementation. \r\n\r\nThe Team's research objectives are as follows: \r\n1. Characterize and prospectively monitor patterns and contexts of substance use, sexual behaviour,\r\nand resultant health outcomes among young gbMSM in BC.\r\n2. Identify and respond to intervention implementation gaps, including instances where interventions\r\ndifferentially affect outcomes across population sub-groups of young gbMSM in BC.\r\n3. Identify the implementation factors that promote the effective, ethical and evidence-informed scale-up of interventions across contexts and population sub-groups of young gbMSM in BC.\r\n\r\nThese objectives will be achieved through the completion of the following research activities on an annual basis: \r\n1) Interviews with 50 young gbMSM who use substances; \r\n2) Interviews with 40 key stakeholders; 3) Interviews with 15-20 Mpowerment participants; \r\n4) Interviews with 30 HIM clients; 5)Data harmonization among existing cohorts; \r\n6) Systematic reviews to address gaps in knowledge (2 annually) and \r\n7) Participatory Planning Summits with young men, research partners, and co-investigators.\r\n\r\nDuring Year 1 of the study, our research team received feedback during a Participatory Planning Summit that led us to include revised inclusion criteria for some of our sub-studies. The decision was made by the PIs and supported by research partners (including YouthCO and HiM, who were going through similar processes) to include young Two-Spirit, lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender, queer, intersex, and other gender diverse people (2SLGBTQI+). The section below on data collection provides details regarding the recruitment criteria for each sub-study.","principal_investigator":"Rod Knight and Jean Shoveller","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Anna Carson- Anna.carson@bccsu.ubc.ca until April 2019, Jill Aalhus April 2019-May 2020, Anna Carson after May 2020","funder_name":null},{"id":5272,"title":"Negotiating National Identity in Dubbed Film Humour: The Case Of Québec and Ukraine","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2017-12-04 19:29:40 UTC","updated_at":"2017-12-04 19:35:59 UTC","slug":"negotiating-national-identity-in-dubbed-film-humour-the-case-of-quebec-and-ukraine","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"The present research aims to investigate the concept of national identity in film humour dubbed in Ukraine and Québec in the last decade. Through an in-depth analysis of six American films dubbed into Ukrainian and Québec French, the study will zoom in on: 1) various norms and strategies used by dubbing studios to render humour; 2) strategies of negotiating national identity in translated works; and 3) the role of agents involved in dubbing. The paper hypothesizes that the norms and strategies of dubbing humour into Ukrainian promote the construction of national identity. These norms and strategies will be investigated, analysed, documented and compared with the ones applied by the Québec dubbing industry in order to explore the differences and similarities of nation building through dubbing in the two contexts. ","principal_investigator":"Olga Ivanova","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":5273,"title":"My plan (University of Alberta Template)","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2017-12-04 20:13:47 UTC","updated_at":"2017-12-04 20:13:47 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-alberta-template--634","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Roderick Johnson","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":5274,"title":"Machine learning applied to PET/CT","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-12-04 20:56:24 UTC","updated_at":"2017-12-13 19:03:47 UTC","slug":"machine-learning-applied-to-pet-ct","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"The aim of the study is to make available anonymized PET/CT images, image requisition data, and imaging reports for training of machine learning algorithms designed for automated multimodality registration, normal structure segmentation, and lesion identification. Data will be collected retrospectively. There is no clinical intervention in this study.\r\n\r\nOnce developed, those algorithms could eventually be used for other retrospective and prospective projects to increase the efficiency of research involving analysis of PET/CT and to extract a maximal amount of useful data from the images.","principal_investigator":"François Bénard","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"etrousseau@bccrc.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":5276,"title":"My plan (University of Alberta Template)","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2017-12-05 22:55:08 UTC","updated_at":"2017-12-05 22:55:08 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-alberta-template--635","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":5277,"title":"Psychsocial motor study","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2017-12-06 01:06:59 UTC","updated_at":"2017-12-06 01:08:21 UTC","slug":"psychsocial-motor-study","organisation_id":14,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":5279,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_i