 19:00:03 UTC","updated_at":"2018-09-04 19:00:23 UTC","slug":"mon-plan-universite-de-montreal-fr--15","organisation_id":32,"grant_number":"8766276","identifier":"123432422","description":"","principal_investigator":"Sébastien Roy","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":6234,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2018-09-04 20:13:28 UTC","updated_at":"2018-09-04 20:13:28 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2035","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Yi Fei Chen","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":6235,"title":"Family Farms - Letters and Emails to Government","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2018-09-04 20:24:44 UTC","updated_at":"2018-09-04 20:25:24 UTC","slug":"family-farms-letters-and-emails-to-government","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Emily Reid-Musson","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":6237,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2018-09-05 18:22:31 UTC","updated_at":"2018-09-05 19:18:04 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2037","organisation_id":23,"grant_number":"","identifier":"00225881","description":"Indigenous Women, Survivance, and Post Incarcertaion\r\nThe number of Indigenous women entering into federal corrections facilities continues to climb despite Canada’s political narrative shifting to one of relationship building and reconciliation.  In 2001, the number of Indigenous women who were newly admitted to a federal corrections institution was reported to be 55, and this number has increased to 124 over a 14 year period (StatsCan, 2018). In 2017, despite representing only 4.16% of the Canadian female population, Indigenous women represented 39% of all federally incarcerated women (Reitano, 2017; Statscan, 2017).  To address the overrepresentation of Indigenous peoples in corrections facilities, Correctional Service Canada (CSC) has developed Aboriginal cultural programming. Even though Indigenous cultures and communities vary significantly across Canada, the current correctional policies offer a pan-Indigenous or one-size-fits-all model of programming within a federal corrections institution (CSC, 2014). Even though pan-Indigenous education and curriculum training is understood to have negative impacts on one’s personal identity, there has been limited research to examine the implications of the CSC’s Aboriginal cultural programming on Indigenous women’s perceptions of self post-incarceration.\r\n\r\nThe following research question will serve as a guide throughout the project: How does the CSC’s pan-Indigenous Aboriginal cultural program impact the cultural identity of Indigenous women post-incarceration? The objective of this project is to examine the experiences of Indigenous women who have participated in the CSC’s Aboriginal cultural programming to understand the impacts of the program on an Indigenous woman’s cultural identity post-incarceration. The goal is to evaluate the effectiveness of such a program from the participant’s perspectives rather than those of administrators within the system. The project aims to make way for the voices and actions of the women to stand on their own in the hopes of influencing corrections programming and policy.","principal_investigator":"Alicia Clifford","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Alicia Clifford","funder_name":null},{"id":6238,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2018-09-05 22:19:08 UTC","updated_at":"2018-09-05 22:19:08 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2038","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Calum Center","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":6239,