ant_number":"","identifier":"1005016","description":"Use the information content of firm disclosures to generate more accurate predictions of the diffusion rates of, and payoffs from, emerging technologies.","principal_investigator":"Theophanis Stratopoulos","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0001-9106-7187","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":6453,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2018-10-04 17:34:46 UTC","updated_at":"2018-10-04 18:10:52 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2156","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":6454,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2018-10-04 20:15:02 UTC","updated_at":"2018-10-04 20:17:18 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2157","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Linking tourism, social/cultural capital, and disaster recovery: Comparative perspectives from Nepal, Indonesia and the Philippines.\r\n\r\nThe research goal is to analyze intersections between disaster recovery, cultural/social capital, and tourism, with the aim of improving disaster recovery programming and vulnerability reduction in a developing country context. Specific objectives are: 1. To explore the multiple ways in which tourism influences disaster recovery; 2. To trace the specific influence and importance of community cultural and social capital as this intersects with the tourism sector in a post-disaster recovery context; 3. To examine the degree to which disaster recovery lessons relating to tourism, and cultural and social capital, are similar or different across diverse communities in developing countries.  \r\n\r\nData are collected for student thesis and PI/co-I publication purposes","principal_investigator":"Brent Doberstein","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":6455,"title":"My plan (University of Alberta Template)","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2018-10-04 21:50:59 UTC","updated_at":"2018-10-04 21:50:59 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-alberta-template--697","organisation_id":2,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Sara O'Shaughnessy","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":6456,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2018-10-04 21:51:29 UTC","updated_at":"2018-10-04 21:51:29 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2158","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Sara O'Shaughnessy","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":6458,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2018-10-04 22:35:46 UTC","updated_at":"2018-10-04 22:35:46 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2159","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Melissa Orobko","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":6459,"title":"Digital Codex Marchalianus","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2018-10-05 14:47:31 UTC","updated_at":"2018-10-05 14:49:16 UTC","slug":"digital-codex-marchalianus","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"The seventh-century Codex Marchalianus (Q, Vaticanus graecus 2125) is one of the most important yet inaccessible manuscripts of the Greek Bible. This project will unlock this value by producing a set of digital editions of Codex Marchalianus that can be repurposed for a variety of other areas of research and disciplines.\r\n\r\nQ is important because (1) it attests a text that in the case of Isaiah at least, could well be more free from scribal corruptions than any other manuscript of the Greek Bible; (2) it  preserves a wealth of marginal notes recording readings from alternate translations of the Hebrew scriptures; (3) it includes marginal notes that indicate how the divine name was written and pronounced; (4) it includes two versions of a pseudepigraphal “Lives of the Prophets.” \r\n\r\nYet this important manuscript has until two years ago been accessible only through a few monochrome heliotype facsimiles made in 1890. Although scattered parts (“Lives”, Daniel, Amos 9:12-15, Hosea 1:1-2:17) have been transcribed and published, no transcription of the scriptural text or marginalia has been attempted, so that its textual readings are accessible only indirectly through collations in the editions of the Septuagint and the Hexapla. Then in November 2016 the Vatican posted high quality colour photos of this manuscript online, making it more accessible for scholarly use.\r\n\r\nThis project is to transcribe the text represented on the manuscript photographs (both main text and marginalia and interlinear notes) to make the data recorded in this manuscript available to a wide audience, following a time-honoured tradition of editing and publishing primary texts. Yet this project will push that tradition into the digital age in two ways: method and output. \r\n\r\nWhereas the time-honoured way is also time consuming, the way of the future combines a set of unified software tools that simplify and ease future work on other texts. The use of computer assisted editing is not in itself new; numerous computer tools already exist to assist in the production of machine-readable texts. What is new is the integration of such computer tools for every stage of the workflow. Because each stage of the workflow will use a combination of automated data enrichment and human input, curation, and editing, the challenge is twofold: on the one hand, one needs the human skills of paleography, codicology, philology (morphology, lexis, and syntax), translation, and alignment (to images and translation), but also one must design or adapt the algorithms and data structures that alleviate the tedium of some of these tasks.\r\n\r\nThe outputs of this project will include not only the standard print edition with introduction, conventional transcription, and translation, but because this edition is born digital, it will be made accessible online accompanied by a rich set of metadata. This metadata will not only enable human readers to customize how the text is presented to them and to search for specific linguistic features, but it will also expose its data in standard ways (primarily the TEI standard) to automated text processors (via standard APIs), thus opening the textual data to be repurposed for discoveries yet to be imagined.\r\n","principal_investigator":"Ken M. Penner","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0003-1971-9579","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":6460,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2018-10-05 16:20:32 UTC","updated_at":"2018-10-05 16:20:32 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2161","organisation_id":37,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Asako Yoshida","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":6461,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2018-10-05 17:59:26 UTC","updated_at":"2018-10-05 17:59:26 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2162","organisation_id":43,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":6462,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2018-10-05 19:37:48 UTC","updated_at":"2018-10-05 19:37:48 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2163","organisation_id":20,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":6463,"