ps","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"145401","identifier":"361347","description":"Our research aims to contribute evidence of promising relational approaches to care in late life, using qualitative research to examine and document the multi-level complexities of late life issues in LTC settings.\r\n\r\nIn this project we will conduct primary qualitative case study research using ethnographic qualitative methods--observations, key informant and focus group interviews--to explore how relationships are experienced and understood by all the paid and unpaid participants in LTC, and how gender and culture shape relational late life care.\r\n\r\nOur research design will allow us to map care relationships both within and between LTC facilities. We will focus on examining the intersecting policy, organizational and micro-politics of care in four provinces: British Columbia, Alberta, Ontario and Nova Scotia. Within each province we will study two facilities, and within each facility we will study two care constellations. We will choose constellations with the most different care relationships within each facility.\r\n\r\nThe central objectives of this research are as follows:\r\n\r\nObjective 1: Identify two facilities in each of 4 Canadian provinces (BC, AB, ON, NS) with promising relational approaches to LTC.\r\n\r\nObjective 2: Map how promising approaches to care relationships in LTC are organized and experienced.\r\n\r\nObjective 3: Explore transferability of promising relational care approaches in LTC across jurisdictions.\r\n\r\n","principal_investigator":"Dr. Tamara Daly, Dr. Ivy Bourgeault, Dr. Katie Aubrecht","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Emily McIntyre (emmc2@yorku.ca)","funder_name":null},{"id":6671,"title":"Mon plan (Université de Montréal (FR))","dmptemplate_id":43,"created_at":"2018-11-14 17:22:02 UTC","updated_at":"2018-11-14 17:22:02 UTC","slug":"mon-plan-universite-de-montreal-fr--59","organisation_id":32,"grant_number":null,"i