tage-template--2312","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Diane Lee","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":6758,"title":"Reducing pathogens and greenhouse gas emissions from swine manure using anaerobic digestion","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2018-11-30 16:23:56 UTC","updated_at":"2018-12-04 13:53:11 UTC","slug":"reducing-pathogens-and-greenhouse-gas-emissions-from-swine-manure-using-anaerobic-digestion","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"030364","identifier":"","description":"The pork industry is a major pillar of the agricultural sector, contributing $3 billion to the national economy and\r\nmaking Canada the fifth largest exporter of pork in the world. Pork production contributes about 9 % of total manure production in the Canadian livestock sector. Current practices for pork manure management are storage in solid form and/or land application. During storage and direct land application, manure undergoes natural degradation leading to the emission of greenhouse gases (GHGs) such as methane and nitrous oxide. Anaerobic digestion (AD) of pork manure will reduce pathogens, mitigate GHG emissions, and capture methane for use as heat and/or renewable energy. In Ontario AD has not been readily adopted by pork producers, due in part to technological challenges associated with the nitrogen-rich nature of swine manure. We propose co-digestion of swine manure with lignocellulosic biomass in a novel dry AD process with a plug-flow reactor design. The design will overcome technical barriers and increase feasibility of AD for swine manure management, with positive benefits for producers and the environment.","principal_investigator":"Brandon Gilroyed","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0002-6524-6840","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":6760,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2018-11-30