19-01-08 20:02:57 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2380","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"The purpose of this study is to examine local perspectives on food gentrification through a case study in Kitchener, Ontario.  This study aims to understand whether sustainable or alternative food narratives are contributing to processes of gentrification. This is guided by the following research questions: \r\n\r\nHow do low-income immigrant residents experience food gentrification in a rapidly changing urban centre? \r\na. How have changes in the local food environment affected individual adaptation strategies or behaviours in relation to food security? \r\nb. How might food gentrification impact individual and community health?\r\n c. What could urban agriculture projects do to address socio-spatial equity in their food work?\r\n\r\nhrough a series of surveys and interviews, this research will help to understand whether sustainable or alternative food narratives are contributing to processes of gentrification.  Participants will be asked to complete the Canadian Community Health Survey Household Food Security Survey Module to understand their food security status, as well as a short survey to collect their demographic characteristics.  To follow, more open-ended questions will be integrated to understand perspectives on food environment changes, attitudes toward urban food initiatives, food procurement behaviours, and other observations on community change.  The results of this study can help to bring awareness to the complexity of urban greening, and promote equity in sustainable food work.  Ultimately, this research can help to develop targeted social safeguards and policies aimed at improving equity and diversity in local food security work.","principal_investigator":"Vanessa Ong","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":6876,"title":"My plan (CEOS Template - Draft)","dmptemplate_id":22,"