"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":7152,"title":"My plan (University of British Columbia Generic Template)","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2019-03-08 21:28:42 UTC","updated_at":"2019-03-08 21:28:42 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-british-columbia-generic-template--452","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Eugene Barsky","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":7153,"title":"Methods for Assessment of Extreme Wave Conditions","dmptemplate_id":44,"created_at":"2019-03-08 23:27:01 UTC","updated_at":"2019-03-08 23:33:00 UTC","slug":"methods-for-assessment-of-extreme-wave-conditions","organisation_id":21,"grant_number":"","identifier":"P1501","description":"This research investigates methods for estimating extreme wave conditions in coastal waters with a focus on British Columbia.  We seek an accurate method to estimate the magnitude and spatial variation of extreme wave statistics.","principal_investigator":"Clayton Hiles","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0002-7407-2141","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":7154,"title":"Prevalence and Early Detection of Wooden Breast Syndrome and White Striation in Canadian Broilers","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2019-03-10 01:54:49 UTC","updated_at":"2019-07-19 23:20:26 UTC","slug":"prevalence-and-early-detection-of-wooden-breast-syndrome-and-white-striation-in-canadian-broilers","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"UofG2017-2922","identifier":"","description":"Recently, numerous reports have indicated a significant increase in the incidence of breast muscle myopathies in broiler chickens, including the so-called Wooden Breast Syndrome (WB), White Striation (WS), and Spaghetti Meat (SM). These myopathies cause loss of myofibers and fibrosis, leading to poor meat processability, economic losses at the processing plant, and negative customer perception. The prevalence of these myopathies has increased in many countries, with WB prevalence reaching 27-32% in the US, leading to an estimate $200M losses per year. \r\n\r\nNo data about the prevalence of WB, WS and SM in Canada have been published. Understanding how common these myopathies are in the Canadian poultry industry is important to assess their economic impact, and apply possible reparative measures. Therefore the first Objective of our research is to measure the frequency of such myopathies  in selected processing plants in Ontario.\r\n\r\nThe second Objective of our research is to understand how these myopathies affect meat quality, by assessing several physical parameters on the affected breast fillets (i.e., water holding capacity, toughness), which directly translate to organoleptic qualities that are experienced by the consumers when they cook their meat. This can help understand how affected meat can be used in further processed products, and better gauge the economic impact of such lesions. \r\n\r\nThe third Objective of our research involves investigation of new methods for rapid and accurate detection of WB, WS and SM at the processing line. Currently, identification of WB, WS, and SM relies on subjective visual and physical inspection performed by plant workers. Given the speed of meat processing at the plant, inspections are time-consuming and might result in decreased sensitivity in detecting myopathies. Therefore, we are working to develop non-invasive, in-line automated methods (such image analysis, spectrometry) to improve detection of these myopathies as fillets move along the processing belt. \r\n\r\nThe proposed research has the potential to significantly impact the Canadian poultry industry. WB, WS, and SM are recognized problems for the commercial poultry industry worldwide, including Canada. However, no published data report the impact of such myopathies in Canada or any Canadian Provinces. Secondly, collected data will offer the opportunity to evaluate risk factors associated with the prevalence and severity of these myopathies, resulting in practical recommendations to producers. Evaluation of different additives to improve the characteristics of WB- and WS-affected meat is another outcome of this research. Since part of this study involves lesion assessment in the context of other health parameters (from the processing plant), an additional benefit of this study is the preliminary evaluation of the impact of WB, WS, and SM on the welfare and health status of affected birds.","principal_investigator":"Leonardo  Susta and Shai Barbut","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Susta: lsusta@uoguelph.ca; Barbut: sbarbut@uoguelph.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":7155,"title":"NS Biomass Modelling","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-03-11 12:53:22 UTC","updated_at":"2019-03-11 12:56:02 UTC","slug":"ns-biomass-modelling","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Emily Mantin","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":7156,"title":"McGill Library testing plan one","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-03-11 13:36:57 UTC","updated_at":"2019-03-11 14:26:03 UTC","slug":"mcgill-library-testing-plan-one","organisation_id":13,"grant_number":"1234","identifier":"1234","description":"where I will put my data for .testing","principal_investigator":"Jeffry Archer","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"jeffry.archer@mcgill.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":7157,"title":"test (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-03-11 17:25:34 UTC","updated_at":"2019-03-11 17:50:18 UTC","slug":"test-portage-template--3","organisation_id":13,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"test","principal_investigator":"Andrea Miller-Nesbitt","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_conta