dentifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":7271,"title":"My plan (University of Manitoba )","dmptemplate_id":35,"created_at":"2019-03-27 16:48:36 UTC","updated_at":"2019-03-27 16:48:36 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-manitoba--31","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Emily Tufts","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":7272,"title":"Case 1: Periwinkle","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-03-27 19:42:47 UTC","updated_at":"2019-03-28 18:30:00 UTC","slug":"case-1-periwinkle","organisation_id":15,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"This research project is about marine wildlife tracking. ","principal_investigator":"Professor Periwinkle","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":7273,"title":"Professor Pinkerton DMP","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-03-28 13:08:09 UTC","updated_at":"2019-03-30 23:15:31 UTC","slug":"professor-pinkerton-dmp","organisation_id":15,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"This data management plan outlines how Professor Pinkerton should manage their collection of Excel and CSV spreadsheets. Data being collected covers a broad array of topics however focus is on Management Information Systems. Data is collected with the purposes of being used in future research and for personal interest with the aim to provide research data to other researchers. Most of the data are open-access. Non-open data can be accessed upon request on a case to case basis.","principal_investigator":"Lydia Hunsberger","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":7274,"title":"Creating language resources for Plains Cree","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2019-03-28 19:57:41 UTC","updated_at":"2019-03-28 20:04:36 UTC","slug":"creating-language-resources-for-plains-cree","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"All Indigenous languages of the Americas are vulnerable or endangered; children are no longer learning many of them, and some will disappear within the next generation. In this context, our project aims to design a prototype for a publicly accessible, annotated, web-based, textual corpus of Nêhiyawêwin (Plains Cree), a First Nations language belonging to the Algonquian language family and spoken in British Columbia, Alberta, Saskatchewan, and Montana. Nêhiyawêwin, also called the y-dialect of Cree, is the western-most dialect of a Cree dialect continuum that extends from the foothills of the Rockies through to the eastern seaboard. Nêhiyawêwin is estimated to have 50,000 speakers, and is considered to be one of the more robust First Nations languages of Canada, though the number of child learners is dropping precipitously. In this situation of extreme vulnerability, we aim to test algorithms for automatically tagging and analyzing Nêhiyawêwin texts by integrating two sets of computational tools, namely the Alberta Language Technology Tools (ALTLab Tools) developed at the University of Alberta and the Système d’Analyse de Texte par Ordinateur (SATO) developed at Université du Québec à Montréal (UQAM). This pilot project has six inter-related goals:ʼ\r\n1. Modularize computational tools that allow multiple representations of features;\r\n2. Based on already existing prototypes, further develop & test algorithms for part-of-speech tagging of Plains Cree texts;\r\n3. Develop a multi-purpose architecture (distributed across multiple sites) for virtual, publicly accessible, web-based, textual Plains Cree corpora;\r\n4. Conduct corpus-based & corpus-driven research on Plains Cree grammar;\r\n5. Create a cadre of researchers with intercultural competency in Aboriginal & Western intellectual traditions, and interdisciplinary expertise;\r\n6. Build capacity within stakeholder communities & academic institutions.","principal_investigator":"Rose-Marie Dechaine","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":7275,"title":"Plan de gestion des données du projet Chez-soi des aînés et services de soutien à domicile","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-03-28 23:20:40 UTC","updated_at":"2019-03-29 00:14:32 UTC","slug":"plan-de-gestion-des-donnees-du-projet-chez-soi-des-aines-et-services-de-soutien-a-domicile","organisation_id":29,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Avec le vieillissement de la population, les besoins de soutien auprès des personnes âgées augmentent et font pression sur le système de santé actuel. Les stratégies mises en place par le gouvernement provincial favorise le vieillissement à domicile tel que le met de l'avant la politique \"Vieillir et vivre ensemble – Chez soi, dans sa communauté, au Québec\". Face aux difficultés d'accès aux résidences privées pour les personnes âgées en perte d'autonomie et aux nombre de places toujours limités dans les CHSLD, les aînés en perte d'autonomie doivent ouvrir la porte de leur domicile à des intervenants de divers services de soutien à domicile. Dans ce contexte, les logiques organisationnelles de ces intervenants présentent un risque d'institutionnalisation du domicile qui met en négociations l'espace du chez-soi de l'aîné. L’objectif principal de cette recherche est de produire des connaissances qui permettront de mieux comprendre les interactions entre les services de soutien à domicile et le sentiment de se sentir chez-soi chez la personne âgée. Plus spécifiquement, le projet cherchera à recueillir des données pour décrire : 1. Comment l’espace du chez-soi est lié à l’espace public et semi-public environnant le domicile, compte tenu de la perte d’autonomie et du soutien reçu; 2. Comment l’espace du chez-soi est lié à la réorganisation du domicile, compte tenu de la perte d’autonomie et du soutien reçu; 3. Comment l’espace du chez-soi est lié aux relations établies avec les ressources d’aide à domicile; 4. Comment la continuité du chez-soi est anticipée dans l’hypothèse d’un point de rupture dans l’autonomie qui implique un déménagement.\r\n\r\nLes données seront recueillies par des entretiens en parcours commentés avec prise de photographies. Un parcours a lieu au domicile et un autre dans le quartier du participant. La troisième rencontre s'appuie sur la version imprimées des photos prises lors des parcours pour faire deux cartographies de l'espace du chez-soi.","principal_investigator":"Cynthia Lisée","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0003-3883-3676","data_contact":"514-441-7448 ; lisee.cynthia@gmail.com","funder_name":null},{"id":7276,"title":"Professor Pinkerton Data Management Plan","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-03-29 15:10:47 UTC","updated_at":"2019-03-29 15:13:59 UTC","slug":"professor-pinkerton-data-management-plan","organisation_id":15,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Robyn Nicholson","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":7277,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-03-29 19:04:32 UTC","updated_at":"2019-03-29 19:04:32 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2587","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Mitchell Jabalee","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":7278,"title":"Problem Solving Study 1","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-03-29 19:28:06 UTC","updated_at":"2019-03-29 19:29:06 UTC","slug":"problem-solving-study-1","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":"","identifier":"MST001","description":"Problem solving literature indicates that expert problem solvers follow a systematic approach to solving novel problems that has been honed through a combination of knowledge, skills, and experience.  Novice problem solvers often lack this systematic approach to problem solving, instead employing what some researchers have termed \"random search\".  It is the aim of this study to demonstrate that novice problem solvers are in fact not searching randomly.  Rather, it is hypothesized that novice problem solvers who do not have sufficient background knowledge and experience will focus on many of the more obvious features of the problem and will try to match them with the features identified during instruction.  This would imply that the search for the problem solution is not actually random, but is instead knowledge driven.","principal_investigator":"Michael Cooper-Stachowsky","principal_investigator_identifier":"mstachow","data_contact":"Michael Cooper-Stachowsky","funder_name":null},{"id":7279,"title":"Dr. Green","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-03-29 19:51:20 UTC","updated_at":"2019-03-29 19:51:51 UTC","slug":"dr-green--2","organisation_id":15,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"DMP for Dr. Green's interdisciplinary teams research.","principal_investigator":"Jack Schembri","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":7280,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-03-29 20:04:58 UTC","updated_at":"2019-03-29 20:04:58 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2590","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Colton Johnston","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":7281,"title":"Appropriate Use of Enterprise Social Media","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-03-31 15:49:34 UTC","updated_at":"2019-03-31 15:52:22 UTC","slug":"appropriate-use-of-enterprise-social-media","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"This research data management plan will support the collection and and analysis of data for my PhD dissertation.  I am looking at how appropriate use of enterprise social media is socially constructed.  I will 