C","updated_at":"2019-05-07 21:01:54 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2682","organisation_id":23,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":7434,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-05-08 03:17:39 UTC","updated_at":"2019-05-08 03:17:39 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2683","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":7435,"title":"Case Management","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-05-08 12:09:21 UTC","updated_at":"2019-05-08 12:33:33 UTC","slug":"case-management","organisation_id":15,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Case management in primary care for frequent users of healthcare services with chronic diseases and complex care needs: implementation and realist evaluations. \r\nMulti-case embedded study in Saskatchewan, Quebec, New Brunswick, Nova Scotia, and Newfoundland - 2 primary care clinics per province. This plan pertains to the Nova Scotia sites only. \r\n\r\nCase management (CM) is a collaborative approach used to assess, plan, facilitate, and coordinate care to meet individual/patient and family healthcare needs, through communication and available resources including all sectors of healthcare (such as community, primary, secondary, and tertiary care), as well as sectors outside of the health system (such as social services, housing, etc.) with the intent to improve individual and health system outcomes. \r\n\r\nThe overarching research goals are: 1) generate findings on the implementation of case management (CM) in primary care for individuals with chronic conditions and complex healthcare needs who frequently use healthcare services; and 2) implement evidence-based CM that will not only improve care experience and outcomes but will also reduce the use of healthcare services by these individuals and related costs. \r\n\r\nResearch Questions\r\n1) What are the facilitators and barriers of case management (CM) implementation in primary care clinics across Canada?\r\n2) What are the relationships between the actors, contextual factors, mechanisms, and outcomes of case management (CM)? \r\n3) What are the next steps towards scalability (expansion within similar contexts and extension to different contexts) across Canada? \r\n\r\nCase management will be led by a nurse or social worker 1 day a week in clinic. \r\n\r\nParticipants: Adults who are living with at least one chronic condition and have used the emergency department (ED) 4 times or more over a 12 month period and/or have visited their primary health clinic several times over a 12 month period and who score ≥ 17 on the Intermed self-administered (IMSA) questionnaire asking questions about physical and psychological health, will be included or a relative will participate as a representative of a patient, if the patient is unable, or will fill in as needed. Healthcare professionals who work at the primary care clinics where the research is taking place will also be included in the study. \r\n\r\nParticipants:\r\n2 cohorts of 30 patients and/or relatives each\r\n\r\n2 case managers\r\n\r\n2-4 clinic managers \r\n\r\n16 healthcare professionals - 8 per cohort\r\n\r\n\r\n","principal_investigator":"Fred Burge","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Alannah Delahunty-Pike, adpike@dal.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":7436,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-05-08 14:55:35 UTC","updated_at":"2019-05-08 14:55:35 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2685","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Meghan Landry","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":7437,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-05-08 16:36:18 UTC","updated_at":"2019-05-08 16:36:18 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2686","organisation_id":20,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Michael Nolta","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":7438,"title":"Visual Perspective in Memory for Events","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2019-05-08 16:56:08 UTC","updated_at":"2019-05-08 17:04:13 UTC","slug":"visual-perspective-in-memory-for-events","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":"RGPIN-2019-06080","identifier":"RES0043421","description":"This is a project on visual perspective in memories for events in human participants. It will investigate how visual perspective influences the formation and retrieval of memories for 360-degree videos of real-world events, using a cognitive neuroscience approach. Behavioural data will include subjective ratings, memory accuracy, narrative descriptions, and responses on standardised questionnaires.  Neuroimaging data will include structural and functional images from magnetic resonance imaging. ","principal_investigator":"Peggy St Jacques","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0935-4588","data_contact":"pstjacqu@ualberta.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":7439,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-05-08 18:38:05 UTC","updated_at":"2019-05-08 18:38:05 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2687","organisation_id":10,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Alexandra Loop","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":7440,"title":"My plan (Ontario Agri-Food Innovation Alliance Template)","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2019-05-08 19:04:20 UTC","updated_at":"2019-05-10 12:51:12 UTC","slug":"my-plan-ontario-agri-food-innovation-alliance-template--28","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"The purpose of this project is to better understand the differences in consumer opinion regarding genetically modified food products. It is important to understand the driving forces behind these opinions to allow for better communication about the topic and to address consumer concerns. \r\n\r\nThe primary objective of this research project is to evaluate the role of affect (aka emotions) in consumer perception and evaluation of the hypothetical product the Always Green Avocado. The secondary objective is to observe if specific information about the Always Green Avocado presented in four experimental information treatments triggers positive or negative affect in participants compared to a control group provided with the basic information only that is presented to all participants.\r\n\r\nThis projects attempts to answer the following research questions:\r\n-Are emotions, risk aversion, and ambiguity aversion important factors to consider when explaining Canadian consumers current benefit and risk perception of GM foods? \r\n-Does information about product benefits or the novel food approval process in Canada influence consumers emotional relationship to, and perception of, GM food?\r\n\r\nIt is necessary to collect data in order to test the above research questions. The data being collected to do so is consumer survey data. ","principal_investigator":"Andreas Boecker","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Andreas Boecker","funder_name":null},{"id":7441,"title":"Dissertation Plan","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-05-09 16:57:47 UTC","updated_at":"2019-05-09 17:00:40 UTC","slug":"dissertation-plan--3","organisation_id":33,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"A study of women's substantive representation in the Canadian House of Commons and Senate. The study uses publicly available data from LiPaD for a content analysis of Hansard, as well as independently generated interview data from Canadian parliamentarians.","principal_investigator":"Elizabeth McCallion","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":7442,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-05-09 17:04:48 UTC","updated_at":"2019-05-09 17:05:10 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2689","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Jacqueline Gillis","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":7443,"title":"Graduate Thesis Ethics","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-05-09 17:24:37 UTC","updated_at":"2019-05-09 17:29:36 UTC","slug":"graduate-thesis-ethics","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Kimberly Friesen","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":7444,"title":"My plan (University of British Columbia Generic Template)","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2019-05-09 17:26:42 UTC","updated_at":"2019-05-09 17:26:42 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-british-columbia-generic-template--475","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Nusrat Matin","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":7445,"title":"Sensorimotor Physiology Lab Test Plan","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2019-05-09 17:35:37 UTC","updated_at":"2019-05-09 17:36:53 UTC","slug":"sensorimotor-physiology-lab-test-plan","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"test plan","principal_investigator":"Liam Foulger","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":7446,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-05-09 17:53:14 UTC","updated_at":"2019-05-09 17:53:14 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2691","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Pasquale LaPorta","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":7447,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-05-09 18:07:51 UTC","updated_at":"2019-05-09 18:07:51 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2692","organisation_id":13,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Heidi Hoernig","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":7448,"title":"NS Biomass Modeling ","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-05-09 18:14:16 UTC","updated_at":"2019-05-09 18:14:48 UTC","slug":"ns-biomass-modeling","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Emily Mantin","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":7449,"title":"My plan (University of Guelph  (Alliance/Food from Thought) Template)","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2019-05-10 14:12:40 UTC","updated_at":"2019-05-10 14:12:40 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-guelph-alliance-food-from-thought-template","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Carol Perry","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":7450,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-05-10 15:33:42 UTC","updated_at":"2019-05-10 15:33:42 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2694","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Amy Minnikin","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":7451,"title":"CIMP205: Identifying habitats that influence body condition and fitness of adult female boreal caribou in the southern Northwest Territories","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-05-10 17:51:31 UTC","updated_at":"2019-07-12 20:21:55 UTC","slug":"cimp205-identifying-habitats-that-influence-body-condition-and-fitness-of-adult-female-boreal-caribou-in-the-southern-northwest-territories","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"CIMP205","identifier":"CIMP205","description":"This project aims to identify what nutritional and environmental factors (e.g. disturbance) contribute to variation in boreal caribou body condition, and provide guidance and tools to managers to identify and protect key areas that offer superior nutritional resources.  It includes (1) field sampling of forage quality and quantity in the major vegetation types in southern NT during summer 2019, (2) identifying collared cows with calves surviving to autumn, and sampling body fat of a subset of those caribou in autumn 2019 and 2020, and (3) vegetation site assessments and information-sharing with traditional knowledge holders.  Data analysis will include vegetation quality laboratory assays in winter 2019-20, analysis of caribou telemetry data to determine core use areas, and modeling to relate caribou body fat levels to vegetation types used the previous summer, and to the nutritional value of those habitats. This will result in tools and guides to help managers develop better landscape plans to help reduce cumulative impacts for caribou in the future.  Since body condition is closely linked to ungulate fitness across a large number of ungulate studies, we think this knowledge is important for managing cumulative impacts by ensuring that habitats with higher nutritional value are identified in range plans and other environmental assessment processes.  ","principal_investigator":"Allicia Kelly","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Allicia_Kelly@gov.nt.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":7452,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-05-10 20:06:22 UTC","updated_at":"2019-05-10 20:06:22 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2696","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":7454,"title":"Mon plan (Modèle Portage)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-05-13 18:44:28 UTC","updated_at":"2019-05-13 18:44:28 UTC","slug":"mon-plan-modele-portage--370","organisation_id":42,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Mélissa Marcil-Bédard","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":7455,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-05-13 20:12:30 UTC","updated_at":"2019-05-13 20:12:30 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2697","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Kim Jasken","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":7456,"title":"My plan (University of British Columbia Generic Template)","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2019-05-13 22:12:27 UTC","updated_at":"2019-05-13 22:12:27 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-british-columbia-generic-template--477","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Jeff Gardner","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":7457,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-05-13 22:13:42 UTC","updated_at":"2019-05-13 22:13:42 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2698","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Jeff Gardner","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":7458,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-05-13 22:14:53 UTC","updated_at":"2019-05-13 22:14:53 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2699","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Tamara Leys","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":7459,"title":"Manomin Research Project","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-05-14 14:16:49 UTC","updated_at":"2021-02-10 20:34:53 UTC","slug":"manomin-research-project","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"The Manomin Project is a multi-disciplinary community-engaged research imitative being led by Niisaachewan Anishinaabe Nation, Dr. Andrea Bradford (School of Engineering, University of Guelph), and Dr. Brittany Luby (College of Arts, University of Guelph) with a focus on restoring the Manomin spirit in the upper Winnipeg River drainage basin.\r\nThrough this partnership, we will analyze flow data, conduct Elder interviews about ancestral foodways and crop care, and determine whether indigenous foodstuffs could be revitalized in the district. By doing so, we will co-develop culturally-appropriate crop management techniques that respond to (and, mitigate) settler-imposed changes.\r\nMore than that, we hope that our research will stimulate agricultural expansion in northwestern Ontario while contributing to cultural revitalization, economic and food security in Anishinaabe communities, and scholarly discussions of interdisciplinary research.","principal_investigator":"Brittany Luby","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"brittany.luby@uoguelph.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":7460,"title":"My plan (University of Alberta Template)","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2019-05-14 15:01:33 UTC","updated_at":"2019-05-14 15:01:33 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-alberta-template--741","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Aliya Spigelman","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":7461,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-05-14 15:23:13 UTC","updated_at":"2019-05-14 15:23:13 