ersity-of-british-columbia-generic-template--507","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Elena Ostroumov","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":7775,"title":"My plan (University of Alberta Template)","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2019-08-08 22:06:42 UTC","updated_at":"2019-08-08 22:07:26 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-alberta-template--751","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":"","identifier":"1607699","description":"","principal_investigator":"Rani  Lorenzetti","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":7776,"title":"Molecular epidemiology of Streptococcus suis in Ontario nursery pigs","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2019-08-09 14:20:43 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-26 14:54:41 UTC","slug":"molecular-epidemiology-of-streptococcus-suis-in-ontario-nursery-pigs","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"030464","identifier":"","description":"Streptococcus suis-related diseases are among the most common infectious problems on Ontario swine farms, resulting in decreased performance, increased drug use, nursery mortality, and welfare concern. S. suis is a common bacterial inhabitant of the tonsils and nasal cavities of healthy pigs; however, it is unclear why some pigs become healthy carriers while others develop clinical disease. Over the last five years we have isolated several hundred S. suis isolates from various samples including nasal cavities, tonsil, blood, meninges as well as GI tract from pigs with clinical signs of infection and healthy pigs on Ontario swine farms. The isolates have been identified either as known serotypes or remained untypable, however, it is unclear whether the untypable isolates are a mutant of a known serotype or a new serotype. Therefore, we propose to use whole genome sequencing to determine the molecular characteristics (virulence-associated-factors, Multilocus-Sequence-Typing (MLST) groups, and antimicrobial resistance genes) of 400 S. suis isolates already recovered from Ontario nurseries. Further, the pig DNA will be screened for presence of polymorphisms associated with resistance to S. suis infection in pigs using a panel of 54,000 SNVs. ","principal_investigator":"Vahab Farzan","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":7777,"title":"My plan (University of Guelph Agri-Food Funding Template (Alliance/Food from Thought) )","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2019-08-09 16:25:00 UTC","updated_at":"2019-08-09 16:37:10 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-guelph-agri-food-funding-template-alliance-food-from-thought--40","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"030468","identifier":"UofG2018-3148","description":"This project aims at determining the body weight and composition thresholds responsible for initiating sexual maturation in two strains of layers reared under different environments mimicking industry practices. As such,  2 successive experiments will be conducted with the first aiming at Identifying the body weight and body composition thresholds and characterizing the metabolic signals responsible, while the second will focus on  determining whether different rearing environments affect the metabolic threshold required to activate the reproductive axis in pullets.\r\n","principal_investigator":"Gregoy Bedecarats","principal_investigator_identifier":"UoG ID# 300015341","data_contact":"Phone: 519 824 4120 Ext. 53692; Email: gbedecar@uoguelph.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":7778,"title":"Promoting Soil Health Knowledge Exchange Between Researchers, Producers and Consumers","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-08-09 17:07:18 UTC","updated_at":"2019-08-09 17:13:14 UTC","slug":"promoting-soil-health-knowledge-exchange-between-researchers-producers-and-consumers","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"10377","identifier":"","description":"This is a knowledge mobilization initiative promoting sustainable soil managem