n Research","principal_investigator":"Linda Melnick","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8032,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-09-25 07:35:46 UTC","updated_at":"2019-09-25 07:35:46 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2995","organisation_id":14,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Katerina Kwon","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8033,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-09-25 15:58:06 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-25 15:45:52 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--2996","organisation_id":10,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"It`s good if you can summarize the main idea of your research! ","principal_investigator":"Sean Sears","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8034,"title":"My plan (University of Guelph Agri-Food Funding Template (Alliance/Food from Thought) )","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2019-09-25 16:21:33 UTC","updated_at":"2019-09-25 16:29:19 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-guelph-agri-food-funding-template-alliance-food-from-thought--83","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"","identifier":"UofG2018-3254","description":"We are investigating the forms and mobility of organic and inorganic phosphorus from the edge of farmed fields to surface water through vegetated buffer strips and riverine buffer strips during soil freeze-thaw and wet-dry cycles. The research will provide information about seasonal impacts on release of phosphorus derived from agricultural fields that has the potential to cause pulses of P in receiving waters.\r\nThe data is being collected to guide producers, through conservation authorities, on implementation of buffer strips between field edges and waterways.","principal_investigator":"Susan Glasauer","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8035,"title":"Diet Culture in the Digital Age","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2019-09-25 17:34:27 UTC","updated_at":"2019-09-25 17:35:36 UTC","slug":"diet-culture-in-the-digital-age","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Emily Villanueva","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8036,"title":"My plan (University of Alberta Template)","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2019-09-25 17:36:10 UTC","updated_at":"2019-09-25 17:36:10 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-alberta-template--766","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Kayla Reddecliff","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8037,"title":"Indians in the Database","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-09-25 17:39:00 UTC","updated_at":"2019-09-25 17:42:54 UTC","slug":"indians-in-the-database","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"The goal of this research study is to examine how students in the Faculty of Native Studies at the University of Alberta feel about outdated terms for Indigenous peoples, namely “Indian”, in controlled vocabulary subject headings. Controlled vocabulary subject headings are used in libraries to ensure library materials are described in the same way across different libraries and different cataloguers. However, the language used in controlled vocabularies to describe library material about Indigenous peoples does not reflect terms Indigenous peoples use to describe themselves, leading to a disconnect between Indigenous ways of knowing and the library. In this exploratory research study, which is grounded in an Indigenous research methodology, I will conduct interviews to determine how students in the Faculty of Native studies relate to language in controlled vocabulary subject headings.","principal_investigator":"Christian Isbister","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8038,"title":"IMHR Cannabis","dmptemplate_id":33,"created_at":"2019-09-25 19:06:11 UTC","updated_at":"2019-09-25 19:07:40 UTC","slug":"imhr-cannabis","organisation_id":39,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Rebecca Robillard","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Daniel Brabant","funder_name":null},{"id":8039,"title":"A synthesis of benefits and challenges of adopting cover crops in a temperate humid climate","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2019-09-25 20:45:27 UTC","updated_at":"2020-05-08 19:12:46 UTC","slug":"a-synthesis-of-benefits-and-challenges-of-adopting-cover-crops-in-a-temperate-humid-climate","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"030506","identifier":"UG-SI-2019-100071","description":"Inclusion of cover crops in cropping systems over the long-term has\r\nenhanced soil health, agroecosystem resiliency, and sustainability. Despite\r\nthe numerous ecosystem services provided by cover crops, cover crop\r\nusage has not increased tremendously in Ontario. Several barriers prohibit\r\nthe cover crop adoption. Thus, there is a need to identify the most common\r\nbarriers to successfully integrate cover crops. The proposed synthesis\r\nresearch project will provide through evidence valuable information by\r\nidentifying (i) the major barriers limiting cover crop usage to inform\r\nOMAFRA and partner KTT efforts on cover crops that better addresses\r\nbarriers to adoption based on current knowledge and (ii) prioritize the cover\r\ncrop research gaps in Ontario in order to accelerate development of\r\nsolutions to reduce barriers to adoption.","principal_investigator":"Laura L. Van Eerd","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0001-9789-4685","data_contact":"Laura L. Van Eerd","funder_name":null},{"id":8040,"title":"My plan (University of Alberta Template)","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2019-09-25 21:54:26 U