10-22 18:15:03 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-22 18:15:18 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3092","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Look a plan","principal_investigator":"Rebecca Power","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8215,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-10-22 18:22:23 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-22 18:23:20 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3093","organisation_id":27,"grant_number":"","identifier":"SamplePLanWorkshop","description":"Sample dmp for workshops","principal_investigator":"Elizabeth Hill","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"x85049, ethill@uwo.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":8216,"title":"My Plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-10-22 18:32:24 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-22 18:34:26 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3094","organisation_id":27,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Gabrielle Lee","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8217,"title":"Mon plan (Modèle Portage)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-10-22 18:40:56 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-22 18:40:56 UTC","slug":"mon-plan-modele-portage--428","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Guillaume Chicoisne","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8218,"title":"Protein quality of black solider fly larvae using in vivo and in vitro techniques (University of Guelph Agri-Food Funding Template (Alliance/Food from Thought) )","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2019-10-22 19:29:38 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-24 06:51:04 UTC","slug":"protein-quality-of-black-solider-fly-larvae-using-in-vivo-and-in-vitro-techniques-university-of-guelph-agri-food-funding-template-alliance-food-from-thought","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"To successfully introduce a novel ingredient into the agricultural feed industry, characterization of the ingredient nutrient profile is required. However, nutrient content in the raw ingredient does not reflect the capacity of the animal to digest and absorbed the nutrients in it. This capability is called digestibility and is required to be tested in vivo. Moreover, amino acids (protein building units) are not absorbed beyond the small intestine, and ileal digestibility is more precise than total tract digestibility for estimating availability of nutrients to the animals. To determine ileal digestibility in the pigs, animals are surgically modified to collect digesta at the end of the small intestine for calculation of ileal digestibility. Ileal digestibility is considered the most practical and precise method for determining bioavailability of nutrients. However, nutrients that are absorbed in a form that cannot be used by the animal results in overestimation of bioavailability. The indicator amino acid oxidation (IAAO) technique can be used to estimate bioavailability of amino acids at the tissue level, and thus, IAAO can detect decreased bioavailability of nutrients. Alternatively, the in vitro TIM-1 system has been developed to mimic digestion process in the stomach and small intestine. In contrast to conventional in vitro digestibility, TIM-1 can accurately maintain temperature, pH, and mimic digesta flow and absorption of nutrients. The TIM-1 is therefore a dynamic model of digestion that, if proven successful, could reduce utilization of experimental animals for determination of digestibility. \r\nMeasure of digestibility and bioavailability are important to ultimately determine protein quality. Protein quality is defined as the capacity of a protein to meet the individual (human) or animal requirements and considering digestion, absorption and utilization of nutrients. A more conventional and practical method for determining protein quality of ingredients is the Protein Efficiency Ratio method (PER) in which protein consumption is compared to the average daily body weight gain of chickens or egg mass and compared to a protein that is considered of 100% quality (e.g. casein). These 4 methodologies (ileal digestibility, IAAO, TIM-1, and chicken PER) for determining protein quality will be compared, which will help to unify regulatory measures for determining protein quality of ingredients across Canada for use in animal and human diets. \r\n","principal_investigator":"Anna Kate Shoveller","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"ashovell@uoguelph.ca; 519.820.4342","funder_name":null},{"id":8219,"title":"Zooarch Data Mgmt Test","dmptemplate_id":44,"created_at":"2019-10-22 19:35:18 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-24 19:53:36 UTC","slug":"zooarch-data-mgmt-test","organisation_id":21,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Kathryn McKenzie","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8220,"title":"Accelerator survey","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-10-22 19:36:35 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-22 19:49:29 UTC","slug":"accelerator-survey","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"1","identifier":"1","description":"Survey for feedback in considering changes to BrainsCAN's Accelerator Internal Grant Program","principal_investigator":"Fay Harrison","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Ryan Salewski","funder_name":null},{"id":8221,"title":"My plan (University of British Columbia Generic Template)","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2019-10-22 20:14:03 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-22 20:14:03 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-british-columbia-generic-template--520","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Paul Pavlidis","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8222,"title":"UVic archaeology field school ","dmptemplate_id":44,"created_at":"2019-10-22 20:16:16 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-22 20:16:56 UTC","slug":"uvic-archaeology-field-school","organisation_id":21,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Iain McKechnie","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8223,"title":"The development of novel biomarkers for stress, boar taint and reproductive performance of pigs","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2019-10-22 20:37:59 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-22 20:40:14 UTC","slug":"the-development-of-novel-biomarkers-for-stress-boar-taint-and-reproductive-performance-of-pigs","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"499091","identifier":"","description":"Animals on farms are typically managed in groups where performance of the group as a whole is monitored and interventions related to housing, feeding, and management are applied to the group as a whole. Group management uses the average animal as its target, leaving above- and below-average animals at a suboptimal level of nutrition and wellness, and sub-optimally capturing dietary nutrients that otherwise may contaminate air, water, and soil. This variation between animals also results in a wide variability in response to treatments that are designed to address problems in animal production systems. Being able to automatically assess aspects of individual animal performance, behaviour, and metabolism has created an opportunity to tailor management (housing and nutrition) interventions to individual animals. In order to achieve this goal, we need to have a suite of biomarkers that reflect the differences in these parameters among individuals within a group. In this proposal, we will develop and validate behavioural biomarkers for stress, genetic biomarkers for boar taint and examine the metabolite profiles of urine and saliva to identify metabolic biomarkers for reproductive efficiency. Our results will inform genetic selection of animals that are better adapted to their environment and help improve housing, nutrition and management practices that will promote optimal production and welfare.","principal_investigator":"Renee Bergeron","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0001-7757-2531","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8224,"title":"My plan (University of Guelph Agri-Food Funding Template (Alliance/Food from Thought) )","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2019-10-22 23:19:54 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-22 23:27:07 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-guelph-agri-food-funding-template-alliance-food-from-thought--101","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"499089","identifier":"302","description":"This research project is focused on addressing the role that management zones play in precision agriculture. We will explore how remote sensing and soil mapping can improve the return on investment from using variable rate fertilizer, fungicide, and yield mapping. This will lead to improved understanding of the value of precision agriculture as well as improving the results of currently adopted practices. \r\n\r\nMost importantly, plant–soil–weather interactions are not emphasized enough for nitrogen fertilizer applications in corn. There are several approaches for estimating corn nitrogen requirements such as the yield goal system and the maximum return to nitrogen recommendation system. However, both of these approaches can’t account for spatial and/or temporal variation in nitrogen response. ","principal_investigator":"John Sulik","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0003-4637-0886","data_contact":"jsulik@uoguelph.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":8225,"title":"My plan (University of British Columbia Generic Template)","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2019-10-22 23:48:29 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-22 23:48:29 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-british-columbia-generic-template--521","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Stephen MacDonald","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8226,"title":"LTS Network","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-10-23 00:34:32 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-23 00:37:45 UTC","slug":"lts-network","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"One of the projects I am working on includes developing a level of traffic stress network to assess cycling behaviour throughout the City of Hamilton - the idea is to track the movement of SoBi bikes and begin to draw patterns from what links cyclists commonly avoid and how infrastructure at those links can be improved to increase ridership and create a more connected network. ","principal_investigator":"Raj  Ubhi","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8227,"title":"My plan (York University)","dmptemplate_id":47,"created_at":"2019-10-23 14:58:47 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-23 14:58:47 UTC","slug":"my-plan-york-university--23","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8228,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-10-23 14:59:57 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-23 14:59:57 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3096","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8229,"title":"Promise","dmptemplate_id":47,"created_at":"2019-10-23 15:33:23 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-23 15:34:20 UTC","slug":"promise","organisation_id":45,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Franck van Breugel","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8230,"title":"Spatial Stochastic Bioeconomic Modeling of Crop Climate Resilience in Ontario","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2019-10-23 15:44:32 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-23 15:52:38 UTC","slug":"spatial-stochastic-bioeconomic-modeling-of-crop-climate-resilience-in-ontario","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"030330","identifier":"UofG2017-2868","description":"The purpose of this project is to develop, test and apply a spatial, stochastic economic modeling framework that can be used to study ways of improving water use efficiency. The model will be used to study future water use in crop production in Ontario under alternative projected precipitation and temperature conditions. The model projects crop yields for corn, soybeans, winter wheat and hay for 29 counties in southern Ontario for the period from 2020 to 2070. Projections of future irrigation and drainage use for corn production are modeled as contingent on future precipitation and temperature conditions.","principal_investigator":"Glenn Fox","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Lauren Sirrs, (289) 927-5131, lsirrs@uoguelph.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":8231,"title":"Mon plan (UVic DMP Template)","dmptemplate_id":44,"created_at":"2019-10-23 17:04:44 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-23 17:04:44 UTC","slug":"mon-plan-uvic-dmp-template","organisation_id":21,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Patrick Duke","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8232,"title":"Enhancement of Crop Stress Tolerance to Weeds and Cover Crops ","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2019-10-23 17:27:30 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-29 14:18:48 UTC","slug":"enhancement-of-crop-stress-tolerance-to-weeds-and-cover-crops","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"499113","identifier":"","description":" \r\n Plant competition has been viewed traditionally as the negative effects which one plant has on another by being more successful at consuming or controlling access to resources such as light water and nutrients. Resource limitation is important, however, other non-limiting resource mechanisms such as light signalling plays an important role in plant competition. Previous research suggests that plant competition is not driven initially by limiting resources, but rather by molecular, and physiological changes that occur in response to the detection of the Red to Far Red ratio reflected from neighbouring weeds or cover crops.  These changes may pre-condition the crop plant to be more susceptible to subsequent stresses such as limiting resources.  In order to advance our knowledge of plant competition, experiments will designed to test several novel hypotheses involving the effect of the Red to Far Red ratio reflected from both above ground neighbouring weeds/cover crop and a non-biological Far Red filter on the molecular and physiological changes that occur in maize, soybean and Arabidopsis plants. This research will transform our understanding of plant competition and provide new knowledge which may prove useful in breeding programs designed to enhance crop stress tolerance to the presence of neighbouring weeds or cover crops.","principal_investigator":"Clarence Swanton","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000000267225410","data_contact":"Clarence Swanton","funder_name":null},{"id":8233,"title":"Mon plan (Modèle Portage)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-10-23 17:45:29 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-23 17:45:29 UTC","slug":"mon-plan-modele-portage--430","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Perez Bayard","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8234,"title":"Expanding the Value of Soil Health and Soil Ecosystem Services Research through Development of an Integrated Data Sharing Platform","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2019-10-23 18:33:51 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-23 19:34:18 UTC","slug":"expanding-the-value-of-soil-health-and-soil-ecosystem-services-research-through-development-of-an-integrated-data-sharing-platform","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Non-diversified crop rotations such as long-term monoculture of annual crops, frequent tillage, and reliance on fertilizer applications can result in the decline of soil health, threatening the sustainability of food production systems. The implications of poor soil health on long-term agricultural production are of local, national and global concern because of the increase in future food and water demands. Soil health, defined as \"the capacity of soil to function\" is important to sustain crop productivity and the provision of soil ecosystem services such as greenhouse gas emission mitigation, support of microbial diversity, soil organic matter storage, and water filtration. The new soil lysimeter facility at the Soil Health Interpretive Center and associated long-term research projects Elora Research Station form a hub of multi-disciplinary research involving leading experts from several universities. The value of research findings from these initiatives can be expanded immensely if data is archived and preserved properly for future novel analysis of soil ecosystem services, but currently we do not have a dedicated data platform for sharing and data-mining. This project is creating a Soil Health and Soil Ecosystem Services data platform where shareable and archivable files will be made available for current and future use of the data by a multitude of users. This will maximize the scientific output of previous studies and contribute to soil ecosystem service analysis. The breadth of measured variables available to be included in the database will lead to novel analysis on the factors that enhance soil health and control soil ecosystem services in agro-ecosystems, further establishing the University of Guelph as a hub for agri-environmental research.","principal_investigator":"Claudia Wagner-Riddle","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Shannon Brown (sbrown06@uoguelph.ca)","funder_name":null},{"id":8235,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-10-23 18:40:58 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-23 18:40:58 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3097","organisation_id":38,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Tracey-Ann Stitchell","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8236,"title":"My plan (UVic DMP Template)","dmptemplate_id":44,"created_at":"2019-10-23 21:01:30 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-23 21:01:30 UTC","slug":"my-plan-uvic-dmp-template--52","organisation_id":21,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8237,"title":"Finlay Lab Data Management Plan","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2019-10-23 21:09:47 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-24 00:41:44 UTC","slug":"finlay-lab-data-management-plan","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"This data management plan provides an overview of all projects maintained in the Finlay Lab.","principal_investigator":"Brett Finlay","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8238,"title":"My plan (UVic DMP Template)","dmptemplate_id":44,"created_at":"2019-10-23 21:17:17 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-23 21:17:17 UTC","slug":"my-plan-uvic-dmp-template--53","organisation_id":21,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Liz Ramsey","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8239,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-10-23 21:35:30 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-23 21:35:30 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3098","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Kathleen  Matthews","principal_investigator_