","principal_investigator_identifier":"L. Airton and M. Searle","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8265,"title":"Livestock Visualization Project: Using Visual and Spectral Images to Determine Calf Growth and Performance","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2019-10-24 18:54:58 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-25 18:53:53 UTC","slug":"livestock-visualization-project-using-visual-and-spectral-images-to-determine-calf-growth-and-performance","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"499098","identifier":"","description":"Measuring the size of dairy calves is an important way of monitoring their growth and health. This research project will attempt to measure the width, height, length, and girth of dairy calves at important locations on the body. Colour and 3D images of the calves will be collected along with ground truth measurements (measured by humans) for comparison. The purpose is to develop a system that can measure calves more accurately, more frequently, and in a way that is less disruptive than human measurements.","principal_investigator":"Medhat Moussa","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8266,"title":"FFT Aquatic Ecosystems Data","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2019-10-24 19:02:35 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-26 13:18:50 UTC","slug":"fft-aquatic-ecosystems-data","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"302 014600 499075","identifier":"","description":"Collaborative research project studying the effects of agriculture on aquatic ecosystems. Numerous research questions are addressed, spanning from physiology of individual organisms, physical properties of environments, to whole community and ecosystem impacts. ","principal_investigator":"Kevin McCann ksmccann@uoguelph.ca","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Kevin McCann ksmccann@uoguelph.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":8267,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-10-24 20:02:46 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-24 20:02:46 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3113","organisation_id":14,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8268,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-10-24 20:26:43 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-24 20:26:43 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3114","organisation_id":12,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Brenna Santacroce","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8269,"title":"My plan (UVic DMP Template)","dmptemplate_id":44,"created_at":"2019-10-24 20:49:58 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-24 20:49:58 UTC","slug":"my-plan-uvic-dmp-template--56","organisation_id":21,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Shahira Khair","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8270,"title":"Pannexin 1 regulates cortical dendritic spine development","dmptemplate_id":44,"created_at":"2019-10-24 20:50:00 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-24 20:58:18 UTC","slug":"pannexin-1-regulates-cortical-dendritic-spine-development","organisation_id":21,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"An orthogonal approach to investigate the role of the channel-forming protein Pannexin 1 (Panx1) in the formation of excitatory synapses.","principal_investigator":"Juan C. Sanchez-Arias","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0002-8061-7128","data_contact":"juansa@uvic.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":8271,"title":"Expanding sour beer production in Ontario","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2019-10-25 13:18:59 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-25 13:39:03 UTC","slug":"expanding-sour-beer-production-in-ontario","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"LAAIR2018-5350","identifier":"LAAIR2018-5350","description":"The popularity of sour beers has grown exponentially during the last two years with >40% of Ontario microbreweries producing this beer. As a fruity, low-alcohol product with some acidity, it appeals to a larger consumer demographic than the commonly-produced ales/IPAs. Sour beer production is a multistage process involving lactic acid bacteria (LAB), wort temperature adjustments and yeast fermentation. Currently, Ontario\r\nbrewers use 3-4 predominant LAB strains and a limited selection of beer yeasts in production. Many breweries report problematic yeast fermentations when a specific LAB is used. Information regarding the optimal performance of the LAB, its relationship to yeast fermentation efficiency, optimized production conditions and the contributions of both LAB and yeast to the beer flavour profile is currently limiting. We offer 16 alternative LAB and 12 yeast strains in diversifying sour beer production with optimized production conditions. We will deliver information of optimized performance for each LAB in souring and flavour production, a selection of yeasts strains that can efficiently complete the fermentation and contribute to the fruity flavour profile of the beer. We already have a proven commercialization pipeline in place as Escarpment Laboratories is a major supplier of beer LAB and yeast to microbrewers in Ontario.","principal_investigator":"George van der Merwe","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0001-9662-0666","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8272,"title":"Mon plan (Modèle Portage)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-10-25 15:58:50 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-25 15:58:50 UTC","slug":"mon-plan-modele-portage--434","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Lou Richer","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8274,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-10-25 16:00:33 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-25 16:00:33 UTC","slug"