reated_at":"2019-10-29 18:48:38 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-29 18:48:38 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3127","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Clare Cheng","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8330,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-10-29 21:01:02 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-29 21:01:02 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3128","organisation_id":15,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Barry Joyce","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8331,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-10-29 21:21:57 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-29 21:21:57 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3129","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Andraya Watt","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8332,"title":"CHSC 7400 Assignment 1","dmptemplate_id":35,"created_at":"2019-10-29 21:34:48 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-29 21:35:13 UTC","slug":"chsc-7400-assignment-1","organisation_id":37,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Alexandrea Anderson","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8333,"title":"Developing Sustainable Pest Management Strategies for Brown Marmorated Stink Bug","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2019-10-29 23:29:29 UTC","updated_at":"2019-11-04 21:27:13 UTC","slug":"developing-sustainable-pest-management-strategies-for-brown-marmorated-stink-bug","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"UofG2017-2907","identifier":"","description":"Brown marmorated stink bug (BMSB), Halyomorpha halys Stål, is an invasive pest native to East Asia. First\r\nidentified in Pennsylvania in 2001, it has now been detected in 44 states and 3 provinces (Ontario, Quebec and\r\nBritish Columbia), and is of economic importance throughout the Mid-Atlantic US. There are more than 170\r\nNorth American plant hosts, including broad spectrum of important fruit (e.g., apples and grapes), vegetable and\r\nfield crops, as well as landscape trees and shrubs. All are important agricultural commodities in Ontario. BMSBsurvey programs we have established began in Ontario in 2013 and as of October, 2017 BMSB has been\r\ndetected in 19 counties. We have caught BMSB during our survey efforts in 2017 using pheromone traps in\r\nagricultural areas on or near farms (i.e., apples and grapes) at several locations. The presence of increasing\r\nnumbers of BMSB in close proximity to high risk agricultural crops continues to heighten grower concerns.\r\nEffective and novel management strategies need to be identified and surveys continued.The primary goal of this project is to identify sustainable management strategies for BMSB in crops immediately\r\nat risk in Ontario (i.e., apples, tender fruits and grapes) and continue to survey for presence of the invasive pest\r\nin at risk crops with grower cooperation:\r\nObjectives:\r\n1)Investigate sustainable management strategies for BMSB including:\r\ni)Chemical control (oral and contact toxicity, methods of delivering products insecticides (singly and in\r\ncombinations), attract and kill combinations, and ii) Genetic control - RNAi tactics;\r\n2)Development of diagnostic methods in fruits (apples, tender fruits and grapes) to improve our ability to identify\r\nBMSB damage in the field (differentiate from indigenous stink bug damage).\r\n3)Continue to survey for BMSB in at risk crops focusing on a program that involves growers being responsible\r\nfor operation of pheromone traps on their orchards/farms.","principal_investigator":"Cynthia Scott-Dupree","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8334,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-10-30 04:48:13 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-30 04:50:03 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3130","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":"","identifier":"2","description":"Using publicly available statistical data, we estimate that 700,000 businesses are at risk of closure due to owner retirements in the next 10 years nationally, with those in rural and northern communities particularly at risk. The Legacy Leadership Lab (L3) is designed for the business owner who wants to take on the challenge of selling their business in a new manner that leaves a legacy for their community – converting that business into a social enterprise. Our goals are: to identify barriers that business owners face during the transition process; to design social innovation and finance interventions to help overcome those barriers; and to build connections between all the actors in this spaces to allow people to learn from and support one another.","principal_investigator":"Sean Geobey","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Sean Campbell, 519.503.2246, sean.campbell@uwaterloo.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":8335,"title":"My plan (University of Manitoba )","dmptemplate_id":35,"created_at":"2019-10-30 14:19:12 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-30 14:19:12 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-manitoba--47","organisation_id":37,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8336,"title":"My plan (Memorial University of Newfoundland)","dmptemplate_id":20,"created_at":"2019-10-30 14:39:50 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-30 14:39:50 UTC","slug":"my-plan-memorial-university-of-newfoundland--28","organisation_id":16,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Javier Santander","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8337,"title":"My plan (University of Guelph Agri-Food Funding Template (Alliance/Food from Thought) )","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2019-10-30 15:19:43 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-30 15:30:14 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-guelph-agri-food-funding-template-alliance-food-from-thought--113","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"499118","identifier":"Food fot Thought 4251","description":"Bone health is a major production and welfare issue in modern hens and is influenced by many factors including housing, behavior, nutrition, and genetics. In cognizant of the multi-factorial nature of the bone\r\nhealth we propose a multi-disciplinary research approach involving aspects of physiology (Bedecarrats), nutrition\r\n(Kiarie) and behavior (Harlander & Widowski) with the overall objective of investigating the effects of genetic\r\nbackground of commercial hybrid strains on skeletal, behavioral and physiological development in pullets prior to and during sexual maturity. The research will generate foundational data for pullet growers to adjust nutrition and management programs to optimize skeletal development for enhanced hen productivity, skeletal health, livability,\r\nand welfare.","principal_investigator":"Gregoy Bedecarats","principal_investigator_identifier":"UoG ID# 300015341","data_contact":"Phone: 519 824 4120 Ext. 53692; Email: gbedecar@uoguelph.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":8338,"title":"Mon plan (Modèle Portage)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-10-30 17:40:32 UTC","updated_at":"2019-10-30 17:44:31 UTC","slug":"mon-plan-modele-portage--452","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"","identifier":"Cadastre souterrain","description":"Développement de principes de cartographie et modélisation 3D pour les données souterraines cadastrales.","principal_investigator":"Jacynthe Pouliot","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0001-7811-4129","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8339,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-10-31 00:54:19 UTC","updated_at":