tario-canada","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":"","identifier":"41489","description":"","principal_investigator":"Clare Cheng","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8412,"title":"Assembly for Multi-Spectral Optical Imaging of Large Format Soil and Rock Thin-Sections","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2019-11-12 21:52:40 UTC","updated_at":"2019-11-12 22:21:06 UTC","slug":"assembly-for-multi-spectral-optical-imaging-of-large-format-soil-and-rock-thin-sections","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"LAAIR2018-5357","identifier":"","description":"PUBLIC PROJECT OVERVIEW:\r\n1.The technology is a device for the acquisition of multispectral, digital imagery of soil and rock thin-sections at high resolution, without the need for polarizing microscopes\r\n2.Petrography of rock and micromorphology of soil samples are standard and useful methods of evaluating their structure and composition, but the procedures are hampered by the need to use expensive and tedious microscopy protocols that require the convolution of multiple images to generate data for a section in one set of light conditions\r\n3.We wish to evaluate the market potential for our device, as well as to discern market players who could potentially be partners for the commercialization of our solution.\r\n4.The knowledge gaps will be filled through the retention of a market analysis company that will generate a market assessment report enabling us to formulate our subsequent product development strategy and obtain LOIs from potential partners.\r\n5.The deliverables consist of a market assessment report, a product development strategy and LOIs from potential partners\r\n6.The next steps encompass the acquisition of R&D funds, negotiation of a sponsored research and/or licensing agreement with and identified partner who has expressed interest in the project, and then the co-development of production prototypes and further variants of the device.\r\n\r\nPROPOSED OUTPUTS OF INITIATIVE:\r\n- A market assessment report.\r\n- A short list of potential partners.\r\n- Letters of Interest (LOIs) from contacted industrial partners.\r\n- A product development strategy based on market assessment.\r\n- A final report summarising project achievements and the planned follow-up.\r\n","principal_investigator":"Richard J Heck","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0003-4613-439X","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8413,"title":"Quantifying Structural Stability of Agricultural Soils in Ontario","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2019-11-12 22:27:34 UTC","updated_at":"2019-11-12 22:31:12 UTC","slug":"quantifying-structural-stability-of-agricultural-soils-in-ontario","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"UofG2018-3285","identifier":"","description":"ABSTRACT:\r\nSurface and subsurface compaction, due to traffic, and surface crusting, due to rain-induced disaggregation, continue to be major problems facing Ontario agriculture. Structural degradation influences soil hydrophysical behavior, which reduces aeration, and root penetration, ultimately impacting crop performance. With the trend towards larger farms, more massive equipment and increasing unpredictability of climate, the risk of soil compaction increases. In response, many producers are considering track-based implements or remote tire deflation/re-inflation systems on their equipment. The impact of these systems, relative to soil texture, organic matter, and moisture status is still not well understood. High-resolution x-ray CT scanning will be used in this research, in conjunction with infield pressure sensors and soil penetrometers to better understand structural changes under compaction in Ontario soils. In the second component of this research, we will study soil crusting. It is well known that crusting occurs with reduced plant cover and low residue return or manure addition. It is not well understood how soil organic matter composition influences aggregate dispersion. We will use CT scanning, combined with characterization of aggregation stability and associated organic matter, to better understand the relative impact of conventional and alternative rotation and tillage systems on surface crusting in Ontario soils.\r\n\r\nOBJECTIVES:\r\n1) Further our understanding of topsoil and subsoil compaction in Ontario by low-pressure wheeled and tracked farm machinery, as influenced by texture, cropping history and moisture status.\r\n2) Further our understanding of the efficacy of cover crops for the decompaction of topsoil and subsoil in Ontario.\r\n3) Improve our understanding of surface crusting in agricultural soils of Ontario, under diverse management systems (rotations, tillage, cover crops and tree-based intercropping) in relation to soil organic matter and aggregate stability.","principal_investigator":"Richard Heck","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0003-4613-439X","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8414,"title":"CILLDI Stoney Dictionary Project","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2019-11-12 22:28:10 UTC","updated_at":"2019-11-26 22:44:50 UTC","slug":"cilldi-stoney-dictionary-project","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"We are seeking to create a robust language data storage solution for text and audio recordings of the endangered Stoney Nakoda language as spoken in Paul First Nation. This language data will be used to create online and paper-based learning tools for community members and other learners.","principal_investigator":"Jordan Lachler","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8415,"title":"My plan (University of British Columbia Generic Template)","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2019-11-13 02:01:58 UTC","updated_at":"2019-11-13 02:01:58 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-british-columbia-generic-template--535","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_inve