t & Cherie Westbrook","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8488,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-12-02 16:34:37 UTC","updated_at":"2019-12-02 17:34:41 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3210","organisation_id":23,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Tram Pham","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8489,"title":"Gathering in the Stories: A Papaschase Cree Project)","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2019-12-02 18:09:35 UTC","updated_at":"2019-12-02 18:12:13 UTC","slug":"gathering-in-the-stories-a-papaschase-cree-project","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"To support the work of the Papaschase Cree in gathering, recording, digitizing and archiving stories from Papaschase community members, as a pilot project to start an archive of the stories of the Papaschase Cree.  A gathering of Papaschase Cree First Nation elders took place in August 2019; this grant will support the gathering of 3-4 more stories as well as the digitizing and archiving of the stories collected to date. The stories and oral knowledge form a critical part of the work of the Papaschase First Nation Council; the CRAfT grant allows the Faculty of Arts Working Group on Indigenous Initiatives (AWGII) to support this vital work. ","principal_investigator":"Laura Beard","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8490,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-12-02 19:17:53 UTC","updated_at":"2019-12-02 19:17:53 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3211","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Barbara Neis","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8491,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-12-02 19:48:46 UTC","updated_at":"2019-12-02 19:48:46 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3212","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"rae.price@mail.utoronto.ca","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8492,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2019-12-02 20:45:37 UTC","updated_at":"2019-12-02 20:48:36 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3213","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"The Coppermine River, bordering the Hamlet of Kugluktuk, has historically supported a subsistence fishery for Arctic char. Since 2015, community members have reported a decrease in the number of char returning to the river following summer migration, and changes in fish appearance. Given these observed changes and the concerns of community members, a partnership was established in 2017 between the Kugluktuk Hunters and Trappers Organization (HTO), the University of Waterloo, and Fisheries and Oceans Canada (DFO) to study chars in the Coppermine River. As part of this project, researchers will evaluate the degree to which local descriptors correspond with variation measured using western scientific analyses. Western scientific data (i.e. genetics samples and photographs of fish for detailed shape and appearance analyses) were collected in summer 2018 and summer 2019. Participants in the Traditional Knowledge (TK) study will be interviewed in Kugluktuk beginning in January 2020 (at which point a workshop will be held) and during community visits and field research through December 2022.","principal_investigator":"Spencer Weinstein","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8493,"title":"My plan (University of Manitoba )","dmptemplate_id":35,"created_at":"2019-12-03 04:48:16 UTC","updated_at":"2019-12-03 04:48:16 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-manitoba--52","or