ull},{"id":8503,"title":"A Narrative Inquiry into the Experiences of Transitions into and out of Alberta Correctional Facilities for People Living with HIV","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2019-12-04 21:54:26 UTC","updated_at":"2019-12-04 22:00:51 UTC","slug":"a-narrative-inquiry-into-the-experiences-of-transitions-into-and-out-of-alberta-correctional-facilities-for-people-living-with-hiv","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"As a researcher-practitioner working within corrections in Canada, I am interested in the experiences of people who have faced significant health and social inequities. I acknowledge the value that narrative inquiry, as a relational methodology, brings when inquiring into the stories of incarcerated and previously incarcerated people who have faced marginalization. My research puzzle centers on the experiences of transitions for PLWH into and out of Alberta correctional facilities. Hoping to advance understandings of transition from a life-course perspective and provide insight into stories to live by, this project will recruit three to five PLWH who have experienced incarceration in Alberta. This study will be grounded in Dewey’s (1938) pragmatist theory, where the experiences and personal knowledge of PLWH as they transition into and out of correctional centers is vital. Transitions are conceptualized narratively – calling attention to the complexity of a life by attending to social context, time, and place. This project seeks to understand the experiences of transitions for PLWH and how this may affect health and social inequities, sense-making processes, and access to, and organization of, health and social care. I will approach the participants’ experiences from an inequity stance, hoping to imagine otherwise the identified barriers and injustices experienced by PLWH when transitioning into and out of Alberta correctional facilities.","principal_investigator":"Morgan Wadams","principal_investigator_identifi