ll},{"id":8639,"title":"My plan (University of Alberta Template)","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2020-01-04 04:15:40 UTC","updated_at":"2020-01-04 04:15:40 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-alberta-template--791","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Wenhui li","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8640,"title":"My plan (University of Alberta Template)","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2020-01-06 03:48:08 UTC","updated_at":"2020-01-06 03:48:08 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-alberta-template--792","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Matt Gallivan","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8641,"title":"SHICKLUNA SHIPYARD PROJECT","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-01-06 16:21:58 UTC","updated_at":"2020-01-06 16:25:20 UTC","slug":"shickluna-shipyard-project","organisation_id":55,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Dr. Kimberly Monk","principal_investigator_identifier":"Colleen Beard","data_contact":"Colleen Beard","funder_name":null},{"id":8642,"title":"Complex Shaped Designed Bioplastics and Biocomposites by 3D Printing for Engineering Applications","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-01-06 16:22:38 UTC","updated_at":"2020-01-06 16:27:14 UTC","slug":"complex-shaped-designed-bioplastics-and-biocomposites-by-3d-printing-for-engineering-applications","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"030485","identifier":"UofG2018-3125","description":"This project aims to utilize Ontario’s agro-residues, bioplastics, and recycled plastics to develop sustainable three-dimensional (3D) complex geometry products using filament/pellets/powder-based 3D printing for biomedical and automotive applications under the bioeconomy approach. This project is divided in two parts: (i) development of functional and custom-fitting prosthetics, orthoses, splints and dental appliances in biomedical applications using conventional virgin plastics/biobased plastics and nanocellulose (from agro-residues) with improved mechanical properties and lightweight; and (ii) development of sustainable products using virgin/recycled plastics and bio-sourced carbon (biocarbon) to reduce the cost with improved thermal and dimensional stability, that are critically required for automotive applications. This high-risk and highly rewarding project will be a breakthrough for new research prospects, discoveries and knowledge on the use of waste stream materials (agro-residues; plastic wastes) and bioplastics to design value added complex-shaped products (with sustainable content>50%), which are not feasible due to high cost when manufacturing the complexed shaped products by conventional techniques. 3D printing technology facilitates rapid prototyping with a broad window for design visualization and can be extended for industrial production and commercialization. This project will involve undergraduate and graduate students, summer interns and postdoctoral researchers to extend the insight knowledge on sustainable biocomposites in various applications.","principal_investigator":"Amar Mohanty","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8643,"title":"Biodegradable straws for single-use applications","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-01-06 16:54:20 UTC","updated_at":"2020-01-06 16:58:56 UTC","slug":"biodegradable-straws-for-single-use-applications","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"030486","identifier":"UofG2018-3210","description":"The main objective and novelty of this project is the development and marketing of biodegradable and/or compostable biobased plastics targeted to substitute polymers (polypropylene and polyethylene) currently used in the manufacture of food contact straws. The overall aim is to develop a platform for material formulations to be used in the production of disposable and/or common single-use items including cutlery, food containers, and other small packaging formats. Another novelty of this project is the production of quality natural fiber for food contact uses, which will be derived from crops available in Ontario such as wheat, corn, soy, grape and apple pomace, etc. These fillers will be used to improve performance and reduce production costs making it competitive with current synthetic food grade counterparts.\r\n\r\nEvery single day, Canada alone consumes about 57 million straws, and this number may be over 500 million in the US. Because of the non-biodegradability and ease of leak into the diverse ecosystems, the global trend is to phase out plastic straws and other similar environmentally harmful disposable products. This project proposes an alternative solution to the current non-biodegradable straws, supporting product innovation, new market opportunities for Ontario companies and better environmental solutions.","principal_investigator":"Manjusri Misra","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8644,"title":"Mon plan (Modèle Portage)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-01-06 20:16:57 UTC","updated_at":"2020-01-06 20:16:57 UTC","slug":"mon-plan-modele-portage--465","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Céline Desjardins","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8645,"title":"Sample plan to test template steps","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-01-07 03:55:40 UTC","updated_at":"2020-01-07 03:58:15 UTC","slug":"sample-plan-to-test-template-steps","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"","identifier":"12345","description":"Abstract of study here. ","principal_investigator":"Erin Clary","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0003-2703-8458","data_contact":"erin.clary@carl-abrc.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":8646,"title":"MUN RDM Survey 