ance/Food from Thought) )","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-01-29 15:09:00 UTC","updated_at":"2020-01-29 15:09:00 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-guelph-agri-food-funding-template-alliance-food-from-thought--127","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Carol Perry","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8734,"title":"A Mixed Methods Study Exploring the Meaning, Value, and Use of Patient-reported Data for Personal Health Records within a Primary Care Network in Rural BC ","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-01-29 17:48:09 UTC","updated_at":"2020-01-29 17:52:31 UTC","slug":"a-mixed-methods-study-exploring-the-meaning-value-and-use-of-patient-reported-data-for-personal-health-records-within-a-primary-care-network-in-rural-bc","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"The purpose of the study is to understand the meaning, value and use of patient-reported data for both patients and providers using an integrated personal health record (PHR) within a primary care network in Kootenay Boundary region of BC (eg. Nelson, BC). The study will use a mixed methods design and will include two phases: Phase 1 will involve soliciting patient and provider feedback on preferred features of the PHR. Phase 2 will involve integrating the PHR into a group of primary care network practices in that region. Both phases will combine qualitative (patient and provider focus groups) and quantitative (patient and provider surveys) components.","principal_investigator":"Kathy Rush","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":8735,"title":"Antimicrobial Resistance One Health Consortium: Prevention of Transmission, Innovation and Commercialization ","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2020-01-29 18:27:35 UTC","updated_at":"2020-01-30 18:50:16 UTC","slug":"antimicrobial-resistance-one-health-consortium-prevention-of-transmission-innovation-and-commercialization","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"This project is titled: Reducing Antimicrobial Units by selecting for animals more resilient to infectious disease. This topic is of impotance as in the age of antimicrobial resisitnace, resilient animals require less antimicrobial treatment, and are considered advantgeous in the efforts amde to decrease the use of antimicrobials in livestock production. Therein increasing the amount of resilient  animals in a system through breeding can help increase sustainability in the livestock industry. What: increasing the breeding potential of these resilient animals can limit the antimicrobial imprint while still keeping up with food demands in livestock animals. We intend to find ways to predict resilience, apply the phenotypes associated with resilience to breeding, and improve management of susceptible animals. Through the use of a porcine disease challenge model and bovine respiratory disease study, we will use omics data to learn how to identify resilient and susceptible animals and provide innovative technology and approaches to the industry. ","principal_investigator":"Janelle Jiminez","principal_investigator_identifier":"Graham Plastow","data_contact":"G. Plastow, (780) 492-1496, plastow@ualberta.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":8736,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-01-29 23:40:53 UTC","updated_at":"2020-01-29 23:40:53 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3346","organisation_id":23,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Cynthia Samphire","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":8737,"title":"SSHRC IG 2020","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2020-01-30 18:14:54 UTC","updated_at":"2020-06-15 19:14:08 UTC","slug":"sshrc-ig-2020","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"SSHRC IG 2020 summative assessm