e Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-05-28 00:10:28 UTC","updated_at":"2020-05-28 00:10:28 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3579","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Ryan Tennant","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9190,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-05-28 02:51:56 UTC","updated_at":"2020-05-28 02:51:56 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3580","organisation_id":13,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Claire Honda","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9191,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-05-28 14:34:07 UTC","updated_at":"2020-05-28 14:34:07 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3581","organisation_id":26,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9192,"title":"Farmland Values and Farmland Rents Data for Ontario","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-05-28 17:48:45 UTC","updated_at":"2020-06-04 21:07:23 UTC","slug":"farmland-values-and-farmland-rents-data-for-ontario","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"UG-SI-2019-100042","identifier":"","description":"The Ontario Farmland Value and Rental Value Survey generates public information about farmland values and rental rates for Ontario at the Census Division level. This survey is administered through an anonymous online survey form, which is distributed by OFA via email to their membership.","principal_investigator":"Brady Deaton","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0003-3041-9382","data_contact":"Brady Deaton, 519-824-4120 x 52765, bdeaton@uoguelph.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9193,"title":"Mon plan (Modèle Portage)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-05-28 18:25:23 UTC","updated_at":"2020-05-28 18:25:23 UTC","slug":"mon-plan-modele-portage--533","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Natalia Poliakova","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9194,"title":"Evaluation and potential augmentation of bovine fertility using small non-coding RNAs","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-05-28 20:18:36 UTC","updated_at":"2020-05-29 16:18:15 UTC","slug":"evaluation-and-potential-augmentation-of-bovine-fertility-using-small-non-coding-rnas","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"","identifier":"UG-T1-2020-100265","description":"The efficient generation of high quality offspring with optimal traits is essential to success in modern dairy and beef farming systems. This process relies on the fertility of both the dam and sire, which can be compromised in high quality animals whose genetics have been selected to favour production over reproductive success. There is growing awareness that reproductive parameters are indispensable components of the selection process for sire and and dam breeding combinations. Unfortunately, other than well-established criteria for gamete selection for AI and ET, there are few strategies utilizing molecular genetic characteristics of gametes to optimize reproductive success. In collaboration with Semex, we have recently identified small RNA genetic \"markers\" that may reflect the reproductive potential of male and female gametes. Here, we aim to determine whether these RNAs can be reliably employed to identify optimally fertile animals for breeding and to augment fertility in high quality sub-fertile animals.","principal_investigator":"Jonathan LaMarre","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"jlamarre@ovc.uoguelph.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9195,"title":"Predictors of mobile Health application (mHealth app) use in middle aged and older adults with vascular burden. ","dmptemplate_id":44,"created_at":"2020-05-28 22:07:48 UTC","updated_at":"2020-05-29 15:39:38 UTC","slug":"predictors-of-mobile-health-application-mhealth-app-use-in-middle-aged-and-older-adults-with-vascular-burden","organisation_id":21,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Research confirms the negative impact of modifiable vascular risk on cognitive status. Hypertension, diabetes mellitus, and hypercholesterolemia all increase in prevalence with age, and have been shown to confer risk of progression to vascular and Alzheimer’s disease related cognitive impairments. Mobile health applications (mHealth apps) targeting medication, dietary, and physical activity management have the potential to aid individuals in managing vascular risk for cognitive decline, mitigating future risk of cognitive, and other related morbidity (e.g. stroke) and mortality.\r\n\r\nMy goal is to improve understanding of how middle aged and older adults with vascular burden utilize diet, fitness, and medication management mHealth apps available to Canadians. Increasing understanding of how individuals interact with these now nearly ubiquitous technologies has the potential for measurable impact on future improvements to mobile interventions, in turn improving Canadians’ management of vascular burden. \r\n\r\nMy primary aim is to determine use rates of mHealth apps among Canadians with vascular burden, with the secondary aim of preliminarily examining relationships between individual, psychosocial, and app-related factors that may, together, simultaneously impact use/success of use of these apps. To meet my primary aim, I plan to conduct a national online survey of Canadian adults assessing app use, and collecting demographic and health information. My secondary aim is to collect pilot data to inform a statistical model examining simultaneous relationships between individual, psychosocial, and app-related variables that impact adoption, continuity, and perceived success using mHealth apps. Achieving these two aims will strengthen my application for a CIHR Project Grant in Fall 2020.\r\n","principal_investigator":"Theone Paterson","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0002-5876-1991","data_contact":"416-274-9426; tpaterson@uvic.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9196,"title":"My plan (UVic DMP Template)","dmptemplate_id":44,"created_at":"2020-05-28 22:08:25 UTC","updated_at":"2020-05-28 22:08:25 UTC","slug":"my-plan-uvic-dmp-template--83","organisation_id":21,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Shahira Khair","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9197,"title":"NILLA DMP","dmptemplate_id":44,"created_at":"2020-05-28 22:08:50 UTC","updated_at":"2020-05-28 22:10:15 UTC","slug":"nilla-dmp","organisation_id":21,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"NILLA","principal_investigator":"Onowa McIvor","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Barbara Jenni - netolnew@uvic.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9198,"title":"Transitions DMP","dmptemplate_id":44,"created_at":"2020-05-28 22:10:30 UTC","updated_at":"2020-05-28 22:41:57 UTC","slug":"transitions-dmp","organisation_id":21,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"This is the DMP for the Transitions from College study. Data for this study was collected at Washington University in St. Louis from April 2014 to January 2019. We recruited students from several cohorts of graduating college seniors to assess how their personality and social networks changed as they transition from college to life in \"the real world.\"","principal_investigator":"Kelci Harris","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9199,"title":"Understanding and supporting the social connections and digital connectivity of older Canadians during and after the COVID-19 pandemic","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-05-29 13:28:17 UTC","updated_at":"202