ejimkujik National Park Chain Pickerel Project","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-06-19 01:21:54 UTC","updated_at":"2020-06-19 01:23:34 UTC","slug":"kejimkujik-national-park-chain-pickerel-project","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Darrin Reid","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Brandon Nilsen, (902) 456-2417, brandonnilsen@acadiau.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9318,"title":"An integrated strategy for the control of linuron resistant pigweed species in carrots","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-06-19 14:27:38 UTC","updated_at":"2020-06-19 14:58:44 UTC","slug":"an-integrated-strategy-for-the-control-of-linuron-resistant-pigweed-species-in-carrots","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"2018-27352","identifier":"","description":"Integrated weed management for vegetable crops grown on high organic soils (> 70% organic matter) is critical in order to protect plant health and optimize yield. Linuron resistant pigweed species (Amaranthus retroflexus and Amaranthus powellii) have been identified on more than 8000 hectares in Ontario. The inability of linuron to control annual pigweed species is a serious threat to successful carrot production. The results of this study identified new herbicides and application timings that provided excellent control of linuron resistant pigweed species as well as demonstrating excellent crop selectivity. . The identification and registration of these new herbicides for the control of linuron resistant pigweed species will provide new weed management options for growers’ in-regards to the best management practices for current and future herbicide resistant populations.","principal_investigator":"Clarence Swanton","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000000267225410","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9319,"title":"SapHIA (Sustainability and Prevention through Health Impact Assessment)","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2020-06-19 15:23:05 UTC","updated_at":"2020-06-19 15:23:44 UTC","slug":"saphia-sustainability-and-prevention-through-health-impact-assessment","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Jennifer Ann Brown","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9320,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-06-19 19:25:49 UTC","updated_at":"2020-06-19 19:25:49 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3638","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Anthony Reardon","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9321,"title":"The influence of online food purchasing on consumers’ diet quality and eating practices","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2020-06-19 23:48:19 UTC","updated_at":"2020-06-19 23:50:05 UTC","slug":"the-influence-of-online-food-purchasing-on-consumers-diet-quality-and-eating-practices","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Background: Digital food retail environments are a growing part of e-commerce. In 2019, 29% of Canadians used food delivery apps (e.g., Skip the Dishes). Furthermore, online groceries (e.g., Superstore Click and Collect) and meal kits (e.g., GoodFood) are becoming increasingly popular. However, the impacts of these digital food retail services on consumers’ food choices are unknown.  \r\nHypothesis: Online food purchasing is associated with diet quality and eating practices and is driven by consumer preferences.\r\nObjectives: To explore the associations between online food purchasing, diet quality, and eating practices and to evaluate the impact of different online purchasing attributes on meal choice.\r\nMethodological approach: This is a cross-sectional study that includes an online survey and discrete choice experiment. The survey will collect information on participant characteristics, diet quality, and eating practices (online food purchasing, meals prepared at home, and food literacy). Canadian adults who do not purchase food online and who use food delivery apps, online groceries or meal kits will be recruited on social media (expected n = 1170). Associations of diet quality and eating practices with online food purchasing will be analyzed using separate multiple linear regression models, controlling for participant characteristics. A discrete choice experiment consisting of a series of choice tasks will be used to study preferred meal selection based on different online purchasing attributes. \r\nValue of research to future dietetic practice: This study aligns with the Canadian Foundation of Dietetic Research’s area of support “Determinants of food choice”. Findings will reveal positive and negative effects of purchasing food online, which will help develop strategies to assist the public in making healthy online food purchasing decisions. This exploratory study will fill knowledge gaps regarding the impacts of emerging digital food environments on food choices. \r\n","principal_investigator":"Melissa Fernandez","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0002-3464-4870","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9322,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-06-21 00:11:18 UTC","updated_at":"2020-06-21 00:11:18 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3639","organisation_id":33,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Liana Wong","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9323,"title":"inhibitory control in a cohort with presumed neurological impairment of unknown etiology","dmptemplate_id":56,"created_at":"2020-06-21 00:35:06 UTC","updated_at":"2020-06-21 00:38:49 UTC","slug":"inhibitory-control-in-a-cohort-with-presumed-neurological-impairment-of-unknown-etiology","organisation_id":15,"grant_number":"","identifier":"B00810630","description":""