vel methods to prevent disease\".","principal_investigator":"Jeff Caswell","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1991-3219","data_contact":"Monica Baquero, 5198301212, mbaquero@uoguelph.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9425,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-07-14 14:17:49 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-14 14:17:49 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3703","organisation_id":36,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Vielka Salazar","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9426,"title":"My plan (University of Guelph Agri-Food Funding Template (Alliance/Food from Thought) )","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-07-14 14:57:24 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-14 14:57:24 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-guelph-agri-food-funding-template-alliance-food-from-thought--163","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Nader Soltani","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9428,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-07-14 22:22:04 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-14 22:22:04 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3704","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Jane Foo","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9429,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-07-15 18:45:22 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-15 18:45:22 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3705","organisation_id":42,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Jeff Moon","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9430,"title":"My plan (Ocean Data Management Plan)","dmptemplate_id":28,"created_at":"2020-07-15 18:46:51 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-15 18:46:51 UTC","slug":"my-plan-ocean-data-management-plan--139","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Jeff Moon","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9431,"title":"The Gynaecological Cancer Tissue Bank","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-07-15 18:55:05 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-15 19:00:01 UTC","slug":"the-gynaecological-cancer-tissue-bank","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"The purpose of the Gynecological Cancer Tissue Bank is to improve knowledge about gynecological cancer, by making available to scientists across Canada large numbers of gynecological tumour specimens and normal control tissues for studies of cancer biology, detection and treatment. To this end, pathologist, clinicians and cancer researchers in British Columbia have formed the Gynecological Cancer tissue bank to collect tissue from gynecological cancers. Research to determine how gynecologic cancers begin, what causes them, how to treat them and the long term effects of treatments is urgently needed. In conjunction with the BC Gynecological Cancer Registry, it forms a database platform that includes biospecimens, outcomes data, 'omics data, and imaging data that aims to accelerate transformative research to reduce death and suffering from gynecologic cancers in Canada. ","principal_investigator":"Jessica McAlpine","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Rachel Wan","funder_name":null},{"id":9432,"title":"The Ontario Lodge: an alternative to the contemporary cottage through designed communal space and shared environmental stewardship.","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-07-15 21:32:35 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-15 21:35:22 UTC","slug":"the-ontario-lodge-an-alternative-to-the-contemporary-cottage-through-designed-communal-space-and-shared-environmental-stewardship","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"The purpose of this study is to research the relationships between Southern Ontario cottage culture and rural communities. Specifically, the differences between seasonal residents, rural residents, in-town residents, converters, regular tourists, and outsiders caused by lack of public lake access to Baptiste and Elephant lake in the Haliburton-Hasting Highlands area. This site is a good example of high tourism cottage country paired with one of the poorest municipalities in the province. The hypothesis is that rural residents, in-town residents, and outsiders do not have a connection to the local bodies of water (lakes, rivers, etc.), yet they enjoy the same recreational water use as the other groups. It is assumed that rural residents, in-town residents, and converters rely on more public forms of socialization, therefore they may be more open to socializing along Baptiste Lake and Elephant Lake if adequate public access were provided.  The aim of this study is to confirm the assumptions made in the hypothesis and provide a localized context for the social relationships around shared water-use. The objective is to use the results to prove or disprove the idea that commercial shoreline properties, like lodges and marinas, can be alternative places for community. The results will also inform architectural design decisions that work to accommodate the different types of residents.  ","principal_investigator":"Richard Andrighetti, Hannah Spasov","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Hannah Spasov","funder_name":null},{"id":9433,"title":"HERBICIDE-RESISTANT WEEDS IN ONTARIO - SURVEYS, MECHANISM OF RESISTANCE, AND DEVELOPMENT OF INTEGRATED MANAGEMENT STRATEGIES (University of Guelph Agri-Food Funding (Alliance/Food from Thought) )","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-07-16 12:48:47 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-17 16:20:36 UTC","slug":"herbicide-resistant-weeds-in-ontario-surveys-mechanism-of-resistance-and-development-of-integrated-management-strategies-university-of-guelph-agri-food-funding-alliance-food-from-thought","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"UG-T1-2020-100089","identifier":"","description":"There is an increasing number of herbicide-and multiple-resistant weed biotypes in Ontario and they are found in wider geographic area. Herbicide-resistant waterhemp, common ragweed, giant ragweed, and Canada fleabane have caused an average yield loss of 17, 75, 72, and 64% in corn; and 43, 74, 74, and 65% in soybean, respectively. Understanding the biology of these emerging weed pests is required to develop integrated weed management strategies. Surveys on their distribution and an understanding of the mechanism of resistance of these biotypes is crucial for the proper development of control strategies. Studies will be implemented on the evaluation of new herbicides and new herbicide-resistant crop hybrids/cultivars. Trials will be established on farms to evaluate diverse integrated weed management strategies including environmental impact, crop row width, crop rotation, cover crops and diverse herbicide modes-of-action.","principal_investigator":"Peter Sikkema","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0002-6326-9678","data_contact":"Dr. Nader Soltani, 519-902-1221, soltanin@uoguelph.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9434,"title":"Evaluation of Collaborative Editing Techniques in Behaviour Tree Authoring Tools ortage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-07-16 17:54:58 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-02 03:52:40 UTC","slug":"evaluation-of-collaborative-editing-techniques-in-behaviour-tree-authoring-tools-ortage-template","organisation_id":48,"grant_number":"210364","identifier":"REB# 10491","description":"Behavior trees have become increasingly popular as an action selection mechanism for non-player characters in games because it allows game developers a level of control that was previously out of reach without having some knowledge of writing code. Node Canvas is one of the most popular tools in Unity for creating advanced AI behaviors and logic for game characters. We want to create NCAlt+ (Node Canvas Alternative+), an extension to Node Canvas that supports collaboration among game developers so that they can improve opportunistic task adaptation and help co-developers when they are stuck. In our proposed collaborative extension to Node Canvas, the developers can collaborate both synchronously and asynchronously while working on the behavior trees. Besides, this tool aims to resurrect behavior tree variants from the past, allowing the developers to create alternatives from history. \r\nWe will conduct a study, where participants will be asked to perform three tasks using the three interfaces (synchronous, asynchronous and actual Node Canvas with an external chat system such as Discord) for collaborative behavior tree authoring. The three tasks will involve developing AI behaviors collaboratively, where two participants will be involved simultaneously. In the end, participants will rate the three interfaces using a self-developed questionnaire, a standard SUS (System Usability Scale), and the CSI (Creativity Support Index), which was designed, among other things, to rate collaboration. How participants use the interfaces will be logged and their screens will be recorded for further analysis. Semi-structured interviews will be administrated to supplement the findings with more qualitative data. The audio of the interviews will be recorded for analysis.","principal_investigator":"Dr. Loutfouz Zaman","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"loutfouz.zaman@ontariotechu.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9435,"title":"My plan (University of Alberta Template)","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2020-07-17 16:44:37 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-17 16:44:37 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-alberta-template--852","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Paul Stothard","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9436,"title":"My plan (University of British Columbia Generic Template)","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-07-18 19:55:50 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-18 19:55:50 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-british-columbia-generic-template--576","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Ismalia De Sousa","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9437,"title":"Applying Wearable Sensors & Machine Learning to Improve Dairy Cow Health & Production   ","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-07-19 13:50:56 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-27 16:43:54 UTC","slug":"applying-wearable-sensors-machine-learning-to-improve-dairy-cow-health-production","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"This research project aims to establish prepartum rumination patterns and their abitilty to predict postpartum disease susceptibility. Utilizing rumination, activity, health events, production and feed intake, models will be established to predict high and low risk groups based on disease development postpartum. Additionally, it will aim to investigate the possibility of prepartum interventions and their ability to reduce disease risk. With this data collected and these predictive models established, there is great potential to improve herd health, welfare, productivity and profitability. ","principal_investigator":"Eduardo de Souza Ribeiro","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9438,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-07-19 15:56:23 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-19 16:01:48 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3708","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Nancy Klos","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9439,"title":"Mon plan (Modèle Portage)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-07-19 20:41:03 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-19 20:41:03 UTC","slug":"mon-plan-modele-portage--543","organisation_id":29,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Marie Larocque","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9440,"title":"Supplementation of omega-3 fatty acids as a nutraceutical strategy to control postpartum inflammation and enhance production efficiency and fertility in dairy cows","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-07-20 15:07:59 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-07 19:57:41 UTC","slug":"supplementation-of-omega-3-fatty-acids-as-a-nutraceutical-strategy-to-control-postpartum-inflammation-and-enhance-production-efficiency-and-fertility-in-dairy-cows","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"UG-T1-2020-100222","identifier":"","description":"This project aims to test whether dietary supplementation of omega-3 fatty acids during the early postpartum period can mitigate the degree and hasten the resolution of postpartum inflammation. Thus improving subsequent milk production efficiency and reproduction of lactating cows. In addition we will test whether this supplementation during the breeding period can improve the uterine environment, early embryonic development and survival. The purpose of the data being collected is to evaluate whether dietary supplementation of omega-3 fatty acids is advisable during the postpartum and/or breeding period as a nutraceutical strategy to improve milk production efficiency and fertility. ","principal_investigator":"Eduardo De Souza Ribeiro","principal_investigator_identifier":"orcid.org/0000-0002-4201-7383","data_contact":"eribeiro@uoguelph.ca; (519) 824-4120 Ext. 56516 ","funder_name":null},{"id":9441,"title":"Therapist Perception 2","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-07-20 22:40:41 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-20 22:43:25 UTC","slug":"therapist-perception-2","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":"","identifier":"42250","description":"Hons thesis project of Jackline Ponomariov (F2019-F2020). One of 2 studies - the other is Therapist Perception (ORE 41807). Ratings of simulated therapist profiles. Therapist age, sex, credentials, weight varied.","principal_investigator":"Jonathan Oakman","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9442,"title":"My plan (University of British Columbia Generic Template)","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-07-20 22:40:57 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-20 22:40:57 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-british-columbia-generic-template--577","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9443,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-07-21 14:55:04 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-21 14:55:04 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3710","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Peter Sikkema","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9444,"title":"My plan (University of British Columbia Generic Template)","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-07-21 16:12:33 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-21 16:12:33 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-british-columbia-generic-template--578","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Janete Estevao","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9445,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-07-21 19:49:57 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-21 19:49:57 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3711","organisation_id":28,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Sandra Cowan","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9446,"title":"My plan (University of British Columbia Generic Template)","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-07-21 22:23:48 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-21 22:23:48 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-british-columbia-generic-template--579","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9447,"title":"Genetic assessment of stress resilience in dairy cattle and sheep (University of Guelph Agri-Food Funding Template (Alliance/Food from Thought) )","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-07-22 13:20:35 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-04 19:49:33 UTC","slug":"genetic-assessment-of-stress-resilience-in-dairy-cattle-and-sheep-university-of-guelph-agri-food-funding-template-alliance-food-from-thought","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"","identifier":"UofGT2-2019-27365","description":"Livestock are routinely subjected to physical and biological stressors that negatively impact health and production. As global climate conditions continue to destabilize, livestock will be faced with additional stressors including extreme fluctuations in temperature and increased exposure to pathogens and mycotoxins. The goal of this project is to identify and breed robust livestock to enhance stress resilience, while maintaining production efficiency. Our plan is to develop an immune-based stress model using microbial-associated molecular patterns (MAMP) such as LPS to stress phenotype dairy calves, calculate heritability, explore associations with other measured health and production traits, and carry out a genome-wide association study (GWAS) to identify genetic markers associated with stress responsiveness. The resilience of stress-phenotyped calves, and also sheep, will also be assessed in response to climate associated stressors. Overall, the stress phenotyping of dairy cattle and sheep will identify the stress-associated genetic markers which will allow Ontario breeding companies to improve animal health and production well into the future.","principal_investigator":"Niel Karrow","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"nkarrow@uoguelph.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9448,"title":"Evaluating the impact of pollination on cannabinoid production in industrial hemp","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-07-22 14:22:26 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-22 14:29:55 UTC","slug":"evaluating-the-impact-of-pollination-on-cannabinoid-production-in-industrial-hemp","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"030545","identifier":"UG-T1-2020-100193","description":"This project will determine what the impact is of pollination on the cannabinoid profile and yield of field grown industrial hemp. This information will enable farmers to determine if the added expense of planting an all female industrial hemp crop is economically advantageous. This proposal addresses the Competitive Production Systems research priority under the broad OMAFRA Research Focus Area of Improved Management and Processes and specifically looks to address the OMAFRA Research priority question (8.2.7); “What are the agronomic and production practices needed to optimize plant growth and productivity to take advantage of the entire plant and flower for cannabidiol (CBD) extraction?”. Scientifically validated information on the role of pollination in CBD yield will enhance the competitiveness of Ontario farmers as they develop this new industry.","principal_investigator":"Rene Van Acker","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Rachel Riddle","funder_name":null},{"id":9449,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-07-22 15:12:08 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-22 15:12:08 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3712","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Emily Michailidis","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9450,"title":"Community Mapping - Deaf Arts","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2020-07-22 17:28:01 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-22 17:33:53 UTC","slug":"community-mapping-deaf-arts","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"The research project consists of a series of deaf community mapping workshops soliciting feedback from teachers of the deaf, parents of deaf children, deaf community leaders, deaf artists and actors, and nondeaf artists and actors working with deaf individuals and groups.  Specifically the researcher aims to determine the communities’ response to arts-based language and literacy interventions previously implemented in deaf education programs (K-12)  and to explore the potential  for implementing deaf community arts-based projects that would involve multiple partners and be coordinated through the educational institutions located within the three sites (Edmonton, Regina and Winnipeg).  ","principal_investigator":"Joanne Weber","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0002-6031-2802","data_contact":"jweber1@ualberta.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9451,"title":"My Look before she leaves: Improving cull dairy cow welfare through better on farm decisions (University of Guelph Agri-Food Funding Template (Alliance/Food from Thought) )","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-07-22 21:19:42 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-22 21:26:30 UTC","slug":"my-look-before-she-leaves-improving-cull-dairy-cow-welfare-through-better-on-farm-decisions-university-of-guelph-agri-food-funding-template-alliance-food-from-thought","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"100283","identifier":"UG-KTTR-2020-100283","description":"KTT project on producer and veterinary attitudes and knowledge of cull cows.\r\nIdentify common producer attitudes about cull dairy cows through a\r\nqualitative survey\r\n• Understand the barriers to knowledge transfer for producers around best\r\nmanagement practices for cull dairy cows and\r\nimplementation of changes to on-farm practices in this area.\r\n• Develop an online tool for self-directed producer education about best\r\nmanagement practices for managing cull dairy cows\r\n• Develop and deliver in-person workshops for producers at Elora Dairy on\r\ndecision making for cull dairy cows\r\n• Evaluate the utility of online training and in-person workshops for\r\nmodifying producer knowledge and decision making for cull dairy\r\ncows","principal_investigator":"Todd Duffield","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0001-6035-4669","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9452,"title":"My plan (Memorial University of Newfoundland)","dmptemplate_id":20,"created_at":"2020-07-23 11:51:44 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-23 11:51:44 UTC","slug":"my-plan-memorial-university-of-newfoundland--53","organisation_id":16,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9453,"title":"Analysis of rubber yield selection gain in Russian DandelionMy plan (University of Guelph Agri-Food Funding Template (Alliance/Food from Thought) )","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-07-23 12:55:58 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-23 12:57:36 UTC","slug":"analysis-of-rubber-yield-selection-gain-in-russian-dandelionmy-plan-university-of-guelph-agri-food-funding-template-alliance-food-from-thought","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"UG-T2-2019-100736","identifier":"","description":"The project will evaluate gain from selection to improve rubber yield in Russian Dandelion after eight selection cycles.","principal_investigator":"David Wolyn","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"David Wolyn","funder_name":null},{"id":9454,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-07-23 15:22:47 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-23 15:22:47 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3713","organisation_id":11,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Tim Tripp","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9455,"title":"Mon plan (Modèle Portage)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-07-23 18:14:21 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-23 18:14:21 UTC","slug":"mon-plan-modele-portage--544","organisation_id":29,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Amelie Mainville","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9456,"title":"My plan (University of British Columbia Generic Template)","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-07-24 00:06:25 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-24 00:13:28 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-british-columbia-generic-template--580","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Liliana Jimenez","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9457,"title":"My plan (University of British Columbia Generic Template)","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-07-24 00:10:52 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-24 00:11:04 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-british-columbia-generic-template--581","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Jian Liu","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9458,"title":"Impact of maternal trace mineral supplementation sources during late gestation on quality of colostrum, and on immunity, health, and performance of dairy calves","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-07-24 17:38:17 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-07 19:59:22 UTC","slug":"impact-of-maternal-trace-mineral-supplementation-sources-during-late-gestation-on-quality-of-colostrum-and-on-immunity-health-and-performance-of-dairy-calves","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"UofGT2-2019-27374","identifier":"","description":"Trace minerals comprise a small portion of the diet of a dairy cow but one that cannot be ignored. They are integral in the proper functioning of all body systems of the cow but play an especially important role in the immune system as crucial aspects in enzyme function. Inorganic trace minerals are widely understood to be less bioavailable and thus less readily used by the animal in these vital roles than organic trace minerals due to biochemical and structural differences. The purpose of this study is to investigate if and how the prepartum supplementation of organic vs inorganic trace minerals of the dam will impact the immunity, health, and performance of her calf, as well as how it impacts colostrum quality and passive transfer of immunity. Currently, the impact of organic trace mineral supplementation in the gestating dam on postnatal life of the calf has been undercharacterized.","principal_investigator":"Eduardo de Souza Ribeiro ","principal_investigator_identifier":"orcid.org/0000-0002-4201-7383","data_contact":"eribeiro@uoguelph.ca; (519) 824-4120 Ext. 56516 ","funder_name":null},{"id":9459,"title":"My plan (University of Saskatchewan)","dmptemplate_id":21,"created_at":"2020-07-25 22:16:41 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-25 22:16:41 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-saskatchewan--10","organisation_id":17,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Simon Rickards","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9460,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-07-27 15:24:00 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-27 15:24:00 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3714","organisation_id":9,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Stefanie Haustein","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9461,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-07-27 15:29:09 UTC","updated_at