l},{"id":9466,"title":"Mon plan (CEOS Template - Draft)","dmptemplate_id":22,"created_at":"2020-07-27 20:04:23 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-27 20:04:30 UTC","slug":"mon-plan-ceos-template-draft--6","organisation_id":19,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Amelie Mainville","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9467,"title":"Mon plan (University of Alberta Template)","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2020-07-27 20:05:36 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-27 20:05:36 UTC","slug":"mon-plan-university-of-alberta-template--20","organisation_id":2,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Amelie Mainville","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9468,"title":"Preliminary Insight on Uranium Mining in Dene, Cree, and Métis Territory, Northern Sask.","dmptemplate_id":56,"created_at":"2020-07-28 13:44:03 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-28 16:29:19 UTC","slug":"preliminary-insight-on-uranium-mining-in-dene-cree-and-metis-territory-northern-sask","organisation_id":15,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"The objective of this research is to analyze an archive of uranium mining activity in collaboration with the Dene, Cree, and Métis communities on whose territory this mining occurred.\r\n\r\nOur research will be directed by members of these communities to produce research outputs that may be useful in their contemporary struggles for rights and justice. \r\n\r\nThese outputs will include annotated historical maps of mining activity; quantitative records of mine production and toxic waste products; and narratives of Dene, Cree, and Métis communities’ interaction with mining. ","principal_investigator":"Aaron Sidney Wright","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9469,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-07-28 14:32:16 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-28 14:32:16 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3718","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9470,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-07-28 22:32:48 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-28 22:32:48 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3719","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Andrea Davidson","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9471,"title":"My plan (University of Guelph Agri-Food Funding Template (Alliance/Food from Thought) )","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-07-29 13:53:17 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-30 15:22:58 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-guelph-agri-food-funding-template-alliance-food-from-thought--172","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"UG-T1-2020-100198 development of a sustainable pest management program for the box tree moth - a pest of the nursery and landscape industry.","identifier":"","description":"The box tree moth (BTM) (Cydalima perspectalis) is an invasive insect pest that was confirmed to be present\r\nin Etobicoke, Ontario by the CFIA in November, 2018. BTM attacks boxwood (Buxus sp.), a popular broadleaf plant used in residential and commercial gardens, hedges and topiary in Canada. For the nursery sector, boxwood represents a very high value, slow-growing crop in Ontario, Quebec and BC. BTM is a distinct threat to this industry causing severe defoliation that quickly leads to death of the plant in both young and mature specimens. Currently, there is no IPM program for BTM in Ontario. This proposed project will focus on the\r\ndevelopment of a sustainable IPM program for BTM that will include monitoring, a phytosanitary protocol,\r\nBTM biology in Ontario (life cycle, plant phenology indicators, degree day), biological and chemical control\r\ntactics. The nursery industry will benefit from the development of BMP for BTM.\r\nThe overarching objective of the project is to develop an effective IPM program for the that will allow the nursery industry and residential landowners to manage and slow the spread:\r\n1) Survey and monitoring - delineate the dispersal of box tree moth from confirmed locations in Etobicoke;\r\nidentify outbreaks in new areas away from Etobicoke but associated with boxwood in Ontario;\r\n2) Investigate the biology, population ecology and behaviour of BTM in Ontario since they appear to be\r\ndifferent from population in Asia and Europe;\r\n3) IPM - strategies for BTM management will be investigated with a focus on biological (classical,\r\naugmentative and conservation) , and chemical (screening chemicals; biochemical biopesticides - mating\r\ndisruption) controls;\r\n4) Develop a BTM phytosanitary protocol/certification for commercial growers of box tree in an effort to\r\nretain export markets to the US.","principal_investigator":"Cynthia Scott-Dupree","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0001-8159-4768","data_contact":"Cynthia Scott Dupree","funder_name":null},{"id":9472,"title":"My plan (Dalhousie University Generic Plan)","dmptemplate_id":56,"created_at":"2020-07-29 16:23:03 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-29 16:23:03 UTC","slug":"my-plan-dalhousie-university-generic-plan--21","organisation_id":15,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Poppy Nicolette Riddle","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9473,"title":"My plan (University of Alberta Template)","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2020-07-29 17:41:16 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-29 17:41:16 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-alberta-template--854","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Matthias Hoben","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9474,"title":"Meeting the Care Needs of Transnational Households in the Context of Covid-19: Belizean Migrant Women and their Contributions","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-07-29 23:53:53 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-30 01:34:13 UTC","slug":"meeting-the-care-needs-of-transnational-households-in-the-context-of-covid-19-belizean-migrant-women-and-their-contributions","organisation_id":15,"grant_number":"","identifier":"2020-5155","description":"Care refers to the affective tasks of social reproduction. Household members constantly exchange care. Care involves financial, material, emotional and moral support (Baldassar, Kilkey, Merla & Wilding, 2016). Care needs can be immediate and routine (i.e. food, shelter); immediate but acute (i.e. health care emergency, environmental disasters); long term and routine (i.e. ensuring access to education and health care) or long-term and acute (corresponding to prolonged illness). These tasks are usually delegated to women either as unpaid care and household duties or in the waged labour markets. Women are also joining global care labour markets as a household income generating strategy. Households take on a transnational character when social ties remain strong and they continue to socially reproduce despite geographical distance. They either adopt new strategies or reinforce traditional caregiving systems (Fog Olwig, 2007; Baldassar & Merla, 2014). Communication technology facilitates care provision (Mahler, 2001; Barber, 2001) plus mobilizes material and non-material resources. Nonetheless, because transnational households contend with migration policies and institutions from more than one nation state, they usually encounter constraints and opportunities that impact care provisioning. \r\n\r\nIn the settlement site, migrant women, especially care workers, are likely to encounter constraints such as temporary, low-income jobs, difficult working conditions, and social exclusion. Or they might be covered by restrictive policies that make them disposable, deportable, or temporary. Such situations impede their capacity to care for themselves plus dependents. This is concerning, because transnational households especially in the global south tend to rely on the resources provided by the migrant, particularly in the form of remittances. Employing a feminist political economy framework, this research will investigate how Belizean migrant women are contributing to the care needs of transnational households despite vulnerabilities.\r\n\r\nThe study population includes 10 transnational households whose members reside in Belize, Central America, and Northern Illinois, United States. Using a matched sample, the migrant in the U.S. plus two adult members in Belize will add up to about 30 participants. Using multi-sited ethnography, I will utilize migration history and face-to-face semi-structured interviews. Communication technology such as Skype and WhatsApp will be used as an alternative, if needed. Participant observation might take place if public events are hosted by the Belizean community in the U.S. during the data collection period there. \r\n\r\nThis study will fill literature gaps on transnational households, transnational caring and precarity. It will lead to a better understanding of how transnational households respond to opportunities and constraints. Findings will generate debates on caregiving strategies, resource mobilization, power inequalities plus long-term and short-term safeguards used by transnational families in a Central American context, particularly the understudied case of Belize. It will produce relevant information on contemporary Belizean political economy regarding migration and remittances. Findings can influence state governments to reduce those policy decisions that place migrants and dependents in vulnerable situations. Findings will emerge at a critical time, as the country moves forward with national economic development programming which envisions household remittances as a key resource for foreign exchange and investment.","principal_investigator":"Melanie Smith","principal_investigator_identifier":"Melanie C Smith","data_contact":"1303-1094 Wellington St. Halifax, Nova Scotia, B3H 2Z9","funder_name":null},{"id":9475,"title":"Assessing Land Use Planning Tools to Mitigate Odour and Lighting Nuisances Related to Cannabis Production (Alliance Grant)","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-07-30 00:33:54 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-26 18:28:43 UTC","slug":"assessing-land-use-planning-tools-to-mitigate-odour-and-lighting-nuisances-related-to-cannabis-production-alliance-grant","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"030558","identifier":"","description":"This study will examine current land use planning policies for cannabis facilities. In examining existing policies and through interviews/focus groups with municipal representatives, recommendations for minimum standards will be provided.","principal_investigator":"Sara Epp","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9476,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-07-30 18:40:05 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-30 18:40:05 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3721","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Sheila Petty","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9477,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-07-30 22:15:53 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-30 22:15:53 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3722","organisation_id":33,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9478,"title":"My plan (University of Alberta Template)","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2020-07-31 02:34:19 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-31 02:34:19 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-alberta-template--855","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Laura lmurphy@ualberta.ca","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9479,"title":"Gesture and Form: A Field-based Approach to New Methods of Architecture and Handcraft in Textiles Using Augmented Reality Technologies","dmptemplate_id":56,"created_at":"2020-07-31 18:33:57 UTC","updated_at":"2020-07-31 18:50:00 UTC","slug":"gesture-and-form-a-field-based-approach-to-new-methods-of-architecture-and-handcraft-in-textiles-using-augmented-reality-technologies","organisation_id":15,"grant_number":"NFRFE-2019-00863","identifier":"","description":"“Gesture and Form” employs an empirically-grounded research-creation process to find methods, forms, and instruments to create, think, and teach with embodied knowledge. The researchers propose an interaction design methodology combining movement recorded with hand-tracking devices and visual representations of forms overlaid in physical space through augmented reality (AR) head-worn displays (HWDs). Augmented Reality (AR) is a display technique that allows users to perceive and interact with virtual (computer-generated) content as if it were part of the real world. \r\n\r\nThe larger study considers the relationship between AR technology and embodied knowledge through the following cases: the making of intricate rope lattices in architectural education settings; the reproduction of beadwoven artifacts in textile and material culture educational contexts; and two community-based experiential learning settings which teach the fundamental principles and techniques of architecture and beadweaving. Together these use-cases will explore the possibilities and limitations of AR technology in the designing and making of handicrafts and complex physical environments, insights which have ramifications for both the material aspects of near and built environment, and their social construction.\r\n\r\nThis project unites researchers in architectural design and technology, human computer interaction (HCI), cultural anthropology and material culture studies, and constructed textiles. Given this disciplinary diversity, we seek to integrate the methods and methodological paradigms of both design anthropology and design research. This dual approach enables a fine-grained ethnographic understanding of the design process - via design anthropology - and practice-led design research through the design process (suitable to the research-creation framework of the funded project).","principal_investigator":"James Forren, Derek Reilly, Claire Nicholas","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"James Forren, james.forren@dal.ca; Derek Reilly, reilly@cs.dal.ca; Claire Nicholas, cnicholas2@unl.edu","funder_name":null},{"id":9480,"title":"My plan (Dalhousie University Generic Plan)","dmptemplate_id":56,"created_at":"2020-08-04 20:03:55 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-04 20:03:55 UTC","slug":"my-plan-dalhousie-university-generic-plan--23","organisation_id":15,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Derek Tittensor","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9481,"title":"Olfaction et violence","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-05 15:14:00 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-05 15:33:59 UTC","slug":"olfaction-et-violence","organisation_id":42,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Mesures neuropsychologiques d'impulsivité, d'attention et d'olfaction chez des personnes violentes atteintes d'un trouble du spectre de la schizophrénie","principal_investigator":"Christian Joyal","principal_investigator_identifier":"Christian Joyal","data_contact":"Christian Joyal","funder_name":null},{"id":9482,"title":"Everyday Practices of Making Home","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-05 16:48:48 UTC","updated_at":"202