updated_at":"2020-08-07 20:01:55 UTC","slug":"using-basic-science-to-improve-fertility-in-dairy-cattle-development-of-an-endometrial-receptivity-test-for-genetic-selection","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"UofG2017-3029 ","identifier":"","description":"The purpose of this study is to investigate how the endometrium of primiparous cows will respond to an intrauterine infusion of pregnancy derived factors which simulate the presence of a preimplantation fetus. The objective is to evaluate the responsiveness of the endometrium and associate this response will reproductive performance. This association has been undercharacterized and is an important piece of the puzzle in the potential development of a fertility test with applications in genetic selection.","principal_investigator":"Eduardo de Souza Ribeiro ","principal_investigator_identifier":"orcid.org/0000-0002-4201-7383","data_contact":"eribeiro@uoguelph.ca; (519) 824-4120 Ext. 56516 ","funder_name":null},{"id":9489,"title":"My plan (University of Alberta Template)","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2020-08-06 15:40:34 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-06 15:40:34 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-alberta-template--856","organisation_id":2,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Tanya Voth","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9490,"title":"Applying Wearable Sensors & Machine Learning to Improve Dairy Cow Health & Production   ","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-08-07 01:54:59 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-07 19:58:24 UTC","slug":"applying-wearable-sensors-machine-learning-to-improve-dairy-cow-health-production--2","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"This research project aims to establish prepartum rumination patterns and their abitilty to predict postpartum disease susceptibility. Utilizing rumination, activity, health events, production and feed intake, models will be established to predict high and low risk groups based on disease development postpartum. Additionally, it will aim to investigate the possibility of prepartum interventions and their ability to reduce disease risk. With this data collected and these predictive models established, there is great potential to improve herd health, welfare, productivity and profitability. ","principal_investigator":"Eduardo de Souza Ribeiro","principal_investigator_identifier":"orcid.org/0000-0002-4201-7383","data_contact":"eribeiro@uoguelph.ca; (519) 824-4120 Ext. 56516 ","funder_name":null},{"id":9491,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-07 14:51:50 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-07 14:51:50 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3727","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Jessie Gunnell","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9493,"title":"My plan (University of Guelph Agri-Food Funding Template (Alliance/Food from Thought) )","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-08-07 15:36:41 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-07 15:38:21 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-guelph-agri-food-funding-template-alliance-food-from-thought--176","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"UofGT2-2019-27354","identifier":"","description":"Impact of a Dietary Citrus Extract on Reducing Stress Associated with Regrouping of Dairy Cows","principal_investigator":"Trevor DeVries","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9494,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-08 15:05:36 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-08 15:07:33 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3728","organisation_id":55,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Just a test plan to learn about the process.","principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9495,"title":"WAVE Project","dmptemplate_id":44,"created_at":"2020-08-10 02:40:01 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-10 02:24:02 UTC","slug":"wave-project","organisation_id":21,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"[Copied from Research Proposal] In the last decade there has been an increase in the use of Automatic Identification System (AIS) to understand the movement, intensity and potential impact of vessel operations, primarily shipping and fishing, in relation to wildlife and marine environments for informing conservation policy and marine spatial planning. However, there are no known studies using AIS data to characterize and understand whale watching activities specifically, leaving a significant gap in our understanding of this sector. Working in partnership with the whale watching industry, regulators and exactEarth, in British Columbia and the Strait of Gibraltar, we aim to (1) to increase the understanding of whale watching activities in general using AIS, and (2) to determine the feasibility of utilizing AIS data as a tool for informing whale watching operations as well as conservation policy and regulations in particular. Through the research we hope to empower individual vessel operators to collect data that are valuable to them and that could also contribute not only to the management of whale watching industry but also to marine conservation processes.","principal_investigator":"Rosaline Canessa","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Andrea Nesdoly & Norma Serra-Sogas","funder_name":null},{"id":9496,"title":"Using Behavioral Economics to Promote Best Management Practices Adoption: Experimental Evidence on the Effectiveness of Nudges, Framing, and Messenger Selection","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-08-10 18:05:29 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-14 16:17:13 UTC","slug":"using-behavioral-economics-to-promote-best-management-practices-adoption-experimental-evidence-on-the-effectiveness-of-nudges-framing-and-messenger-selection","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"","identifier":"UG-T1-2020-100160","description":"Data will be collected from participants in an incentive-compatible economic experiment. This research seeks to determine the comparative effectiveness of subsidies versus the network effect in influencing the adoption of new technology. This experiment will be designed with the purpose of understanding the factors influencing adoption of technologies which offer a positive externality/public good component with applications in the areas of agricultural and natural resource management. Additionally, this research can be used to identify the attributes of early technology adopters dependent on varying risk scenarios.","principal_investigator":"Tongzhe Li","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Tongzhe Li, 1-519-824-4120 x53332, tongzhe@uoguelph.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9498,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-10 20:34:26 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-10 20:34:42 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3729","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Kevin  Lindstrom","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9499,"title":"Equine Herpes Virus (EHV) and EHV-associated disease in the Ontario Equine Industry - Disease prevalence and prevention","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-08-11 16:59:10 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-29 20:35:25 UTC","slug":"equine-herpes-virus-ehv-and-ehv-associated-disease-in-the-ontario-equine-industry-disease-prevalence-and-prevention","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"UofG2017-2939","identifier":"030350","description":"Equine herpesvirus 1 and 4(EHV-1 and EHV-4) are major causes of reproductive, neurological and respiratory\r\ndisease in horses worldwide. The initial infection is acquired during the first months of life, which results in a\r\nlife-long latent infection in most horses, and the disease has a significant negative economic impact on the horse\r\nindustry within Ontario and further abroad. The stimulus for reactivation remains unclear and despite repeated\r\nvaccination, EHV-associated disease and death still occur in horses world-wide. As a result of the ongoing\r\noccurrence of clinical disease and viral reactivation/shedding, greater understanding of the epidemiology of this\r\nvirus is imperative.\r\nWe suspect the true rate of abortion in Ontario and prevalence of EHV-1-associated disease or abortion is much\r\nhigher than the values that have been reported through diagnostic laboratories and referral facilities alone. We\r\nhave completed a survey of horse farms/breeders and identified ~70 willing to participate in a wider surveillance\r\nprogram for EHV. This project will investigate the prevalence of EHV and EHV-associated disease on Ontario\r\nhorse farms, investigate the time course of EHV shedding and serological responses during the reproductive\r\ncycle and attempt to determine novel strategies to minimize the occurrence and impact of EHV-associated\r\ndisease.\r\n","principal_investigator":"Brandon Lillie","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0002-3116-9111","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9500,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-12 14:06:14 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-12 14:06:14 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3730","organisation_id":10,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Abeer Siddiqui","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9501,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-12 14:18:58 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-12 14:18:58 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3731","organisation_id":10,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Ryan Belowitz","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9502,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-12 15:00:37 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-12 15:00:37 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3732","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Nicole Westlund Stewart","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9503,"title":"Biodegradable and Compostable Bale Wrap for Ontario Agriculture","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-08-12 20:06:19 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-12 20:13:47 UTC","slug":"biodegradable-and-compostable-bale-wrap-for-ontario-agriculture","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"030578","identifier":"UG-T1-2020-100279","description":"Bale wraps now accounts for 6 million pounds of silage produced in Canada yearly and they are wrapped with non-biodegradable polyethylene (PE) to promote the fermentation and forage quality of sealed bale. However, non-biodegradable PE is not recycled practically, resulting to a 2400 tonnes/year of bale wrap wastes in Canada entering landfilling. The main objective and novelty of this project is the fabrication of cost and performance competitive biodegradable and compostable green composites with hybrid fillers, targeted to develop an alternate to the current used PE. The overall aim is to develop biodegradable polymer composites based thin blown films with high melt strength, excellent oxygen barrier and good extensibility (% elongation > 250%) by introducing waste starch agro-based wastes derived biocarbon and cellulosic material as fillers. By introducing waste starch, pyrolyzed agro-residues based biocarbon, the final films with targeted properties will be cost competitive to the current petroleum-based PE films.","principal_investigator":"Manjusri Misra","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9504,"title":"Master's thesis","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-12 21:15:21 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-12 21:16:58 UTC","slug":"master-s-thesis--2","organisation_id":23,"grant_number":"","identifier":"30014771","description":"Dana Cramer's SSHRC CGS-M funded Master of Arts thesis project. Research project on Internet Protocols and their effect on physical telecommunications networks.","principal_investigator":"Dana Cramer","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"dana.cramer@ucalgary.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9505,"title":"Slip Detection Experiment Plan","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-13 08:13:45 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-13 09:38:26 UTC","slug":"slip-detection-experiment-plan","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Slip detection algorithm validation trial, participants will use a prosthetic to move a block with increasing load, attempting to determine when a slip will occur. This will be done to test the efficacy and impact on movement of a slip detection algorithm to a prosthetic hand.\r\nData collected will be time, maximum load on block, and if slip/no-slip.","principal_investigator":"Andrew Smiles","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9506,"title":"User interfaces for collabortive human robot tasks","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-13 08:57:46 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-18 14:12:18 UTC","slug":"user-interfaces-for-collabortive-human-robot-tasks","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"To deploy autonomous robots user can create a specification for robot behaviour by defining traffic rules for robots. The main resarch question is: Can interactive learning help users to create more efficient robot specifications?","principal_investigator":"Stephen L. Smith","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9507,"title":"Mon plan (Modèle Portage)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-13 14:49:21 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-13 14:49:21 UTC","slug":"mon-plan-modele-portage--548","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9508,"title":"Solving Stemphylium Unversity of Guelph Agri-Food Funding Template (Alliance/Food from Thought) )","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-08-13 15:27:20 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-13 15:32:45 UTC","slug":"solving-stemphylium-unversity-of-guelph-agri-food-funding-template-alliance-food-from-thought","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"030554","identifier":"UG-T1-2020-100115","description":"This project involves field, greenhouse and laboratory trials to improve the current disease forecasting program for Stemphylium leaf blight of onion and provide additional management tools for onion growers","principal_investigator":"Mary Ruth  McDonald","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9509,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-14 20:31:11 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-14 20:31:11 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3736","organisation_id":20,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Kevin  Lindstrom","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9510,"title":"RCT","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-15 06:28:00 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-24 08:05:48 UTC","slug":"rct","organisation_id":14,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"A randomized controlled trial of a relationship education workshop. \r\nDoes participation in the RE workshop improve relationships over 6 months, help people to feel more confident about dealing with relationship problems, and make better relationship decisions.","principal_investigator":"Rebecca Cobb","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9511,"title":"My plan (University of Guelph Agri-Food Funding Template (Alliance/Food from Thought) )","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-08-17 05:50:05 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-17 05:50:05 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-guelph-agri-food-funding-template-alliance-food-from-thought--181","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Kathleen Nolan","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9512,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-17 17:25:15 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-17 17:25:15 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3738","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Hector Perez","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9513,"title":"Genetic improvement of asparagus for yield, quality and disease traits ","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-08-17 19:41:28 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-17 19:45:07 UTC","slug":"genetic-improvement-of-asparagus-for-yield-quality-and-disease-traits","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"UG-T2-2018-27343","identifier":"","description":"Develop all-male asparagus hybrids with improved performance","principal_investigator":"David Wolyn","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"David Wolyn","funder_name":null},{"id":9514,"title":"Evaluation of the High Immune Response Technology™ in beef cattle in the context of climate change, calf health and the development of a genomics test for immune response","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-08-19 15:25:31 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-25 01:11:11 UTC","slug":"evaluation-of-the-high-immune-response-technology-in-beef-cattle-in-the-context-of-climate-change-calf-health-and-the-development-of-a-genomics-test-for-immune-response","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"UofGT2-2019-27367 ","identifier":"UofGT2-2019-27367 ","description":"The HIR technology is a University of Guelph patented test method that identifies animals with inherently superior immunity. HIR can be used by livestock producers as a management and/or breeding tool to naturally improve herd health. Genetic regulation of the immune system using HIR has improved animal health and welfare, a benefit to producers, consumers, animals, and food safety. Healthy animals require less treatment, thus decreasing antibiotic use, combating antimicrobial resistance. High immune responders display improved response to commercial vaccines and are diseased almost 50% less frequently than herd-mates. The Canadian Cattlemen’s Association has identified bovine respiratory disease (BRD) as the most common and costly disease affecting the North American Beef industry. Despite the need for improved health in Canadian beef production and significant advancements in medicine and management practices, BRD disease rates remain seemingly unchanged. The HIR technology for beef cattle is another potential tool for the beef industry’s battle against BRD and other important disease and environmental challenges, such as climate change. In addition to calf management changes, such as prophylactic pre-weaning protocols and the use of advanced antimicrobials, this research enables beef breeders to develop a more robust beef animal that is naturally resistant to disease.\r\n\r\nThis project aims to develop an HIR genomics test for beef cattle. A genomics test for IR will exponentially increase marketability of this technology as animals could be HIR tested by submission of a DNA sample. A study of 4000 Angus cattle in Australia, IR phenotyped using a modified HIR test, indicated that animals classified as high responders were less likely to die from BRD. To broaden the applicability of the HIR technology for beef cattle, this project is evaluating the HIR test system to develop a genomic HIR test similar to that successfully used by Semex for Holsteins. This project is also evaluating the effect of climate change, particularly heat stress, on the IR of beef cattle, as well as the quality of colostrum and passive transfer of maternal antibody from HIR phenotyped beef cattle.","principal_investigator":"Bonnie Mallard","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9516,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-20 13:45:56 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-20 13:45:56 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3740","organisation_id":14,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Dan Phillips","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9517,"title":"My plan (Dalhousie University Generic Plan)","dmptemplate_id":56,"created_at":"2020-08-20 13:46:30 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-20 13:46:30 UTC","slug":"my-plan-dalhousie-university-generic-plan--25","organisation_id":15,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Dan Phillips","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9518,"title":"My plan (OFI Module E (Ecosystem Indicators))","dmptemplate_id":55,"created_at":"2020-08-20 13:47:24 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-20 13:47:24 UTC","slug":"my-plan-ofi-module-e-ecosystem-indicators--12","organisation_id":15,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Dan Phillips","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9520,"title":"Means to improve the robustness of newly weaned pigs exposed to mycotoxin-contaminated feeds","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-08-20 14:48:34 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-25 14:41:25 UTC","slug":"means-to-improve-the-robustness-of-newly-weaned-pigs-exposed-to-mycotoxin-contaminated-feeds","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"N/A","identifier":"UofGT2-2019-27363","description":"Mycotoxins, including deoxynivalenol (DON), are secondary metabolites of fungal infections that frequently occur in cereal grains and corn. Pigs are the most susceptible livestock species to DON and symptoms of exposure include reduced feed intake and growth, which represents a $50 million loss of profits for the Ontario pork industry with only modest DON contamination. We evaluated different dietary mitigation strategies for reducing the negative effects of DON in nursery pig diets. We conducted two studies using a total of 500 nursery pigs. ","principal_investigator":"Lee-Anne Huber","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9521,"title":"Protein and non-protein methionine requirements for first parity gestating and lactating sows","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-08-20 15:00:51 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-25 14:48:42 UTC","slug":"protein-and-non-protein-methionine-requirements-for-first-parity-gestating-and-lactating-sows","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"N/A","identifier":"UG-T2-2019-100519","description":"Feed is the number one input cost in the pork production system. Thus, to improve efficiency of the system, it is important to supply dietary nutrients to precisely meet estimated requirements. For reproductive sows, the nutrient requirements for the amino acid methionine were estimated over 40 years ago and do not take into account the production levels of our modern sows. Methionine is important in the body for protein synthesis, but also other non-protein roles including one-carbon metabolism. Therefore, the objectives are to precisely determine the protein and non-protein methionine requirements for both gestating and lactating sows, which can be incorporated into precision feeding programs. We used 200 sows and their offspring over four studies. ","principal_investigator":"Lee-Anne Huber","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9522,"title":"Données géospatiales","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-20 15:01:47 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-20 15:02:56 UTC","slug":"donnees-geospatiales--2","organisation_id":29,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Dany Bouchard","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Sylvie St-Pierre","funder_name":null},{"id":9523,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-21 13:14:03 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-21 13:14:03 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3741","organisation_id":33,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Christine Mills","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9524,"title":"Giving a voice to family care partners of older people about the meanings of their experience and recommendations for supportive actions during the COVID-19 pandemic: A critical ethnography ","dmptemplate_id":43,"created_at":"2020-08-21 19:02:01 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-21 19:54:26 UTC","slug":"giving-a-voice-to-family-care-partners-of-older-people-about-the-meanings-of-their-experience-and-recommendations-for-supportive-actions-during-the-covid-19-pandemic-a-critical-ethnography","organisation_id":32,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"This project is qualitative project being done with the same protocol that was developed by Bourbonnais in Québec, Ontario and British Columbia. A PI is responsible for the conduct of the project in each province:\r\n\r\nQuébec: Bourbonnais\r\nOntario: Hsu\r\nBritish Columbia: Baumbusch\r\n\r\nRecruitment, data collection and data analyzi will be done independently and results will be triangulated between provinces. Results can be published from a provincial perspective or pan-Canadian perspective.","principal_investigator":"Anne Bourbonnais, Jennifer Baumbusch, Amy Hsu","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Anne Bourbonnais","funder_name":null},{"id":9525,"title":"My plan (University of Guelph Agri-Food Funding Template (Alliance/Food from Thought) )","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-08-23 17:17:42 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-23 17:20:30 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-guelph-agri-food-funding-template-alliance-food-from-thought--186","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"27364","identifier":"UofGT2-2019-27364","description":"How does asthma (heaves) develop and progress in horses?","principal_investigator":"Dorothee Bienzle","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0002-2301-2931","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9526,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-23 20:36:07 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-23 20:36:07 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3742","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Ryan Johnson","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9527,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-24 13:06:31 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-24 13:06:31 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3743","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Jose Delos Reyes","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9528,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-24 18:02:31 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-24 18:02:31 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3744","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9529,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-25 13:14:25 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-25 13:14:25 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3745","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Carol Hannam","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9530,"title":"My plan (NRC Data Management Plan template Draft)","dmptemplate_id":33,"created_at":"2020-08-25 13:17:46 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-25 13:17:46 UTC","slug":"my-plan-nrc-data-management-plan-template-draft--34","organisation_id":39,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Carol Hannam","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9531,"title":"Livres anciens UQAM","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-25 13:33:23 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-25 13:41:54 UTC","slug":"livres-anciens-uqam","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Projet de numérisation des ouvrages anciens du XIIe au XVIIIe siècle de la collection du Centre des livres rares et des collections spéciales de l'UQAM, dans le cadre d'une base de données comportant les descriptions bibliographiques et matérielles des livres numérisés","principal_investigator":"Sylvie Alix","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"541-987-3000 poste 3153 alix.sylvie@uqam.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9532,"title":"Severance Study DMP_rev1","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-08-26 01:08:48 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-26 01:09:35 UTC","slug":"severance-study-dmp_rev1","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"UG-T1-2020-100093","identifier":"","description":"Problem: It is unclear whether the Provincial Policy Statement (PPS) lot creation policies should be adjusted given pressures to develop prime agricultural areas. There is no data on the impacts of these policies since 2009. Overview: This project assesses the impacts of lot creation (severance) policies by providing a province-wide evaluation of the extent and nature of rural non-farm development across Ontario between 2010 and 2019. Approach: This project will document the numbers and purpose of lots created on prime agricultural land in Ontario between 2010 and 2019. Relevant local and provincial land use policies will be identified and the impact on agriculture will be evaluated. Policy changes or other alternatives to ensure farmland availability will be suggested.","principal_investigator":"Dave Guyadeen","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0002-5628-6736","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9533,"title":"OMAFRA-UoG Tier II","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-08-26 09:03:29 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-28 14:34:40 UTC","slug":"omafra-uog-tier-ii","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"27379 OMAFRA-UoG Tier II project DMP.  Biology and management of turfgrass diseases.","identifier":"","description":"OMAFRA-UoG Tier II project DMP\r\n- annual fungicide trials (proprietary)\r\n- DMI resistance survey (2024)\r\n- Activated resistance research (2024)\r\nThe overall goals of this research program are to improve management of turfgrass diseases through research on\r\nfungicide resistance, and non-conventional controls such as activated resistance and low-risk products.","principal_investigator":"Tom Hsiang","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0002-9549-1847","data_contact":"T Hsiang, 519-824-4120x52753, thsiang@uoguelph.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9534,"title":"Projet biomarqueurs - phase I","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-26 13:10:36 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-26 14:52:33 UTC","slug":"projet-biomarqueurs-phase-i","organisation_id":44,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Les objets connectés offrent une opportunité unique de collecter, à distance et de façon non invasive, une pléthore d’information ayant le potentiel de renseigner sur l’état de santé et de bien-être des citoyens. L'utilisation d’objets connectés s'inscrit dans un changement de paradigme vers un système de santé connecté et global qui se veut prédictif, personnalisé, préventif et participatif.  Ce projet de recherche s’inscrit dans cette mouvance en santé connectée et tente de mettre à profit les technologies numériques (p. ex., téléphone intelligent, bracelet moniteur d’activités) et l’intelligence artificielle dans le but d’identifier des biomarqueurs (p. ex., activité cardiaque) et marqueurs numériques (p. ex., pratique d'activité physique, habitudes de déplacement et de sommeil) hautement prédictifs de la santé et du bien-être.  Ces données ont le potentiel fournir de nouvelles perspectives en matière de détection précoce de la maladie. Cette approche prédictive de la santé permettrait de mieux intervenir (c.-à-d., au moment opportun) et d’offrir des services sur mesure aux individus.  La phase 1 de ce projet de recherche est faite en partenariat avec deux entreprises privées : Lucine inc. et Berger-Levrault. Le présent plan de gestion de données comprend donc des informations concernant la gestion des données du côté des partenaires lorsque cela s'applique. Il est à noter qu'au moment de rédiger le présent plan, certaines modalités du protocole de recherche auquel ce plan fait référence peuvent être amenées à changer. Le cas échéant, le présent plan sera mis à jour afin de documenter les changements de modalités apportées de façon à rendre compte précisément de la gestion des données tout au long du projet. Il est a noter également que le partenaire Berger-Levrault a pris la décision de limiter son implication qu'à la phase 1 du projet de recherche. Par conséquent, une entente de résiliation qui précise que Berger-Levrault n'aura pas droit de regard sur les données et les publications qui découleront du présent projet, mais recevront uniquement un rapport présentant les résultats de la phase 1. ","principal_investigator":"Vicky Drapeau, Sébastien Tremblay","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9535,"title":"Streptococcus suis infection and nursery diet in pigs","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-08-26 14:55:43 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-26 16:28:24 UTC","slug":"streptococcus-suis-infection-and-nursery-diet-in-pigs","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"UofGT2-2019-27377","identifier":"","description":"Streptococcus suis reside in tonsils of almost all pigs, yet it is still not well understood why disease can suddenly occur. However, some cases of S. suis disease might be related to sudden changes in feed intake from milk to starters. Dietary fermentable-fibre and fermentable-protein content can have detrimental effects on overall gastrointestinal health. For example, functional amino acids have been shown to be important in the maintenance of gut barrier function and immune response. The introduction of soybean meal has been particularly noted as a cause of gut inflammation. It is possible that S. suis resides in the gut of younger pigs and if there is gut damage the bacteria can enter the blood stream and possibly the brain. Previous studies have shown that the nursery pigs fed a higher amount of soybean and corn were more susceptible to develop meningitis caused by S. suis infection. The objectives of this study are 1) to develop S. suis infection model in post-weaning pigs, 2) to evaluate the impact of nursery diet ingredients such as soybean and corn on S. suis infection in nursery pigs experimentally challenged with S. suis, and 3) to assess the impact of diet on S. suis associated diseases in pigs naturally challenged with S. suis.","principal_investigator":"Vahab Farzan","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9536,"title":"Evaluating the resilience of diversified crop rotations to extreme weather events","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-08-26 16:28:22 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-26 16:50:02 UTC","slug":"evaluating-the-resilience-of-diversified-crop-rotations-to-extreme-weather-events","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":": Extreme weather events such as intense precipitation and freeze-thaw cycles are becoming more common with climate change with dire consequences for crop production and environmental impact of agroecosystems. Diversified rotations with cover crops have been suggested as practices that can buffer against these extreme events, but this has not been evaluated well. Here we propose to investigate two aspects of potentially improved resilience of diversified crop rotations using a soil lysimeter facility. Firstly, we will assess how soil water retention and/or recharge in diversified vs. non-diversified annual cropping systems respond to individual rainfall events and consequently impact crop production. Secondly, we will apply winter pulse warming to simulate extreme freeze-thaw cycles and evaluate their impact on water\r\nquality and greenhouse gas emissions. With this analysis we will determine the resilience of crop production and environmental losses to current and future extreme weather events under contrasting crop rotations. \r\n","principal_investigator":"Claudia Wagner-Riddle","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9537,"title":"MSc Data Management Plan","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-26 16:57:44 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-26 17:00:43 UTC","slug":"msc-data-management-plan","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"This data management plan is for Alicia's MSc thesis, which is focused on microbial ecology. ","principal_investigator":"Alicia Halhed","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0002-7612-2405","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9538,"title":"Wing use and disuse hypothesis: the missing link to understand keel bone damage in adult laying hens","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-08-27 13:51:02 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-27 15:43:13 UTC","slug":"wing-use-and-disuse-hypothesis-the-missing-link-to-understand-keel-bone-damage-in-adult-laying-hens","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"","identifier":"UofGT2-2019-27371","description":"The locomotory abilities and musculo-skeletal characteristics of pullets and laying hens may be significantly affected by their rearing and adult housing system or lighting management.  However, whether and how the specific use (or disuse) of different muscles, muscle groups or the mechanical forces involved in different locomotory patterns lead to the biological differences observed cannot be determined simply by assessing birds in different housing or management systems. This section of the project will focus on the biomechanics and physiology of locomotion and effects of muscle use on keel bone damage in adult laying hens. Robust experimental protocols will be used to manipulate use of different muscle groups; particularly the two major muscles that control the wings (pectoralis and supracoracoideus). The overall objective of this project is to determine whether wing use/disuse leads to keel bone damage (KBD) in adulthood. To this end, the following experiments were conducted: \r\n•\tExperiments 1: testing whether pectoral and leg muscle use changes will be related to keel bone damage (KBD), and whether trained wing muscles protect laying hens from KBD.\r\n•\tExperiment 2: testing the effect of wing exercise and restraint on pectoral muscle and KBD.\r\n","principal_investigator":"Alexandra Harlander","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"aharlander@uoguelph.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9540,"title":"Cultural, biological and chemical management of downy mildew of hops","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-08-27 16:27:48 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-27 16:28:38 UTC","slug":"cultural-biological-and-chemical-management-of-downy-mildew-of-hops--2","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"UofG2015-2412","identifier":"","description":"The goal of this project is to improve management of hop downy mildew (DM) by:\r\n\r\n1. Validating existing DM forecasting models for use by Ontario hop growers. This will be achieved by:\r\na) identifying monitoring sites to record environmental data and DM incidence; and b) establishing a replicated field trial to evaluate the accuracy and efficacy of a DM model.\r\n\r\n2) Evaluating biological/organic fungicides for control of hop DM and cone diseases. This research will identify products with the potential for registration and data to support registration.\r\n\r\n3) Evaluating differences in susceptibility of DM in hop cultivars. The outcome of this work will help growers avoid planting highly susceptible cultivars.\r\n\r\n4) Test DM from Ontario hop yards for resistance to metalaxyl-M and fosetyl-AL fungicides. There have been reports of resistance to these products in the U.S. which question their future usefulness to Ontario hop growers","principal_investigator":"Katerina Jordan","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Cathy Bakker","funder_name":null},{"id":9541,"title":"Incidence, timing of infection and management of bitter rot in Ontario","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-08-27 16:29:21 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-27 16:30:45 UTC","slug":"incidence-timing-of-infection-and-management-of-bitter-rot-in-ontario","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"UofG2018-3164","identifier":"","description":"The objectives of the project are:\r\n\r\n1. Determine the incidence of bitter rot in Ontario apple orchards using both symptomatic and asymptomatic fruit samples.\r\n\r\n2. Investigate the timing of infection on apple fruits and co-relate it with weather data.\r\n\r\n3. Determine the sensitivity of Colletotrichum fioriniae isolates to pyraclostrobin and captan.\r\n\r\n4. Evaluate the efficacy of different fungicides and calcium chloride to control bitter rot, identify fungicides with the potential for registration and collect data to support registration","principal_investigator":"Katerina Jordan","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Asifa Munawar","funder_name":null},{"id":9542,"title":"Net life cycle greenhouse gas emissions of Canadian organic field crop production systems","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-27 16:54:38 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-27 16:59:22 UTC","slug":"net-life-cycle-greenhouse-gas-emissions-of-canadian-organic-field-crop-production-systems","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Given the scale and growth of organic field crop production in Canada (>300,000 ha in 2015), heterogeneity in the national distribution of production and production technologies, and the importance of their products in organic food and feed production, we will undertake robust, regionally-resolved analyses of the life cycle greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions characteristic of the 6+ major field crops typically grown in rotation. Our analyses will be based on detailed, multi-year farm-level input and yield data from commercial farms under a variety of organic management strategies, intensities and contexts. The suite of crops for which analyses will be possible will ultimately be determined by the data that become available through the participation of farmer informants and the crops they routinely grow in rotation. Based on 2012 statistics of hectarage under organic field crop production, we anticipate that analyses will be possible for the following crops: wheat, oats, barley, (possibly rye), potatoes, peas, soybeans, lentils and corn, along with rotation crops including forages and green manures. \r\n\r\nWe are attempting to address the following research questions:\r\n\r\n1) What are the net greenhouse gas emissions that result from the production of major field crops grown commercially in Canada under organic management?\r\n\r\n2) Where sufficient data exist, how do factors related to farm location, farm management practices, and farmer experience affect the greenhouse gas emissions of field crop production under organic management in Canada?\r\n\r\n\r\nThe study is, in the majority, quantitative and based on farm data, but will include some demographic data related to farmer education and experience, e.g., the number of years spent farming.\r\n\r\nWe are collecting these data to better understand the greenhouse gas emissions performance of organic farming in Canada, with a view to providing supportive strategies to farmers and policy makers.","principal_investigator":"Goretty Dias, Peter Tyedmers, Nathan Pelletier","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Ryan Johnson, (519) 216-1372, r24johns@uwaterloo.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9543,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-27 20:58:48 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-27 20:58:48 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3748","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Alecia Kallos","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9544,"title":"Production efficiencies of apple growers in the Pacific Northwest","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-08-29 00:07:36 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-29 00:20:20 UTC","slug":"production-efficiencies-of-apple-growers-in-the-pacific-northwest","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"In the 1970s, the goal for apple producers in British Columbia (B.C.) was to achieve 40 bins of apples per acre of land in order to be competitive with growers in Washington State.\r\nIn 2020, there are many examples of growers producing up to 100 bins of apples per acre, however, the average production of B.C.Tree Fruits Cooperative, which makes up 85% of producers in the province, is still just 38 bins per acre (Walker, 2017).\r\nThis has created an issue in which a large number of British Columbian apple orchards are operating at a deficit, threatening the future of the apple industry in B.C.\r\n\r\nA number of factors are known to influence apple production. These include:\r\nspring rains that limit pollination, \r\nsummer rains that contribute to disease, \r\npresence of pollinators (impacted by use of pesticides as well as natural annual population fluctuations), \r\nsummer temperatures that influence fruit ripening, \r\nlabour costs - and consequently ability to hire - associated with both pruning and thinning to maximise production, \r\nsoil types and nutrient properties, \r\nuse and type of pesticides to protect crops, \r\nage of production trees - with both young and old trees under-producing, as well as root grafts introduced to commercial production in 1997 being more disease resistant and promoting greater fruit yields, \r\nyield capacities of various cultivars, with some cultivars being more vigorous than others.\r\n\r\nThe goal of the project is to attempt to determine which of the above factors are contributing in the most significant way to lower production quantities in BC orchards. Comparative data from Washington State will be used to help identify trends. Follow up research will attempt to identify possible solutions to these factors.","principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9545,"title":"My plan (York University)","dmptemplate_id":47,"created_at":"2020-08-29 20:15:34 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-29 20:15:34 UTC","slug":"my-plan-york-university--45","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Caitlyn Seale","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9546,"title":"Student mobilization for Sustainable Development Goals implementation: a phenomenological study of student experiences with the Sustainable Development Goals Alliance","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-31 04:32:41 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-31 07:17:06 UTC","slug":"student-mobilization-for-sustainable-development-goals-implementation-a-phenomenological-study-of-student-experiences-with-the-sustainable-development-goals-alliance","organisation_id":23,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Qualitative research study exploring the experiences of students with the Sustainable Development Goals Alliance at the University of Calgary","principal_investigator":"Dr. Sarah Skett","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9547,"title":"Identifying developmental determinants of successful behavioral adaptation and musculoskeletal health of egg-laying hens","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-08-31 09:47:10 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-31 10:21:10 UTC","slug":"identifying-developmental-determinants-of-successful-behavioral-adaptation-and-musculoskeletal-health-of-egg-laying-hens","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"UofGT2-2019-27372","identifier":"","description":"The commercial success of egg laying flocks largely depends on hens’ adaptation to their housing system during lay, especially for hens in non-cage systems, where risk for injury and mortality are considerably higher compared to cage systems. The early rearing environment can affect behavioural and skeletal development with lifelong effects on the health and welfare of the hen. This project investigates if and how different rearing systems for chicks and pullets affects their behavior, musculoskeletal characteristics and keel fractures.This information that can be used to inform producers on selection of rearing aviaries and management of pullets destined for alternative housing systems.","principal_investigator":"Tina Widowski","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0003-3274-7558","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9548,"title":"Mon plan (Université de Montréal (FR))","dmptemplate_id":43,"created_at":"2020-08-31 13:16:50 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-31 13:16:50 UTC","slug":"mon-plan-universite-de-montreal-fr--111","organisation_id":32,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Stéphanie Gagnon","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9549,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-31 20:11:08 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-31 20:11:08 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3750","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Rodrigo Curty Pereira","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9550,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-31 20:32:07 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-31 20:32:07 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3751","organisation_id":23,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Radhika Joshi","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9551,"title":"Computational Ontologies Data Plan","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-08-31 20:53:35 UTC","updated_at":"2020-08-31 20:54:07 UTC","slug":"computational-ontologies-data-plan","organisation_id":23,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Kathryn Blair","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9552,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-09-01 14:20:08 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-01 14:20:08 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3753","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Mark Stoller","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9553,"title":"A Gaze Aware Video Player for Improving Video Comprehension","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-09-01 14:33:31 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-18 18:33:35 UTC","slug":"a-gaze-aware-video-player-for-improving-video-comprehension","organisation_id":48,"grant_number":"","identifier":"11041","description":"","principal_investigator":"Dr. Christopher Collins","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9554,"title":"Investigating Noise Impacts of Grain Dryers on Neighbouring Land Uses","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-09-01 19:30:37 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-02 16:51:44 UTC","slug":"investigating-noise-impacts-of-grain-dryers-on-neighbouring-land-uses","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"UG-SI-2020-100747","identifier":"UG-SI-2020-100747","description":"Grain dryers are an essential part of Ontario grain production. Dryers can produce significant dust and noise emissions. It is believed the numbers, types and usage of dryers have increased in Ontario, but no data exists. Increasing populations in some rural areas increase the potential for conflict between residential and agricultural land uses. There has been little study of grain dryer noise emissions. Information on dryers in Ontario, their usage and their noise and dust emissions, is needed by\r\noperators and policy makers to ensure needs of operators and neighbours can be met. This project will determine the types, sizes, geographic distribution and usage of grain dryers in Ontario. Sound level and particulate emissions will be systematically measured at the different types of grain drying facilities in Ontario, and best management practices will be developed for installing and operating\r\ngrain dryers to minimize noise and dust impacts on neighbours.","principal_investigator":"William Lubitz","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0003-3862-2895","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9555,"title":"Alliance Ketosis Project","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-09-01 22:03:01 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-08 20:29:25 UTC","slug":"alliance-ketosis-project","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"100116","identifier":"UG-T1-2020-100116","description":"Nature of research: ketosis in dairy cattle\r\n\r\nResearch questions: 1. herd risk factors for ketosis\r\n2. genetic markers for ketosis risk, resistance and resolution\r\n\r\n\r\n","principal_investigator":"Todd Duffield","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0001-6035-4669","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9556,"title":"My plan (University of Alberta Template)","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2020-09-02 15:58:25 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-02 15:58:25 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-alberta-template--857","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Andrew Daszczynski","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9557,"title":"Airflow patterns and animal welfare in pigs transported at different space allowances in an actively ventilated vehicle in summer and winter (University of Guelph Agri-Food Funding Template (Alliance/Food from Thought) )","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-09-02 18:24:41 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-02 18:36:44 UTC","slug":"airflow-patterns-and-animal-welfare-in-pigs-transported-at-different-space-allowances-in-an-actively-ventilated-vehicle-in-summer-and-winter-university-of-guelph-agri-food-funding-template-alliance-food-from-thought","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"UG-T1-2020-100228","identifier":"","description":"Applied research on the effect of truck type on stress and meat quality in pigs","principal_investigator":"Renee Bergeron","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0001-7757-2531","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9558,"title":"The Impact of Oral Antimicrobial Use in Calves ","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-09-02 18:59:41 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-03 17:53:52 UTC","slug":"the-impact-of-oral-antimicrobial-use-in-calves","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"","identifier":"UG-T1-2020-100297","description":"The overall objective of this project is to determine the impacts of medicated or waste milk feeding during the pre-weaning phase on gut development, function and health of dairy calves. The data generated from this project will elucidate how these common management decisions affect specific mechanisms involved in gut function and development, as well as how these mechanisms influence calf health and the development of antimicrobial resistance. This will lead to the development of knowledge-based solutions that will promote optimal calf gut development and health, while simultaneously improving the safety of food products and increasing consumer trust in the Ontario dairy sector. ","principal_investigator":"Michael Steele","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0001-6941-6205","data_contact":"masteele@uoguelph.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9559,"title":"Open Educational Resources (OER) Awareness, Perceptions, and Use at RDC","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-09-02 19:16:10 UTC","updated_at":"2021-01-19 16:09:18 UTC","slug":"open-educational-resources-oer-awareness-perceptions-and-use-at-rdc","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"This is an exploratory study jointly conducted by the OER Champion group (comprised of members from the Library and the Centre for Teaching and Learning). This group is seeking to determine faculty awareness, perceptions, and use of Open Educational Resources (OER) at RDC. \r\n\r\nThis is the first step of a multi-part project. Results from the survey conducted in this part of the study will help determine a baseline for OER use, and will inform the development of a strategy around OER at RDC. \r\n\r\nThis may lead to subsequent surveys which assess impact and measure effectiveness of initiatives and interventions. Subsequent surveys may include the original survey question set, as well as additional questions as appropriate. ","principal_investigator":"Sona Macnaughton","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0002-3311-1394","data_contact":"sona.macnuaghton@rdc.ab.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9560,"title":"JGR Planets APXS VRR data","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-09-02 20:11:21 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-02 20:18:19 UTC","slug":"jgr-planets-apxs-vrr-data","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Geochemical data used to make plots and tables in:\r\n\r\nThompson, L. M., et al. 2020. APXS-derived compositional characteristics of Vera Rubin Ridge and Murray formation, Gale crater, Mars: Geochemical implications for the origin of the ridge. Journal of Geophysical Research Planets","principal_investigator":"Lucy Thompson","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0002-5444-952X","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9561,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-09-02 21:55:07 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-02 21:55:07 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3757","organisation_id":14,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Dan Phillips","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9562,"title":"DMP Food Literacy Heuristics","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-09-03 01:31:00 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-09 22:26:49 UTC","slug":"dmp-food-literacy-heuristics","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"This study aims to understand common Food Literacy issues in current grocery shopping websites, particularly in awareness, knowledge, and skills for planning and selecting healthier food options among young adults. In this study, we will ask participants to evaluate one popular grocery shopping website using a proposed set of food literacy heuristics, identifying the types of problems these websites have that hinder food-literate purchases. \r\n\r\nThis study will provide us with critical information on Food Literacy issues in grocery shopping websites and validate a set of Food Literacy heuristics to inform designers and researchers how to evaluate and develop grocery websites to support Food Literacy.","principal_investigator":"Marcela Bomfim","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9563,"title":"My plan (Portage TemplateMechanisms of long-term consequences of transition cow biology on production and reproduction traits)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-09-04 16:49:39 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-04 17:34:26 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-templatemechanisms-of-long-term-consequences-of-transition-cow-biology-on-production-and-reproduction-traits","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"The transition period is one of the most challenging times a dairy cow will face in her life due to the immense physiological changes she will undergo while moving from a nonlactating pregnant state to a nonpregnant lactating state. These many changes leave her vulnerable to physiological imbalances and health disorders which can have negative effects on her performance for months. This research project aims to better characterize how the quality of the transition period will impact the productive and reproductive performance in the subsequent lactation and whether interventions through precision management can be developed and applied on an tailored basis to mitigate negative ramifications on health and performance.","principal_investigator":"Eduardo de Souza Ribeiro ","principal_investigator_identifier":"orcid.org/0000-0002-4201-7383","data_contact":"eribeiro@uoguelph.ca; (519) 824-4120 Ext. 56516","funder_name":null},{"id":9564,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-09-04 19:59:18 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-04 19:59:18 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3760","organisation_id":38,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"marco pellino","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9565,"title":"My plan (University of British Columbia Generic Template)","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-09-06 19:27:41 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-06 19:27:41 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-british-columbia-generic-template--583","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Matthew Evenden","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9566,"title":"Mon plan (Modèle Portage)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-09-08 14:15:12 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-08 14:15:12 UTC","slug":"mon-plan-modele-portage--553","organisation_id":44,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Hugues Sansregret","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9567,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-09-08 15:54:30 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-08 15:54:52 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3761","organisation_id":9,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Josée Benoît","principal_investigator_identifier":"Jacinthe Savard","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9568,"title":"Hybridization of artificial intelligence and mechanistic models to create 'intelligent' precision nutrition models for next generation dairy production","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-09-08 17:59:52 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-08 18:49:06 UTC","slug":"hybridization-of-artificial-intelligence-and-mechanistic-models-to-create-intelligent-precision-nutrition-models-for-next-generation-dairy-production","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"030550","identifier":"Model Hybridization - OMAFRA Alliance Project","description":"The development of 'explainable AI' represents the 'bleeding edge' of data science research. While AI methods demonstrate impressive ability to make predictions, their shortfall is in their lack of transparency and ability to explain those prediction. Mechanistic models (MM), on the other hand, are based on causal pathway analysis. These models may be applied to optimize performance and understand causality, but tend to be user demanding. The objective of this research proposal is to examine means to hybridize these two seemingly divergent methodologies to create 'explainable AI', in order to advance the models we use in animal production, and support movement towards truly knowledge-based precision agriculture. The anticipated outcome is the development of an intelligent (based in biology) and optimizable precision nutrition ML based systems for animal production, in order to reduce the environmental impact of farming and improve both the financial and environmental sustainability of animal production systems.\r\n\r\nThis project will largely utilize existing data from two sources (1) Trouw Nutrition (project partner), and (2) Dr Christine Baes (Dept of Animal Biosciences). New data generated will focus around model predictions and outcomes of model simulations.","principal_investigator":"Jennifer Ellis","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000000306419622","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9570,"title":"My plan (Université de Montréal)","dmptemplate_id":43,"created_at":"2020-09-09 19:03:06 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-09 19:03:06 UTC","slug":"my-plan-universite-de-montreal--21","organisation_id":32,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Eve Paquette-Bigras","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9571,"title":"The First Three Years","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2020-09-09 22:36:20 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-14 04:10:22 UTC","slug":"the-first-three-years","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":"435-2020-1064","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Sean Gouglas; Suzanne de Castell; Jennifer Jenson; Johanna Weststar; Jennifer Whitson","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Kenzie Gordon, 780-937-5855, mlgordon@ualberta.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9572,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-09-09 22:53:56 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-09 22:53:56 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3763","organisation_id":23,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Elise Fear","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9573,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-09-10 04:14:28 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-10 04:14:28 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3764","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Justin Robinson","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9574,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-09-10 13:07:51 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-10 13:07:51 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3765","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Stephanie Mutch","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9575,"title":"Breeding of high yielding, disease resistant & value-added soybean using elite and exotic germplasm","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-09-10 15:37:35 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-30 23:17:10 UTC","slug":"breeding-of-high-yielding-disease-resistant-value-added-soybean-using-elite-and-exotic-germplasm","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"UofGT2-2018-27353","identifier":"","description":"The short description of the project above is as follows:\r\nThis project is aimed at continuing to develop outstanding non-GM food grade varieties for Canadian farmers with the following objectives: \r\n\r\n1) Enhance yield of Ontario non-GM food grade soybean by incorporating new alleles from elite Canadian and exotic sources such as the elite and modern Chinese varieties using molecular breeding and genomic tools. The benefit to producers is expected to come from using novel alleles (gene versions) coming from Chinese germplasm to break yield barriers further. \r\n2) Enhance value and market opportunities of soybeans for value-added markets, including developing food grade lines with improved tofu and soymilk properties, higher sucrose content, saponin, isoflavones, and modified oil profiles for the healthy foods and bio-products markets. This will benefit the competitiveness of the Canadian soybean industry by providing novelty in the world soybean markets. \r\n3) Improve genetic resistance to soybean cyst nematode (SCN) using new SCN resistance sources, beyond the common one, PI88788, to develop food grade soybeans in the mid- to short-season maturity groups, i.e., MG 1, 0 and 00, where it is currently lacking as the disease keeps spreading.\r\n4) Improve resistance to white mould, or Sclerotinia stem rot, in soybean using genomic approaches.\r\n\r\nThe purpose of collecting the data is to have the result from research that addresses the above objectives. This in turn will allow us to make decision regarding the direction of the soybean breeding program, provide data for graduate students as they work on their theses and use data for research publications. ","principal_investigator":"Istvan Rajcan","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Same as above. ","funder_name":null},{"id":9576,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-09-10 15:48:33 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-10 15:48:33 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3766","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Victoria Smith","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9577,"title":"My plan (Dalhousie University Generic Plan)","dmptemplate_id":56,"created_at":"2020-09-10 16:51:03 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-10 16:51:03 UTC","slug":"my-plan-dalhousie-university-generic-plan--26","organisation_id":15,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Sharon Oldford","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9578,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-09-10 16:52:32 UTC","updated_at":"2020-09-10 16:52:32 UTC","slug":"my-plan-