\r\n\r\nThe discovery cohort is 10 AF samples taken from CBGS or similar surgeries.\r\n\r\nDetails in OSF https://osf.io/rnw2v/ (not public access)","principal_investigator":"Zachary Laksman","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"jeremy.parker@ubc.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9671,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-10-09 00:58:55 UTC","updated_at":"2020-10-09 00:58:55 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3812","organisation_id":20,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Laurence Horton","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9672,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-10-09 13:38:52 UTC","updated_at":"2020-10-09 13:40:47 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3813","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"This is a sample plan based on the NRC data management plan template.","principal_investigator":"Tobias Spears","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9673,"title":"Honours Data Management","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-10-09 13:59:22 UTC","updated_at":"2020-10-09 14:05:13 UTC","slug":"honours-data-management","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"This research will investigate the impact of racial stressors on ACC functioning. It will aslo explore how two different approaches to racial socialization (legacy vs literacy) moderate the stress response. Nativity status will also be explored as a potential moderator. The purpose of this research is to uncover the impact of race-based stress on Canadian students and how potential protective factors may be applied to buffer the cognitive impact of racial stress. ","principal_investigator":"Noémie Bergeron","principal_investigator_identifier":"Dr Christine Lackner","data_contact":"christine.lackner@msvu.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9674,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-10-09 14:18:46 UTC","updated_at":"2020-10-09 14:18:46 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3815","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Trent Johnson","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9675,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-10-09 14:45:43 UTC","updated_at":"2020-10-09 14:45:43 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3816","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9676,"title":"My plan (University of Manitoba )","dmptemplate_id":35,"created_at":"2020-10-09 18:12:10 UTC","updated_at":"2020-10-09 18:12:10 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-manitoba--67","organisation_id":37,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9677,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-10-09 21:03:24 UTC","updated_at":"2020-10-09 21:03:24 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3817","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9678,"title":"My plan (University of British Columbia Generic Template)","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-10-09 22:55:52 UTC","updated_at":"2020-10-09 22:55:52 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-british-columbia-generic-template--601","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Kevin  Lindstrom","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9679,"title":"Doing things differently: An atlas of best practices and opportunities for culturally acceptable and sustainable living environments in Nunavik","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-10-11 03:52:50 UTC","updated_at":"2020-10-11 04:00:11 UTC","slug":"doing-things-differently-an-atlas-of-best-practices-and-opportunities-for-culturally-acceptable-and-sustainable-living-environments-in-nunavik","organisation_id":44,"grant_number":"124804","identifier":"124804","description":"Les communautés inuit du Nunavik font face à des défis urgents en matière de logement, de développement et de changements climatiques et, à cet égard, les maisons et les villages qu’ils habitent ne sont pas durables. Ils sont planifiés selon des modèles du Sud, mal adaptés au Nord, et leur développement trop rapide ne permet pas d’imaginer des solutions mieux adaptées aux ressources et au climat du Nunavik. Il est largement reconnu que ces environnements ne répondent pas à leurs aspirations. Il est urgent de modifier le paradigme de développement actuel (basé sur l'agenda économique) en un processus durable (basé sur l'agenda social et la qualité de la conception) afin de mieux prendre en compte les conditions locales et la culture inuit. En proposant de « faire les choses différemment », le projet s’appuie sur la participation des Inuit et sur l’expérience d’une équipe multidisciplinaire et combine des dimensions liées aux infrastructures / urbanisation et à l'environnement social. Plus important encore, il prend en compte la qualité et l’humanité des lieux d’habitation, car ils ont un impact sur le bien-être et la santé des résidents. Le projet invite diverses disciplines, ainsi que les communautés inuit, à relever le défi des milieux de vie culturellement appropriés, sécuritaires et résilients. Il aborde deux questions de recherche: 1) Quelles sont les meilleures opportunités pour développer des milieux de vie durables et adaptés à la culture? 2) Quels sont les actions les plus utiles qui permettraient de tels développements, et comment pourraient-elles être transformées en outils pragmatiques et conviviaux pour l’engagement communautaire et la prise de décisions? L'équipe s'attaquera à ces questions en concevant collectivement un atlas des meilleures pratiques et opportunités, soit un répertoire de modèles, d'actions et de politiques proposant des scénarios alternatifs pour des milieux de vie durables et culturellement adaptés.","principal_investigator":"Geneviève Vachon","principal_investigator_identifier":"000-0003-4409-9922","data_contact":"Samuel Boudreault","funder_name":null},{"id":9680,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-10-12 21:39:53 UTC","updated_at":"2020-10-12 21:39:53 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3818","organisation_id":20,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Saman Goudarzi","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9681,"title":"TLR2 Milk Cytokine","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-10-13 14:02:39 UTC","updated_at":"2020-10-13 14:05:04 UTC","slug":"tlr2-milk-cytokine","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Allergies are rooted in early life, resulting from the dysregulation of local or systemic\r\nimmunity. While some immunological problems are dependent on genetic predisposition, there is\r\nsubstantial evidence that nutritional and environmental factors are also critical for disease development. A\r\nclear example of this is the influence of early diet, including breastfeeding and the timing of introduction to\r\nallergenic foods, on the development of food allergy and other allergic diseases. Recent evidence suggests\r\nthat earlier introduction to allergenic foods may be beneficial; however, studies to date have not typically\r\naccounted for breastfeeding status at the time of allergenic food introduction. This may be important\r\nbecause breastmilk provides numerous bioactive and immunomodulatory factors (many of which are absent\r\nfrom infant formula) that may contribute to the development of oral tolerance when new foods are\r\nintroduced. Understanding how breast milk and infant feeding practices influence immune system\r\ndevelopment and allergic sensitization could provide important opportunities for disease\r\nprevention.\r\n\r\nWe will measure key immune modulators (sTLR2, microbiota, cytokines) in breast milk samples\r\nfrom the national CHILD birth cohort using a combination of multiplex protein assays, ELISA techniques,\r\nbioassays, and next generation sequencing, and evaluate associations with food sensitization (positive skin\r\ntests to common food allergens) and allergic disease (diagnosed asthma, food allergy, or atopic dermatitis)\r\nassessed at ages 1, 3, 5 and 8 years in the CHILD cohort.\r\n\r\n","principal_investigator":"Stephanie Goguen","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9682,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-10-13 14:10:08 UTC","updated_at":"2020-10-13 14:10:08 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3820","organisation_id":48,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Joshua Wyman","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9683,"title":"My plan (University of British Columbia Generic Template)","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-10-13 16:21:04 UTC","updated_at":"2020-10-13 16:21:04 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-british-columbia-generic-template--602","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Sahar Ahmadvand","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9684,"title":"My plan (UVic DMP Template)","dmptemplate_id":44,"created_at":"2020-10-13 17:27:19 UTC","updated_at":"2020-10-13 17:27:19 UTC","slug":"my-plan-uvic-dmp-template--