e Role of Post-Secondary Experiences in Rural Students’ Attitudes Toward Cultural Diversity and Place-Based Identities","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-10-17 02:11:50 UTC","updated_at":"2020-10-17 02:41:38 UTC","slug":"the-role-of-post-secondary-experiences-in-rural-students-attitudes-toward-cultural-diversity-and-place-based-identities","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"The proposed qualitative study aims to contribute to a better understanding of the ways post-secondary education, defined in terms of its capacity to provide exposure to both cultural diversity, and global/multicultural modes of thinking, interacts with place-based identity, particularly in the lives of rural Canadian students. Special attention will be paid to how factors such as contact with a diverse student body, exposure to internationalizing institutional practices, and classrooms characterized by diversity-informed curricular and pedagogical elements factor into how both rural and international students experience the post-secondary environment in relation to their identities and attitudes. \r\n   Given the context of a multicultural Canada, exploration into the ways diverse identities interact with one another and their environment is likely to provide useful insight for educators, administrators, employers, and others overseeing diverse groups in navigating potential identity-based conflicts, encouraging cultural acceptance, and fostering sensitive yet personally challenging classroom, institutional, and workplace environments. This is especially true in relation to rurality, which can often be overlooked as a source of personal identity and potential source of inter-group conflict. \r\n\r\nResearch Questions: \r\n1.\tHow do rural-identifying students understand themselves and how does this understanding shape their experiences within culturally diverse institutions?\r\n2.\tWhat aspects of students’ experiences (cultural exposure, curricular elemen