rence-for-transit-integrated-ridesourcing-models-in-northwest-waterloo-ontario","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":"","identifier":"42587","description":"This research studies the stated preferences of participants in northwest Waterloo, Ontario for a series of transportation modes to determine their preference toward transit-integrated ridesourcing, specifically, and how it competes with or complements other travel options.","principal_investigator":"Chris Bachmann","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Jacob Terry, jacob.terry@uwaterloo.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9803,"title":"Plan for 690","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-01 20:02:36 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-01 20:06:27 UTC","slug":"plan-for-690","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":"","identifier":"20870071","description":"To investigate brain damage in darter species found in the Grand River following exposure to pharmaceuticals in the wastewater. \r\nResearch question: What is the impact of effluent exposure on three darter species from clean and contaminated sites along the Grand River? Are there neurodegenerative effects such as increased ROS enzymes, damage or changes in specific transcript markers?\r\nExamine the consequence of acute exposure to pharmaceutical combined concentrations of VFX and CBZ in lab using environmentally relevant concentrations (control, 1 ug/L, and 10 ug/L) on three darter species.\r\n\r\nFish will be collected and their brains will be used for gene and enzyme analysis. \r\nThe second part, fish will be exposed to known concentrations of pharmaceuticals and stained with BrdU to examine proliferation (brain damage). ","principal_investigator":"Nicole Gauvreau","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"647-860-0413, ngauvrea@uwaterloo.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9804,"title":"Mapping and Mitigating Microplastics in Built Environmentsplan (University of Alberta Template)","dmptemplate_id":1,"created_at":"2020-11-02 04:20:47 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-02 17:58:39 UTC","slug":"mapping-and-mitigating-microplastics-in-built-environmentsplan-university-of-alberta-template","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Yang Liu","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"yang.liu@ualberta.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9805,"title":"Information Needs of Undergraduate Nursing Students","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-02 14:57:49 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-03 19:37:35 UTC","slug":"information-needs-of-undergraduate-nursing-students","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Kristy Hancock","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9806,"title":"Mon plan (Modèle Portage)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-02 16:11:28 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-02 16:11:28 UTC","slug":"mon-plan-modele-portage--568","organisation_id":42,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Catherine Leduc","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9807,"title":"Test de validation (Modèle Portage) / institution UQTR","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-02 16:11:41 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-02 17:10:31 UTC","slug":"test-de-validation-modele-portage-institution-uqtr","organisation_id":42,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Validation Assistant PGD 2.0 - Français\r\n\r\nAncien PDG toujours accessible /\r\n\r\nDirectives UQTR pas visibles , il faudra  modifier les liens au nouveau site dans les directives UQTR - voir annotation des questions/\r\n","principal_investigator":"Catherine Leduc","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9808,"title":"Mon plan (Modèle Portage)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-02 16:57:17 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-02 16:57:17 UTC","slug":"mon-plan-modele-portage--570","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Caroline Patenaude","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9810,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-02 17:43:15 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-02 17:43:15 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3869","organisation_id":33,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Laura Ryan","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9812,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 11:53:46 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-03 11:53:46 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3870","organisation_id":20,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Mohammad Reza Rezaei","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9813,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 12:54:37 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-03 12:54:37 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3871","organisation_id":55,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Heather Whipple","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9814,"title":"Blablabla","dmptemplate_id":43,"created_at":"2020-11-03 14:04:37 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-03 14:04:50 UTC","slug":"blablabla","organisation_id":32,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Lyne Da Sylva","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9815,"title":"Mon plan (Modèle Portage)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 14:15:38 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-03 14:15:38 UTC","slug":"mon-plan-modele-portage--571","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Brendan Fitzgibbon","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9817,"title":"petit groupe","dmptemplate_id":43,"created_at":"2020-11-03 14:22:55 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-03 14:23:06 UTC","slug":"petit-groupe","organisation_id":32,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"coralie b-c","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9818,"title":"blindfold research","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-11-03 15:01:48 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-03 15:06:32 UTC","slug":"blindfold-research","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"CCSAW","identifier":"","description":"The aim of the study is to determine the effect of placing a blindfold on a horse and navigating obstacles by both an experienced and inexperienced horse handler in both stressful and non-stressful situations.\r\n\r\nObjectives:\r\n1.\tTo determine a baseline of how long it takes to place a blindfold on a horse by an experienced or inexperienced horse handler\r\n2.\tTo measure the effect of blindfolding horses under various conditions on their ease of handling and stress reaction\r\n\r\nHypotheses: \r\n1.\tIt will take longer for an inexperienced horse handler to place a blindfold on a horse and lead it out of its stall.\r\n2.\tHorses that are blindfolded will take longer to navigate various obstacles, require more negative reinforcement from the handler, and show an increase in the frequency of stress behaviours and heart rate. More specifically:\r\n    a.\tA wet blindfold will increase the time needed to place the blindfold on the horse and navigate through obstacles compared to a dry blindfold\r\n    b.\tStressful scenario (firefighter attire) will increase the time needed to place the blindfold on the horse and navigate through obstacles compared to non-stressful scenarios\r\n","principal_investigator":"katrina merkies","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9819,"title":"Bacterial communities impact on formation and bioaccumulation of methylmercury (MeHg) in prairie environments","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 15:42:30 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-08 19:15:05 UTC","slug":"bacterial-communities-impact-on-formation-and-bioaccumulation-of-methylmercury-mehg-in-prairie-environments","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"","identifier":"200456472","description":"- Nature of the research: \r\nBiogeochemistry\r\n---\r\nMethylmercury (MeHg) is one the most neurologically toxic among all the mercury species. This compound is produced when mercury element has been added to one methyl group. This process used to believe a non-enzymatic reaction and it was thought to be a secondary product. Recently a pair of genes has been discovered that show an active process of Methylmercury production. These genes are HgcA and HgcB (HgcAB for short). My project will focus on the benefit of this compound for the bacterial community. \r\n---\r\n\r\n- Main question:\r\nWhat is the benefit of methylmercury (MeHg) production for bacteria?\r\nSub questions:\r\n1- Study the bacterial community in Prairie's wetlands to know the components of each community and their possible impact on MeHg production \r\n2- Study the geological history of earth for the past 3 billion years to find the pressure point that caused HgcAB genes to emerged\r\n3- Study the nature of HgcAB genes and their regulators and promoters and environmental impacts on them.\r\n\r\n---\r\nData collection purpose: \r\nTwo types of samples from the field will be collected every two weeks over the whole summer season from Saskatchewan Prairie Wetlands:\r\n1- Water samples\r\n2- Soil samples \r\nEach sample will be taken from different depth of water/soil and everything will be recorded on a .cvs file. \r\nAlong with the samples, one photo from each pond on every visit will be taken along with other information like geographical coordinates, data and time, temperature and weather condition. \r\nphotos will be save as .jpg and other information on the form of .cvs anf.txt format.\r\n\r\n","principal_investigator":"Zohra Zahir","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0001-5278-1257","data_contact":"zohrazahir@uregina.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9820,"title":"My plan (York University)","dmptemplate_id":47,"created_at":"2020-11-03 16:05:59 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-03 16:05:59 UTC","slug":"my-plan-york-university--48","organisation_id":45,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Minglu Wang","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9821,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 17:35:34 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-03 17:35:34 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3873","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Heather Whipple","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9822,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 17:39:48 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-03 17:39:48 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3874","organisation_id":55,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Shona Mills","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9823,"title":"Phaeomoniella chlamydospora as a latent pathogen","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:13:38 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-01 23:19:52 UTC","slug":"phaeomoniella-chlamydospora-as-a-latent-pathogen","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"N/A","identifier":"0000-0001-5593-8010","description":"Petri disease is a grapevine trunk disease primarily caused by Phaeomoniella chlamydospora. It has been widely speculated that P. chlamydospora is a latent pathogen, remaining asymptomatic until something triggers the pathogenic phase. The main triggers for this transition from latent to pathogenic phase are hypothesized to be abiotic and biotic stress on the grapevine. My questions are: 1. Does abiotic stress (drought stress) impact disease development and symptom expression in young merlot grapevines infected with P. chlamydospora? 2. Does biotic stress (ring nematode infestation of roots) impact disease development and symptom expression in young merlot grapevines infected with P. chlamydospora? 3. Does the application of commercial arbuscular mycorrhizal fungi (AMF) fertilizer to the roots reduce disease development and symptom expression through the ability of AMF to reduce plant stress?\r\nThese grapevines will be placed in a greenhouse for up to two growing seasons, and leaf and shoot dry weight will be collected. Internal trunk necrosis and pathogen quantity (with the use of droplet digital PCR) will be used to measure symptom severity across treatments. This data may be used to help grape-growers reduce the impact of disease in vineyards.","principal_investigator":"Jose Ramon Urbez-Torres","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/my-orcid?justRegistered","data_contact":"Jared Hrycan - jared.hrycan@gmail.com","funder_name":null},{"id":9824,"title":"Genetic determinants of antimicrobial resistance gene persistence in aquatic environments","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:14:09 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-01 21:19:21 UTC","slug":"genetic-determinants-of-antimicrobial-resistance-gene-persistence-in-aquatic-environments","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"The goal of this research project is to determine which genes co-localize with antimicrobial resistance genes and may contribute to enhancing their transmission via plasmids. Bacterial DNA was collected from farm ponds across Saskatchewan, Canada and sequenced to identify antimicrobial resistance genes and their genomic context. This data is being collected to generate a reference library of plasmid-borne gene modules and will begin to map associations between antimicrobial resistance genes, plasmid types, and environmental metadata.","principal_investigator":"Nicole Lerminiaux","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0001-7914-9198","data_contact":"lerminin@uregina.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9825,"title":"Saskatchewan bumble bee occurrence, pathogen prevalence and characterization of gut microbial communities","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:14:22 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-04 21:21:16 UTC","slug":"saskatchewan-bumble-bee-occurrence-pathogen-prevalence-and-characterization-of-gut-microbial-communities","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"","identifier":"200254318","description":"My research project will be looking at various aspects of bumble bee health including bumble bee species occurrence , pathogen prevalence, and characterization of the microbial community compositions of bumble bee guts. Bumble bee occurrence data will be generated using field caught specimens from blue vane traps. Pathogen prevalence will be determined using polymerase chain reactions (PCR). Microbial community composition will be determined by sequencing conserved gene regions (16SrRNA for bacteria and ITS for fungal) using the Illumina MiSeq platform. The aim of this project is to determine if there are relationships between site types (park vs non-park), pathogen presence and microbial community composition of Saskatchewan bumble bees.   ","principal_investigator":"Andrew D.S. Cameron","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0003-1560-8572","data_contact":"Kirsten Palmier (palmieki@uregina.ca)","funder_name":null},{"id":9826,"title":"Evolution and ecological implications of mixed species grouping behavior in terrestrial birds","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:20:42 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-11 08:20:13 UTC","slug":"evolution-and-ecological-implications-of-mixed-species-grouping-behavior-in-terrestrial-birds","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"This is a doctoral Research Project from the Zoology department and Biodiversity Research Center at the University of British Columbia. In this thesis I aim to expand our understanding of group-living behavior in tropical bird communities, using heterospecific groups of birds (mixed-species flocks) as a study system.\r\nMixed-species flocks of birds are found in most terrestrial habitats worldwide. They occur in temperate, subtropical and tropical latitudes from forest to grasslands, at low and high elevations. In many parts of the world, flocks are seasonal associations though in at least some tropical areas, species participate in flocks year-round. Given the broad distribution, prevalence and pervasiveness of mixed-species flocks, they are now being recognized as an important feature of bird communities.\r\nHowever, only a few studies have explored the prevalence of mixed-species flocking behaviour across terrestrial birds, and hypotheses regarding the evolutionary history, ancestry and phylogenetic relationships of flock participants at a global scale have rarely been tested. It is yet unclear whether evolutionary history, in addition to, or instead of, other factors predict the participation of bird species in mixed-species flocks at a global scale. Theory on facilitative interactions among species predicts that association of species in mixed flocks should be more frequent between taxonomically distant species with dissimilar body sizes, which also differ ecologically, as birds with different phylogenetic histories and body sizes are less likely to have resources-related conflicts. The more dissimilar a flock partner is, less is the cost of competition expected, but also less relevant is the information transmitted. However, studies examining assembly rules in mixed-species flocks found that congeners and phenotypically similar species are more likely to associate than expected by chance. \r\nIn this study we examined phylogenetic patterns of interspecific flocking behavior across species of terrestrial birds, using a comprehensive molecular phylogeny. By integrating information on mixed-species flock participation with phylogenetic relationships among species, we explore the ancestry of flocking behavior and tested if mixed flocking behavior evolve many times in parallel or is it phylogenetically conserved, and the tendency of this behavior to be lost or gained across the phylogeny.\r\n\r\n ","principal_investigator":"Jenny  Munoz ORCID 0000-0001-8602-4350","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"e-mail jen.munnoz@gmail.com","funder_name":null},{"id":9827,"title":"DMP for graduate thesis - \"Movement patterns and energetics in two ecotypes of woodland caribou\"","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:32:20 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-04 19:47:34 UTC","slug":"dmp-for-graduate-thesis-movement-patterns-and-energetics-in-two-ecotypes-of-woodland-caribou","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"This graduate thesis project focuses on the diversity of movement patterns and behavioural strategies of woodland caribou (Rangifer tarandus caribou) across Ontario. Effective wildlife management and policy implementation requires accurate and precise knowledge of the behaviours of the species in question. Current knowledge of woodland caribou movement includes primary threats and environmental drivers of movement, but does not entirely account for regional variation. In this study, landcover and habitat data from the James Bay area in Northern Ontario will be collected and compared against caribou gps and energetic data, with the purpose of identifying regional differences in movement and behaviour patterns in response to environmental stimuli. The data will be used to create a movement model that will predict caribou movement in relation to their environment, and this model will subsequently be used to examine how changes in the environment may differentially impact caribou from different ecotypes.","principal_investigator":"Alexis Pereira","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0002-6273-964X","data_contact":"Email: aperei13@uoguelph.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9828,"title":" Greenhouse gas (carbon dioxide, methane, and nitrous oxide) magnitude and controls from natural and constructed agricultural waterbodies on the northern Great Plains","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:42:32 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-03 03:00:41 UTC","slug":"greenhouse-gas-carbon-dioxide-methane-and-nitrous-oxide-magnitude-and-controls-from-natural-and-constructed-agricultural-waterbodies-on-the-northern-great-plains","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"This project examines greenhouse gas (GHG) concentration and flux, and the driving factors in agricultural reservoirs and natural wetland ponds of the northern Great Plains in Canada.\r\n\r\nThis research project aims to answer: what are the daily and seasonal trends and controls in carbon dioxide, methane and nitrous oxide concentration and flux in agricultural reservoirs? Are the concentrations and controls of carbon dioxide, methane, and nitrous oxide the same between natural wetland ponds and agricultural reservoirs? The data collected is from two years of field studies, the first year sampled 20 agricultural reservoirs multiple times seasonally for GHG concentrations and water quality and 4 agricultural reservoirs sampled intensively for GHG concentrations and water quality for 24 hours, and the second year sampled 20 agricultural reservoirs and 20 natural wetland ponds, where each reservoir is paired to a wetland in close proximity, these paired sites were each sampled once. ","principal_investigator":"Sydney Jensen","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0001-6671-2172","data_contact":"sae442@uregina.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9829,"title":"Eelgrass diatom and bacterial community DNA sequecing and scanning electron microscopy","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:42:32 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-03 17:35:34 UTC","slug":"eelgrass-diatom-and-bacterial-community-dna-sequecing-and-scanning-electron-microscopy","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"NA","identifier":"doi_of_paper","description":"This research project aims to describe the structure and composition of the diatoms and bacterial communities found on eelgrass leaves in Montague Harbour, BC, Canada. We will collect eelgrass leaves (the 2nd leaf) every week during the 2020 spring diatom bloom. When the bloom occurs is variable from year to year, but we expect it sometime between February and May. The collected eelgrass leaves will either be prepared for scanning electron microscopy (SEM) or be swabbed to extract epiphyte DNA. DNA libraries for diatom and bacteria will be prepared and sent for illumina sequencing. The diatom sequencing reads will be used both to validate visual identification of species from SEM experiment and to build a phylogenetic tree, whereas the bacterial sequences will only be used to build a phylogenetic tree. These phylogenetic trees can then be used to learn about other aspects of the microbial community, such as identifying the eelgrass core microbiota, which is a sub-aim of the project. \r\n\r\nThis project is for Biol 548U Scientific Data Management for ecology and evolution (2020). This template will focus on eelgrass (Zostera marina) data collection but will be similar to other data management plans. The data are being collected by myself (Siobhan Schenk) and in partnership with the Institute for Multidisciplinary Ecological Research in the Salish Sea (IMERSS), and the University of Victoria with the goal of describing the bacterial and diatom community on eelgrass in Montague Bay (Galliano Island, BC, Canada). \r\n\r\nData produced: DNA sequences and SEM images\r\n","principal_investigator":"Siobhan Schenk","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0572-9303","data_contact":"sschenk@student.ubc.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9830,"title":"Extent to which grazing management of planted grasslands can improve habitat suitability for grassland birds.","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:42:35 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-10 20:23:04 UTC","slug":"extent-to-which-grazing-management-of-planted-grasslands-can-improve-habitat-suitability-for-grassland-birds","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Temperate grasslands across the globe are threatened by increased conversion to agriculture and increased intensification of agriculture. As a result, grassland birds are experiencing steep population declines. Many native grasslands have been planted with tame grasses to support livestock production. Although some grassland birds will use these planted grasslands, there is evidence that these fields are actually populations sinks for these species. The problem seems to be that when they are treated with management by mowing (for hay) the vegetation grows too tall and dense and results in the birds abandoning territory and forgoing breeding. I am hypothesizing that grazing will maintain the habitat structure, across the breeding season, more similar to the structure at the beginning of the breeding season. To test my hypothesis I will divide multiple pastures into 2 equal parts. One half will be treated with grazing for the whole breeding season, and the other half will be treated with mowing, at the end of the breeding season. I will capture and individually mark Sprague's pipits and Savannah sparrows in each treatment type. I will monitor their abundance and persistence across the breeding season.. If my hypothesis is supported, I would expect a grassland specialist (Sprague's pipit) to decline at a steeper rate on pastures treated with mowing compared to pastures treated with grazing. Grassland generalists (Savannah sparrow) will decline at a similar rate across all treatment types. I will also sample vegetative characteristics at locations used by birds and random locations not used by birds in order to determine a preferred habitat structure.","principal_investigator":"Kelsey Bell","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0003-3213-1737","data_contact":"kelseydbell@uregina.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9831,"title":"My plan (University of Guelph Agri-Food Funding Template (Alliance/Food from Thought) )","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:42:59 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-03 19:42:59 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-guelph-agri-food-funding-template-alliance-food-from-thought--213","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Alexis Pereira","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9832,"title":"Data management plan for meta-analysis of the relative impact of top-down and bottom-up regulation on coral-algal interactions inside a benthic coral reef community","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:43:02 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-30 20:32:49 UTC","slug":"data-management-plan-for-meta-analysis-of-the-relative-impact-of-top-down-and-bottom-up-regulation-on-coral-algal-interactions-inside-a-benthic-coral-reef-community","organisation_id":13,"grant_number":"","identifier":"260667154","description":"This research project will explore the relative impact of top-down and bottom-up regulation on coral-algal interactions inside a Caribbean benthic coral reef community through a meta-analysis. \r\nThis meta-analysis will be based on previous meta-analyses conducted by Burkepile and Hay 2006 (Herbivore vs. Nutrient control of Marine Primary Producers: Context-dependent Effects). Their findings showed that herbivores always had stronger effects than nutrient enrichment, which  indicates that herbivory has a larger impact on eutrophication in driving the phase shift from coral- to macroalgal-dominated reefs. What I plan on changing from this meta-analysis is that I will not only be focusing on the primary producers but will also be measuring community responses of corals and grazers in a variety of metrics. I also plan on focusing on grazer dynamics and responses\r\nI plan on using a Linear Mixed Effects model (LMM) to determine the effect of herbivory across two response variables: algal growth and coral growth. The fixed effects across all studies will be herbivory, algal growth and coral growth.\r\n\r\nResearch questions: \r\n1) What is the relative influence of consumers (top-down) vs. resources (bottom-up) in controlling community composition, structure and function?\r\n2) Is top-down herbivory enough to control for macroalgal growth in coral reef communities?","principal_investigator":"Alexandra McCallum","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0003-2509-2522","data_contact":"alexandra.mccallum@mail.mcgill.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9833,"title":"Data Management Plan for paleoenvironmental reconstruction of Deep Lake, SK through diatom enumeration and geochemical composition","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:44:18 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-09 15:45:35 UTC","slug":"data-management-plan-for-paleoenvironmental-reconstruction-of-deep-lake-sk-through-diatom-enumeration-and-geochemical-composition","organisation_id":38,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Closed basin lakes in the Canadian Prairies act as prominent archives for reconstructing the environment on decadal to millennial scales throughout the Holocene, 12,000 years Before Present. Extreme climatic conditions have existed across the prairies since the deglaciation of the Laurentide Ice Sheet and are expected to exist in the future under the onset of anthropogenic climate change. Since freshwater reservoirs are vital for the socio-economic development in the region, it is important to understand the baseline and threshold of the lakes’ natural systems under extreme dry of pluvial conditions that are yet to be recorded in the instrumental record. The first paleoenvironmental reconstruction of Deep Lake, SK will provide insight on the forcings and feedback mechanisms of the environment and the associated watershed in the Qu’Appelle basin under such extreme conditions. By analyzing the paleo-proxies of diatoms, pollen, mineralogical composition, sedimentary structures, isotope and geochemical composition of the lake sediment, the changes in water level, salinity, chemistry, vegetative cover, and primary productivity in the lake can the modelled. The model of the lake’s ancient history with a supplementation of instrumental records will elucidate the changes in the lake that may be expected in the future. The research will seek to provide insight of drastic hydrological and biological changes that policy-makers and stake holders may expect in the future.","principal_investigator":"Yevgeniy Kistanov","principal_investigator_identifier":" ORCID https://orcid.org/0000-0003-1547-448X","data_contact":"jenyakistanov@uregina.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9834,"title":"Microbial community assembly along a terrestrial-aquatic continuum","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:45:55 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-03 22:35:10 UTC","slug":"microbial-community-assembly-along-a-terrestrial-aquatic-continuum","organisation_id":29,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"The project focuses on microbial community assembly along a terrestrial-aquatic continuum using the Romaine river watershed located in North-Eastern Quebec as an empirical example.\r\n\r\nThe main research question is how terrestrial leaching can affect microbial community composition and how the aquatic community changes along an aquatic continuum from headwater streams, along the river until the estuary. The main variables taken for this project are DNA and RNA samples to distinguish the active from the dead and dormant taxa in the community.","principal_investigator":"Masumi Stadler","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0001-5048-8436","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9835,"title":"Impact of functional dispersal diversity on metacommunity resilience","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:46:02 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-01 18:35:37 UTC","slug":"impact-of-functional-dispersal-diversity-on-metacommunity-resilience","organisation_id":12,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"This project is a data aggregation of dispersal traits and their associated rates of dispersal of  two marine metacommunities.\r\n\r\nVariation in dispersal rates among species can play a key role in increasing the stability and resilience of a community through maintaining asynchronous population dynamics. Differences among dispersal traits can increase local and regional biodiversity, adding to functional redundancy and subsequently maintaining ecological resilience. As dispersal is critical for community resilience and response, my objective is to investigate how variation in dispersal diversity enhances a community’s resilience to climate change. I plan on quantifying the functional diversity of dispersal traits in two large-scale marine systems: the Gulf of the Saint Lawrence and the Newfoundland and Labrador Shelves. Dispersal traits will be quantified by how they facilitate spatial interactions within local and regional communities. I hypothesize that dispersal diversity should correlate with metacommunity resilience. This increased resilience should be reflected in the metacommunity’s ability to deal with the onset of climate change. This research has the potential to enable quantitative predictive modeling of metacommunity response to climate change.","principal_investigator":"Danielle Mac Rae","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"daniellembmacrae@gmail.com","funder_name":null},{"id":9836,"title":"Nutrient and microorganisms dynamics in the aquatic system of tank bromeliads","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:46:19 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-03 21:59:41 UTC","slug":"nutrient-and-microorganisms-dynamics-in-the-aquatic-system-of-tank-bromeliads","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"NA","identifier":"NA","description":"Epiphytic tank bromeliads common wild and ornamental plants that allow experimental investigation of these relationships, and the consequences for higher trophic levels. Bromeliads form a rosette with their leaves, where water accumulates, hosting a rich community of micro- and macro-organisms. It is generally accepted that epiphytic tank bromeliads extract nutrients from the water that collects in their leaf rosette through specialized trichomes. However, we do not know what the consequences of this nutrient uptake are on the aquatic foodweb within the bromeliad tanks. In this view, this experiment consists of a manipulative experiment to explore the following questions. What is the degree to which bromeliads extract nutrients from their phytotelm? Does nutrient uptake by bromeliads result in competitive interactions with the phytotelm microfauna? Does potential competition between bromeliads and the phytotelm microfauna for nutrients modify the environment-dependent relationships between autotrophic algae and heterotrophic bacteria? Do bacteria and algae respond predictably to resources of different qualities?","principal_investigator":"Pierre Rogy","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0002-3002-0059","data_contact":"pierre.rogy@gmail.com","funder_name":null},{"id":9837,"title":"Effects of Hypoxia on Thermal Tolerance of Redside Dace","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:46:32 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-10 18:57:49 UTC","slug":"effects-of-hypoxia-on-thermal-tolerance-of-redside-dace","organisation_id":13,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Data management plan for a study on the effects of low dissolved oxygen (hypoxia) on thermal tolerance of Redside Dace (Clinostomus elongatus). In this study, the upper thermal tolerance of 64 Redside Dace will be measured after acclimation to one of four dissolved oxygen treatments (20, 40, 60, and 100 % air saturation). Fish will be measured three times: after two weeks of acclimation, ten weeks of acclimation, and after four weeks of exposure to 100% air saturation. Thermal tolerance will be measured at the highest and lowest oxygen acclimation levels (i.e. half of the fish will be measured at 100% air sat. and the other half will be measured at 20% air sat.). This study design will address whether or not acclimation to hypoxia improves thermal tolerance and whether or not fish are fully acclimated to their oxygen treatment after two weeks of exposure. Moreover, measurement of all individuals after exposure to fully oxygenated water will determine if the effects of hypoxia acclimation persist after reoxygenation. ","principal_investigator":"Jessica Reemeyer, Lauren Chapman","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0002-0081-2573","data_contact":"Jessica Reemeyer, 514-709-9933, jessica.reemeyer@mail.mcgill.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9838,"title":"Data Management Plan for Jess Kennedy's Msc. Thesis: Mechanisms and Consequences of Freeze Tolerance in Intertidal Mussels, Mytilus trossulus","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:46:49 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-02 20:49:36 UTC","slug":"data-management-plan-for-jess-kennedy-s-msc-thesis-mechanisms-and-consequences-of-freeze-tolerance-in-intertidal-mussels-mytilus-trossulus","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"","identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0002-7979-1516","description":"This is my data management plan for my MSc. thesis research on mussel freeze tolerance. Intertidal invertebrates, such as mussels, are susceptible to freezing during winter low tides when air temperatures drop below zero. Thus, many sessile intertidal invertebrates found in temperate and Arctic climates are able to survive being frozen. However, the mechanisms underlying this remarkable tolerance are almost completely unknown. Previous research supports the hypothesis that osmolytes (which are small molecules used by organisms to deal with osmotic stress by preventing cell dehydration or shrinkage) may play a role in enabling intertidal invertebrates to survive freezing. Thus, I propose to use the model organism Mytilus trossulus, an intertidal mussel, to assess this hypothesis by determining if incubating mussel gill tissue in osmolytes will increase gill tissue survival after freezing. I will also determine how mussel freeze tolerance varies along a latitudinal gradient by comparing the extent of mussel freeze tolerance across various sites along British Columbia’s coastline, for example between mussels collected from Vancouver and mussels collected from Calvert Island. Next I will ascertain if changes in osmolyte concentrations might explain some of this potential geographic variation. Finally, I will determine if experiencing freezing may have sublethal effects such as potentially increasing mussel susceptibility to predation by seastars, and/or by lowering mussel feeding rates, which would have consequences for the stability of mussel populations which routinely face freezing stress. This research is critically important because understanding the mechanisms of cellular resistance to freezing can have important biomedical applications, and also because understanding the extent of mussel freeze tolerance will help us to predict how the Northern range limit of this ecologically-important mussel species might change in the future.","principal_investigator":"Jessica Kennedy","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0002-7979-1516","data_contact":"Cell: 647-773-7561, email: kennedy@zoology.ubc.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9839,"title":"Niche Partitioning among sympatric seabirds (MSc. Thesis Petalas)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:47:49 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-08 15:14:18 UTC","slug":"niche-partitioning-among-sympatric-seabirds-msc-thesis-petalas","organisation_id":13,"grant_number":"","identifier":"260766475","description":"Ecological theory predicts that completely competitive species sharing identical overlapping niches cannot coexist in the same habitat at the same time. In order to persist, sympatric species must sufficiently partition their limiting resources, a phenomenon known as niche differentiation. Seabirds provide a unique opportunity to understand patterns of niche segregation because they form island multi-species colonies of breeding aggregations with seemingly overlapping diets and foraging areas. Biologging tools have shown the tactics in which seabirds employ to segregate components of their foraging strategies through the exploitation of different ecological niches such as exploiting different foraging areas and diving to different depths within the water column, leading to reduced interspecific competition. Further, combining diet observations and stable isotope analysis in tissues can allow us to specify information on the origin, type of prey consumed, and overall diet composition of the seabird, providing insight on dietary niche segregation. Thus, we propose to investigate how seabirds living in highly competitive environments segregate components of their foraging strategies, specifically, through analyzing a combination of (1) spatial (foraging area and depth using GPS-depth trackers), and (2) dietary niches (using stable isotope and direct feeding observations) will allow us to understand the ecological processes of how coexisting seabirds select and exploit foraging habitat differently. Particularly, examining the common murre (Uria aalge), razorbill (Alca torda) Atlantic puffin (Fratercula arctica), closely related, wing-propelling, pursuit-diving auks that feed primarily on forage fish on colony islands within the Gulf of St-Lawrence in the Mingan Archipelago.","principal_investigator":"Kyle Elliott","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0002-4313-0345","data_contact":"Christina.petalas@mail.mcgill.ca, (514) 947-8462","funder_name":null},{"id":9840,"title":"Prédire les services phytoremédiateurs à l'aide des traits fonctionnels","dmptemplate_id":43,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:48:19 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-08 14:43:37 UTC","slug":"predire-les-services-phytoremediateurs-a-l-aide-des-traits-fonctionnels","organisation_id":32,"grant_number":"","identifier":"p1209893","description":"Face aux milliers de sites contaminés, la phytoremédiation constitue une solution prometteuse, économique et écologique qui permet de décontaminer les sols à l’aide de plantes et de leurs microorganismes associés. Toutefois, il n’existe pas de cadre théorique permettant de prédire rapidement quelle plante serait plus efficace pour décontaminer des sols pollués. \r\nOBJECTIF\r\nNotre projet vise à fournir les premières assises d’un tel cadre à l’aide d’une approche utilisée en écologie fonctionnelle. En effet, les traits fonctionnels des plantes sont déjà utilisés pour prédire différents services écologiques. Similairement, nous visons à identifier les traits fonctionnels pouvant prédire des services phytoremédiateurs rendus par différentes plantes (p. ex. retraits de métaux de sol). \r\nMÉTHODOLOGIE\r\nAfin de développer ce cadre, les traits fonctionnels doivent pouvoir prédire et être corrélés à l'efficacité des plantes à fournir des services de décontamination. Afin de généraliser les résultats, ces corrélations doivent être présentes chez un grand nombre d'espèces de plantes. Pour ce faire, nous nous procèderons à une revue systématique de la littérature en phytoremédiation pour documenter l’efficacité phytoremédiatrice de centaines d’espèces végétales et compiler l'information dans une base de données. En parallèle, la base de données internationale TRY regroupe des traits fonctionnels pour plus de 16 000 espèces végétales. Nous extrairons ainsi des valeurs moyennes de traits fonctionnels pour chaque espèce phytoremédiatrice. Finalement, nous mettrons en relation l'efficacité phytoremédiatrice de chaque plante avec ces traits moyens dans un modèle linéaire hiérarchique. Cela permettra d'identifier quels traits fonctionnels sont corrélés aux services phytoremédiateurs. Dans ces modèles, nous contrôlerons également pour certaines covariables confondantes, comme la nature du contaminant ou le type de climat. De plus, la base de données en phytoremédiation demeurera, à elle seule, une contribution considérable et unique pour le domaine.","principal_investigator":"Béatrice Gervais-Bergeron","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0002-0489-0122","data_contact":"beatrice.gervais-bergeron@umontreal.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9841,"title":"Aero - Plane Study 3","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:48:33 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-04 01:01:27 UTC","slug":"aero-plane-study-3","organisation_id":48,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Dr. Amy-May Leach","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9842,"title":"How have we detected species range shifts? A systematic review","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:48:46 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-10 01:20:51 UTC","slug":"how-have-we-detected-species-range-shifts-a-systematic-review","organisation_id":13,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Climate change biogeography is a subject of increasing attention in recent years as species redistribute across environmental gradients in space. Empirical observations of species range shifts that have already occurred offer critical insights into drivers and constraints on species ranges, yet our ability to observe these shifts is limited by data availability and resolution over large spatial and temporal scales. The often-opportunistic nature of large-scale biogeography research leads to inconsistency in methodological techniques between range-shift observation studies, and this inconsistency may present barriers when comparing results from one study to another. Here, we use a systematic review of range shift literature to summarize the most common methods in empirical range shift detection efforts, focusing on total temporal duration over which the study was conducted, sampling frequency during that duration, and number of species included in range shift detections. By quantifying how range shifts have been detected in the past, we can standardize methods and definitions for range shift detection efforts in the future. Since methodological techniques may influence accuracy or resolution of results, assessing what methods studies have used will be an important step in comparing studies across methods and systems. ","principal_investigator":"Jake Lawlor","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1499-5227","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9843,"title":"Bayesian model for sustainable yield of Eastern Canada-West Greenland bowhead whales using genetic mark-recapture and utilization distribution","dmptemplate_id":35,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:48:58 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-10 03:52:48 UTC","slug":"bayesian-model-for-sustainable-yield-of-eastern-canada-west-greenland-bowhead-whales-using-genetic-mark-recapture-and-utilization-distribution","organisation_id":37,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"The objective of this study is to use genetic mark-recapture and sample coverage extrapolation techniques to provide an updated population abundance estimate to inform a population dynamics model for Eastern Canada West Greenland (ECWG) bowhead whales. The genetic mark-recapture analysis will use genetic microsatellite data for ECWG bowhead whales to achieve a full population abundance estimate. The resulting estimate of population abundance will be used alongside previous ECWG bowhead whale abundance estimates and historical harvest data to inform a population dynamics model. The resulting population dynamics model will be projected into the future under various harvest scenarios to inform sustainable harvest. ","principal_investigator":"Brooke Biddlecombe","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0002-3273-0644","data_contact":"biddlecb@myumanitoba.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9844,"title":"Influence of Postharvest Deficit Irrigation on Sweet Cherry Cold Hardiness in the Okanagan Valley","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:49:00 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-06 21:14:42 UTC","slug":"influence-of-postharvest-deficit-irrigation-on-sweet-cherry-cold-hardiness-in-the-okanagan-valley","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"","identifier":"ORCID: 0000-0003-1229-7617","description":"Climate change is expanding the suitable growing conditions for sweet cherries to higher elevations and latitudes in the southern interior of British Columbia. With this expansion comes the concern of an increasing water demand and the potential for crop frost damage at these more extreme growing sites. Postharvest deficit irrigation (PDI) can be used to improve water efficiency but its impact on cherry cold hardiness is currently not well understood. Working with local commercial cherry growers, this study will assess the impact of PDI on sweet cherry cold hardiness. Over three growing seasons, a 25% and 50% reduction in postharvest irrigation will be implemented in four orchards the first year and five orchards the following two years across a latitudinal and elevational gradient in the Okanagan Valley. Soil moisture, annual tree diameter, and pruning weight will be measured in addition to fruit bud cold hardiness and moisture throughout the fall and spring. These data will be analyzed statistically and fit to a sweet cherry cold hardiness predictive model that is currently under development. This model will be a useful tool available to British Columbia cherry producers and may be especially helpful to growers looking to expand production to higher elevations or latitudes. This research will help growers assess the benefits of PDI and contribute to the determination of best management practices for irrigation in the interior of British Columbia while enhancing cherry resilience to climate change.","principal_investigator":"Elizabeth Houghton","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"elizabeth.houghton@ubc.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9845,"title":"Mountain Ecosystems Resilience: to ensure the future of the high mountain biodiversity and peoples of Central Asia.","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:49:04 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-06 22:49:59 UTC","slug":"mountain-ecosystems-resilience-to-ensure-the-future-of-the-high-mountain-biodiversity-and-peoples-of-central-asia","organisation_id":14,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Mountains provide both diverse ecological niches for a wide variety of species, and numerous essential ecosystem services that support the economy and society’s well-being. In Central Asia, mountain ecosystems are the home of many threatened and emblematic species including the snow leopard (Panthera uncia), Siberian ibex (Capra sibirica) and argali (Ovis ammon).  These mountains are also a global hotspot for plant biodiversity. Mountain species develop complex interactions across trophic levels, including with local pastoral communities. The management and conservation of wildlife and native plants, diverse high mountains landscapes, and the resilience of local communities requires a detailed understanding their spatial and temporal variability and interactions across different trophic levels. \r\n\r\nThe objectives are (1) to document the current distribution and abundance of snow leopards and their mammalian prey, (2) monitor and assess changes in the timing of vegetation phenology to assess potential changes in forage availability for livestock and wild prey, (3) conduct a socio-economic valuation of critical ecosystem services and \r\n(4) to develop scenarios based on various climatic projections and use historic trends to predict impacts on land-use by wildlife and humans","principal_investigator":"Sherry Young","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9846,"title":"Prussian Carp Reproduction Project","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:49:09 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-09 18:19:55 UTC","slug":"prussian-carp-reproduction-project","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"","identifier":"PRCR","description":"This project is research on Prussian carp and invasive species in Saskatchewan. The project focuses on aging adult and juvenile Prussian carp and determining the best aging structure. The project will also study juvenile Prussian carp habitat selection and spawning times. Prussian Carp reproduce gynogenetically. I will be doing ploidy analysis to determine the genetic makeup of Prussian carp and their reproductive habits. I will collect ages and ploidy counts for Prussian carp and any site and sampling data necessary. This information will give descriptive characteristics to the Prussian carp currently found in Canada. The study will improve understanding of when, how, and how many times Prussian Carp reproduce. The information will give insight on how to manage Prussian carp and the environments they inhabit.  ","principal_investigator":"Jayme Menard","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0003-3238-9930","data_contact":"jaymemenard@gmail.com","funder_name":null},{"id":9847,"title":"The host with the most: Investigating host-parasitoid interactions of two candidate parasitoid biological control agents in an adventive landscape","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:49:11 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-02 18:02:10 UTC","slug":"the-host-with-the-most-investigating-host-parasitoid-interactions-of-two-candidate-parasitoid-biological-control-agents-in-an-adventive-landscape","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Host-parasitoid interactions in ecological communities offer unique opportunities to investigate the mechanisms which drive complex species interactions such as how parasitoids discriminate between potential hosts. My past work investigated variability in a gall wasp community at a local scale and contributed to identifying generalist tendencies in the host use of two gall wasp parasitoids, previously known to be specialists. My research targets two fundamental eco-evolutionary questions critical to understanding host-parasitoid interactions: i) which ecological mechanisms influence specialist or generalist life history strategies; and ii) how do specialists and generalists adapt to adventive landscapes and novel conditions? I aim to contribute to our understanding of how host-parasitoid interactions influence eco-evolutionary dynamics of parasitoids and hosts in novel ecosystems. \r\n\r\nImportation (aka classical) biological control (biocontrol) is an ecologically-based tool for the effective pest management of insects in invaded landscapes. Hymenopteran parasitoids are often used as control agents as they offer effective, highly host-specific, top-down pressures on insect pests. Prior to regulatory approval and release of agents, empirical research must demonstrate no adverse ecological effects of their introduction on non-target, usually closely related, organisms. By necessity, laboratory studies quantify the fundamental or physiological host range of agents. Field experiments investigating the ecological host range of adventive parasitoids in new environments could improve the likelihood of identifying an effective control agent and thus enhance the efficacy of pest management strategies. \r\n\r\nTwo parasitoid wasp species (Hymenoptera: Figitidae), proposed as candidate biocontrol agents for the economically devastating Spotted-wing Drosophila, <i>Drosophila suzukii</i> Matsumara (Diptera: Drosophilidae), have recently been detected in south-western British Columbia (BC). While both Drosophila specialists, one <i>Leptopilina japonica ssp. japonica</i> Novković & Kimura (Hymenoptera: Figitidae) is a relative ‘generalist’ with a broader host range, successfully parasitizing species in the Drosophila subgenus, while <i>Ganaspis brasiliensis</i> Ihering (Hymenoptera: Figitidae) is a more host specific ‘specialist’ primarily attacking <i>D. suzukii</i>. The parasitoids’ adventive presence in BC offers a unique opportunity to assess their ecological host range before they are released across the continent. \r\n\r\n\tThe objectives of this study are to: i) identify the fundamental host range of both parasitoids in BC; ii) identify the ecological host range of the two parasitoid species in an adventive landscape (Fraser Valley, BC); and iii) determine how various host traits influence ‘specialist’ or ‘generalist’ host-choice by each parasitoid. I will rear populations of pest and native <i>Drosophila</i> species and both parasitoids for use in laboratory and field experiments. I will identify the parasitoids’ fundamental host range in BC by exposing each parasitoid to a suite of <i>Drosophila</i> species in choice and non-choice laboratory experiments. These results will inform which native <i>Drosophila</i> are potentially at-risk of non-target attack and will thus inform which species will be used in ecological host range and host trait experiments. I will identify the ecological host range of these parasitoids in the Fraser Valley by infesting fruits with <i>D. suzukii</i> and native <i>Drosophila</i> larvae and measuring parasitism rates in the field. These results will contribute to our understanding of each parasitoids’ host specificity in BC and determine how supposed ‘specialist’ and ‘generalist’ parasitoids react to host availability in an adventive system. I will investigate how fruit species and fruit traits influence host selection by each parasitoid on <i>D. suzukii</i> and potentially at-risk native <i>Drosophila</i>. \r\n\r\n\tThis study will determine how ecological factors influence host selection by parasitoids while the fundamental and ecological host range work will contribute to our understanding of how host-parasitoid interactions influence eco-evolutionary dynamics of parasitoids in novel environments. My findings will directly impact fruit producers by contributing relevant data to enable more effective pest management and improve agro-ecosystem sustainability.","principal_investigator":"Nathan G. Earley","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0003-2835-9739","data_contact":"earley@mail.ubc.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9848,"title":"Land use change & connectivity in Monteregie","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:49:23 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-05 15:52:16 UTC","slug":"land-use-change-connectivity-in-monteregie","organisation_id":13,"grant_number":"NA","identifier":"NA","description":"WARNING: this project has already been carried out and this DMP is being created as part of an assignment for a course on DMPs.\r\n\r\nConnectivity conservation science, whose goal is to preserve the continuity of habitat throughout a given landscape, proceeds by identifying priority areas given the current configuration of the landscape. However, current connectivity conservation planning methods often do not take into account risks associated with future land use and climate change, and often do not confront the results of the prioritization process with the priorities perceived by stakeholders. In this thesis, we show solutions to those two issues in the context of an ongoing effort of connectivity conservation planning for the region of Montérégie in Southern Québec, Canada. In the first chapter, we built on past work of connectivity modelling using circuit theory in the region and complemented it with land use and climate change modelling that uses a combination of statistical modelling and MCMC-based simulations. Models trained on past land use data were used to project future land use changes and estimate future changes in potential functional connectivity for 5 different umbrella species. In a second chapter, we integrated these results with the perceived conservation priorities in the region. We conducted a day-long workshop with stakeholders involved in the ongoing connectivity conservation planning effort in the region and collected information on landscape features considered as priority areas for connectivity. We translated these results into simple conservation scenarios. We showed the importance of considering land use changes to produce a resilient network of protected areas and highlight the need for a multi-stakeholder approach in the definition of conservation scenarios and the identification of regional priorities","principal_investigator":"Valentin Lucet","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0268-818X","data_contact":"NA","funder_name":null},{"id":9849,"title":"Data Management for Delta Pest and Beneficial Insect Biodiversity Project","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:49:30 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-02 18:55:27 UTC","slug":"data-management-for-delta-pest-and-beneficial-insect-biodiversity-project","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"","identifier":"11356145","description":"My thesis project with the University of British Columbia is concerned with the ways that semi-natural habitat restoration in agro-ecosystems impact the biodiversity of pest and beneficial insects. The role of insects in agriculture is extremely important, and finding methods to provide pest management in a sustainable way is and will continue to be important in a changing world. This project will record data on insect species richness, insect counts, and vegetation surveys. This data will be utilised to inform growers in the Lower Mainland region of British Columbia on how best to manage their land and natural habitats to decrease pest pressure and sustain natural communities of beneficial insects.","principal_investigator":"Matt Tsuruda","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9850,"title":"Providing baseline data into the quantities and characteristics of microplastics in selected lakes in British Columbia.","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:49:33 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-07 21:51:43 UTC","slug":"providing-baseline-data-into-the-quantities-and-characteristics-of-microplastics-in-selected-lakes-in-british-columbia","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"n/a","identifier":"","description":"Microplastics, defined as particles smaller than 5 mm in size, have been identified as an emerging contaminant of high environmental concern for aquatic ecosystems. Microplastics have been identified as a widespread pollutant, with researchers finding microplastics in almost all areas they investigate (arctic ocean, deep sea, etc.). However, the bulk of research has focused on marine environments, neglecting freshwater ecosystems. Freshwater lakes in British Columbia are of recreational, economic and cultural importance. This study will be the first to investigate the quanties and characteristics of microplastics in lakes in British Columbia (BC). This study addresses the following research questions: a) are microplastics present in lakes in BC, b) in what quanities, c) what are the main characteristics of microplastics in these lakes (shape, colour, polymer type), and d) is there a correlation between anthropogenic activity and quantities of microplastics observed in this closed lake systems. In collaboration with the BC Ministry of Environment and Climate Change Strategy's Long Term Lake Monitoring Progam, four lakes, Alta, Brohm, Chilliwack and Cultus were selected and sampled for microplastics. Grab samples of water were taken at each lake. In brief, 20L of lake water was filtered through a 63 micron sieve, and the contents were rinsed into a glass jar using reverse osmosis water, then taken to be processed in the laboratory at the University of British Columbia. Triplicate samples were taken at each lake and the number of triplicates taken depended on lake size (n=2 or 3). In the laboratory, wet samples are vacuum filtered onto polycarbonate filters, analyzed under a microscope, and suspected plastics are extracted off the filter and set aside for polymer identification using spectroscopy. This data will provide novel insight into microplastic pollution in lakes in BC, which can be used to assess the ecological risk of microplastics to lake health and future monitoring, mitigation and management strategies. The data will be added to the BC Ministry of Environment and Climate Change Strategy's Long Term Lake Monitoring Progam, which monitors and evaluates the health of selected lakes across the province.","principal_investigator":"Natasha Klasios","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0002-7527-6090","data_contact":"klasios@zoology.ubc.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9851,"title":"Data management plan for intra- and interpopulation variation and heritability of thermal tolerance in kelp gametophytes","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:49:33 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-11 07:43:31 UTC","slug":"data-management-plan-for-intra-and-interpopulation-variation-and-heritability-of-thermal-tolerance-in-kelp-gametophytes","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"This data management plan outlines the practices that will be applied on data to be gathered for my MSc thesis. \r\n\r\nKelps are large brown algae in the order Laminariales. Kelps have a two-stage life history, where a macroscopic, diploid sporophyte stage (the kelp familiar to most people) alternates with a microscopic haploid gametophyte stage. While the abiotic tolerance of both gametophytes and sporophytes have been reasonably well characterized, it is comparatively unknown how abiotic tolerances vary between and within populations of gametophytes, as well as how heritable abiotic tolerance is between the two life stages. Characterizing this inter- and intrapopulation variability would contribute to a better understanding of how kelp populations may respond to anthropogenic change. Additionally, should gametophyte abiotic tolerance correlate well with sporophyte abiotic tolerance, kelp cultivar selection for aquaculture purposes could possibly be conducted on microscopic gametophytes, reducing the need for resource intensive field trials on macroscopic sporophytes. \r\n\r\nThis study aims to answer the following questions: 1) How much do gametophytes vary in their thermal tolerance within and between populations of bull kelp Nereocystis luetkeana? 2) How well does the thermal tolerance of a gametophyte genotype correlate with the thermal tolerance of the sporophytes it produces? ","principal_investigator":"Varoon Pornsinsiriruk","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0002-2891-0335","data_contact":"varoonp@student.ubc.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9852,"title":"Rare earth element abundances of Phanerozoic successions of SE Saskatchewan","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:49:35 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-10 18:24:05 UTC","slug":"rare-earth-element-abundances-of-phanerozoic-successions-of-se-saskatchewan","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"","identifier":"OrcID: 0000-0003-1433-5568","description":"Rare earth elements (REE) are becoming increasingly important in modern society owing to their requirement in numerous high-tech, medical, and green energy applications. However, the current mining of REE occurs in few localities around the world, is highly energy intensive, and has a large environmental footprint. Additionally, Canada does not currently mine REEs, and must rely on imports to meet demand, which makes Canada vulnerable to supply chain disruptions which can arise over global tensions, which in turn can affect multiple industries domestically. \r\nDue to the environmental impact of REE extraction, as well as the need for a stable, domestic supply, research is now beginning to focus on the extraction of REE from non-traditional, secondary sources including brines produced as a result of petroleum extraction. This study focuses on the REE concentrations in subsurface brines and sedimentary successions from southeastern Saskatchewan in order to determine areas of potential REE enrichment as well as to ascertain controls and sources of REEs in the subsurface. Data included as part of this study includes water and bulk rock geochemistry from a suite of geological formations in southeastern Saskatchewan. Geochemical data, mineralogy, and site information, including well identification, geological formation, and depositional environment will be included. Geochemical data for the brines and bulk rock will be collected using Inductively Coupled Plasma – Mass Spectrometry (ICP-MS), while depositional environment and mineralogy will be determined based on drill-core studies. This study will supplement previous work conducted by the Saskatchewan Geological Survey, with the goal of determining locations which could support the economic extraction of these critical metals. \r\n\r\nDMP contact: Brendan Bishop\r\nbab495@uregina.ca\r\n","principal_investigator":"Leslie Robbins","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Brendan Bishop","funder_name":null},{"id":9853,"title":"Using landscape genomics to predict future gene-environment mismatch for lodgepole pine","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:49:41 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-17 22:03:08 UTC","slug":"using-landscape-genomics-to-predict-future-gene-environment-mismatch-for-lodgepole-pine","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"","identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0001-9506-3618 ","description":"This research aims to use a landscape genomics approach (the Gradient Forest model) to explore the relationship between lodgepole pine genomic variation and the changing environment. The Gradient Forest (GF) model involves a large number of SNPs to identify relationships between environmental factors and genetic adaptation of organisms in response to these factors. Research objectives for this project are: (1). To identify major climate variables driving lodgepole pine local adaptation. (2). To predict the spatial distribution of gene-environment mismatch under future climate.","principal_investigator":"Yue Yu","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"yue.yu@ubc.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9854,"title":"Uncovering the genetic basis of Mendelian colour phenotypes in ball pythons","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:50:26 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-06 21:14:54 UTC","slug":"uncovering-the-genetic-basis-of-mendelian-colour-phenotypes-in-ball-pythons","organisation_id":13,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Captive-bred ball pythons (Python regius) represent a powerful model system for studying the genetic basis of colour variation and Mendelian phenotypes in vertebrates. Although hundreds of Mendelian phenotypes (colour morphs) affecting colouration and patterning have been described for ball pythons, the genes causing these colour morphs remain unknown. In this project, we use crowdsourcing to obtain samples from commercial ball python breeders to investigate the genetic basis of Mendelian phenotypes and vertebrate pigmentation. We use whole-genome sequencing of pooled samples followed by population genetic methods to delineate the genomic region containing the causal gene. Functional annotation of genetic variants (SNPs and indels) is used to identify putative causal mutations. This work is intended to show that ball python colour morphs have the potential to be an excellent model system for studying the genetic basis of pigment variation in vertebrates, and highlight how collaborations with commercial breeders can accelerate discoveries.\r\n\r\n","principal_investigator":"Alan Garcia-Elfring ORCID 0000-0002-2093-4041","principal_investigator_identifier":"Rowan D. H. Barrett ORCID 0000-0003-3044-2531","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9855,"title":"Vulnerability Risk Assessment of Canadian Birds to Climate Change Using Functional Traits","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:50:28 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-19 19:11:49 UTC","slug":"vulnerability-risk-assessment-of-canadian-birds-to-climate-change-using-functional-traits","organisation_id":13,"grant_number":"","identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0003-1805-4421","description":"For this study, I propose to use species distribution models to assess how climate change will impact Canadian birds. Using range maps in combination with region-specific bioclimatic and anthropogenic variables, I will determine species vulnerability risk for Canadian birds and identify key regions within Canada in need of conservation efforts. Species’ range maps will be provided by the IUCN and bioclimatic variables from WorldClim simulations. Other related variables such as vegetation change, harvesting, and fire activity will be provided by other simulations such as LANDIS-II. Models will be run under a mid-range Global Circulation Models (GCMs) scenario and the RCP6 emissions scenario. To analyze the results, I will use a Boosted Regression Tree, generalized additive models (GAMs), and generalized linear models (GLMs). Cross-validation of the model will also be performed using a holder dataset and an area under the curve (AUC) analysis. These results could be used to better understand the impact of environmental change for hundreds of birds that occupy these rapidly changing habitats and help predict which species might be at risk across Canada and in need of immediate and further conservation assessments.","principal_investigator":"Andrea Brown","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0003-1805-4421","data_contact":"andrea.brown3@mail.mcgill.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9856,"title":"My plan (University of British Columbia Generic Template)","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:50:30 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-03 19:50:30 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-british-columbia-generic-template--622","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Elise Pletcher","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9857,"title":"Neural correlates of spatial behaviour and spatial memory in relation to contaminant exposure in free ranging gulls","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:50:49 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-07 08:57:36 UTC","slug":"neural-correlates-of-spatial-behaviour-and-spatial-memory-in-relation-to-contaminant-exposure-in-free-ranging-gulls","organisation_id":13,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"My PhD will examine neural correlates of spatial behaviour and spatial memory in relation to contaminant exposure in free ranging ring-billed gulls (Larus delawarensis), with focus on a particularly urban population with exceptionally high contaminant levels. Additionally, individuals from this population have been shown to have large variation in spatial behaviour (e.g. large differences in complexity and repetitiveness). I will use both fundamental and applied approaches as well as field and experimental study designs to answer my questions. The main questions are: (i) what are the underlying neuronal mechanisms for spatial memory, and how do differences in these mechanisms drive differences in spatial behaviour? And (ii) how are these mechanisms affected by contaminant exposure?","principal_investigator":"Anna Lippold","principal_investigator_identifier":"orcid.org/0000-0003-3842-686X","data_contact":"anna.lippold2@mail.mgill.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9858,"title":"Blue Carbon storage in eelgrass (Zostera marina) meadows across Canada's marine coastline.","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:51:06 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-03 14:47:11 UTC","slug":"blue-carbon-storage-in-eelgrass-zostera-marina-meadows-across-canada-s-marine-coastline","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"22R33429","identifier":"NZCV","description":"‘Blue carbon’ refers to the carbon sequestered by coastal marine habitats. In Canada, seagrass beds and salt marshes are major blue carbon habitats, capturing carbon through photosynthesis and particle trapping and sequestering it for millennia. This will 1) Quantify total known and estimated eelgrass habitat area on all three Canadian coastlines, 2) Generate estimates of how much carbon is sequestered in Canada’s eelgrass beds, 3) Quantify variation in carbon storage in eelgrass beds across different environmental conditions.\r\nThe results will be used by the Economic Analysis and Statistics (EAS) Directorate to undertake economic analyses in support of decision making related to multiple policies, including but not limited to the development of Ocean Accounts and Ecosystem Accounts as well as Marine Spatial Planning and Marine Conservation Targets.","principal_investigator":"Mary O'Connor","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0001-9583-1592","data_contact":"Matt Christensen, 604-355-9882,msc01@zoology.ubc.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9859,"title":"Effects of herbivory and climate change on reproductive trade-offs and population persistence of a perennial forb","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:51:19 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-08 04:49:08 UTC","slug":"effects-of-herbivory-and-climate-change-on-reproductive-trade-offs-and-population-persistence-of-a-perennial-forb","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Environmental conditions and interactions with herbivores influence plant life-history strategies, but the extent to which these strategies will change due to anthropogenic factors is difficult to predict. If reproduction carries a cost, theory predicts that allocating more resources to reproduction in one season will trade-off with reduced future vital rates like survival, growth, or fecundity. These reproductive trade-offs are influenced by resource availability and are mediated by floral herbivores, but how these interactions will change in the future, and their impact on population persistence, is an unanswered question. Precipitation regimes are expected to shift with climate change, but the direction and magnitude of these effects vary. In this project I will use a precipitation manipulation experiment to simulate both drier and wetter conditions for an early season flowering herbaceous forb, Dodecatheon hendersonii, in the Garry Oak ecosystem of British Columbia. Using demographic rates and integral population models, I will address the following questions: How does Dodecatheon hendersonii exhibit costs of reproduction as quantified by effects of reproductive effort on future survival, growth, or fecundity? What role does floral herbivory have in mediating these costs through its effect on reproductive success and effort?\r\n\r\n","principal_investigator":"Jennifer Williams/Jenna Loesberg","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"jenna.loesberg@ubc.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9860,"title":"BC Region 4 Resource Selection Function Data for Cervids","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:51:54 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-08 19:21:46 UTC","slug":"bc-region-4-resource-selection-function-data-for-cervids","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"An assessment of cervid migratory pathways into BC for the prevention of Chronic Wasting Disease (CWD) spread.\r\nThis study is primary data aggregation with a focus on assessing habitat connectivity. \r\n\r\nChronic Wasting Disease is a lethal prion infection spreading to cervid animals across North America. The disease is now approaching BC and will affect provincial wildlife management, hunting regulations, and public health.\r\n\r\nMy research question is: Where are animals at risk of CWD entering British Columbia? The purpose of the study is to inform communities and government and increase vigilance and efficiency in testing.\r\n\r\nFocal study species are mule deer, white-tailed deer, moose, and rocky mountain elk.\r\n\r\nThis is an assessment of Region 4 in BC, as well as 100km South and East of the border.","principal_investigator":"Jacob Hubner","principal_investigator_identifier":"0000-0003-1471-2124","data_contact":"2509384919, jkhubner@gmail.com","funder_name":null},{"id":9862,"title":"Phylogenetic Prediction of the Invasion Potential of Ectomycorrhizal Fungi","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:52:44 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-10 22:28:36 UTC","slug":"phylogenetic-prediction-of-the-invasion-potential-of-ectomycorrhizal-fungi","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Ectomycorrhizal fungi (EMF) are soil-living fungi that form connections with the roots of many plants. They provide plants with nutrients from the soil in exchange for carbon the plants produce via photosynthesis; this relationship makes them important to the survival of many plant species. As people have moved plants and soil around the world, they have unintentionally brought EMF with them, and some species have escaped and become invasive in their new environments. For this to happen, however, the fungi must be able to form connections with trees growing in their new habitat, and most EMF can only form connections with a limited number of plant species. Knowing which plant-fungus combinations are compatible is therefore important for predicting where certain fungi may become invasive, but we have a limited understanding of the mechanisms that control this process. We do know that many EMF prefer to associate with plants that are closely related to each other (for instance, fungi from the genus Rhizopogon associate only with members of the pine family). My goal is to use this information to construct maps of the likely ranges available to potential invasive EMF. To demonstrate the concept, I will focus on Eastern White Pine, which is known to be compatible with the invasive EMF Amanita phalloides in eastern North America. I will identify close relatives of White Pine growing in the area, and use their geographic ranges, number of known fungal associations, and degree of relatedness to White Pine to predict where invasive fungi are likely to be found. I will then compare these predictions to the observed range of the real invasive fungus.","principal_investigator":"Liam Johnson","principal_investigator_identifier":"ORCID https://orcid.org/0000-0002-7878-2140","data_contact":"liamgwj@mail.ubc.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9863,"title":"The fossil record of Dinosaur Provincial Park","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:53:23 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-10 19:31:19 UTC","slug":"the-fossil-record-of-dinosaur-provincial-park","organisation_id":13,"grant_number":"FRQNT-289816","identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0002-9149-8427","description":"The main aim of this palaeontological PhD project is to correlate all fossil occurrences known from all quarries within Dinosaur Provincial Park, Alberta, in space and in time. Each quarry will be plotted on a geological map in which the Dinosaur Park Formation will be divided into strata that represent precise time intervals bounded by ash layers for which an absolute age is known. For each quarry with its geographical coordinates, all known fossils will be aggregated in a large database.\r\nThe ultimate aim of this project is to use this fossil database to track changes in biodiversity through the ~1 million years represented by the Dinosaur Park Formation in the Late Cretaceous period with greater precision than what was previously achieved. The Paleobiology Database already exists as a means for palaeontologists to deposit species occurrences from around the world, but it bins large fossil sites such as Dinosaur Provincial Park as a single point in time and space. This constraint is trivial for palaeontological studies that span very long geological time scales (as well as global or continental spatial scales), but it leads to insufficient temporal resolution for studies that focus on a single extinct ecosystem at a more local spatial scale and at a smaller time scale.\r\nThe animal groups that have a sufficiently high sample size for this project would be non-avian dinosaurs, turtles, fish and possibly crocodylians. Since we already know from the sedimentology that this Cretaceous floodplain was located ever closer to an ever-advancing shoreline throughout the formation's duration, we would like to test whether this apparent landscape change is correlated with any change in abundance or diversity in some of the vertebrate taxa found in the Park's fossil record.\r\nA large diversity of metadata will form the foundation of this database. Information will be gathered from fossil specimen identification in museum collections, from studies of the local geology during fieldwork, and from a three-dimensional map of the badlands of Dinosaur Provincial Park produced from the aggregation of aerial and ground-based photographs.","principal_investigator":"Alexandre Demers-Potvin","principal_investigator_identifier":"Hans C.E. Larsson","data_contact":"alexandre.demers-potvin@mail.mcgill.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9864,"title":"My plan (University of British Columbia Generic Template)","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:53:28 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-03 19:53:28 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-british-columbia-generic-template--627","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Mauro Sugawara","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9865,"title":"My plan (Rocky mountains project)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:53:41 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-05 21:02:20 UTC","slug":"my-plan-rocky-mountains-project","organisation_id":29,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"The the effect of size-selective harvesting on brook trout trophic interaction, spatial distribution and the metabolism of mountain lakes.","principal_investigator":"Julien Beaulieu","principal_investigator_identifier":"Alison Derry","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9866,"title":"My plan (University of British Columbia Generic Template)","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:54:04 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-03 20:20:31 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-british-columbia-generic-template--628","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"My research is about the relationship between diversity and resilience in coral reefs. Specifically I am interested in identifying diversity indices that be used to manage communities. The data will be collected to parameterize and validate the model we developed to address these questions.","principal_investigator":"Bruno Carturan","principal_investigator_identifier":" 0000-0001-6811-1063","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9867,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:54:24 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-03 19:54:24 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3897","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Joey Burant","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9868,"title":"Beaver Functional Morphometrics as it Relates to Habitat and Foraging (TBD).","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 19:54:33 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-05 17:08:09 UTC","slug":"beaver-functional-morphometrics-as-it-relates-to-habitat-and-foraging-tbd","organisation_id":13,"grant_number":"N/A","identifier":"","description":"In Canada, the North American beaver (Castor canadensis) has been a staple for centuries, particularly in indigenous trapping communities. More than just a cultural landmark, the beaver is a specialized ecosystem engineer that has particular wood chopping features. Due to its particular specialization and wide distribution through much of North America’s forests composed of different wood densities, the beaver constitutes an ideal model species to investigate the links between functional morphology and habitat type. Furthermore, the beaver is of particular interest to biologists and indigenous trappers which has created a strong foundation of data concerning its distribution, diet, and behaviors, that can be used to assess their current habitats. Objective: The objective of this study is to (1) determine how the functional morphology of beaver dentition and skull strength are related to their habitat (2) to predict the effects of climate warming and habitat loss on the beaver’s distribution and the evolution of its morphology. Hypothesis: Due to the beaver’s dependence on specialized wood herbivory and engineering, and the relationship between morphological selection and specialized behaviors, we hypothesize that beaver skull functional morphology will be closely related to an index of wood density. Experimental approach: Skulls will be sampled from two sources: (1) trapped beaver skulls from Cree trappers who work with members of the laboratory where I will conduct my research and (2) from museum specimens representing individuals occurring in habitat of different wood densities. The functional morphology will be evaluated by combining Traditional Morphology, Geometric Morphometrics (GM), an objective quantitative morphological variance tool, and Finite-Element Analysis (FEA), an engineering approach to investigate the significance of the dentition and cranial structure with respect to the biomechanics of wood biting. These methods will be applied using an electron microscope from the laboratory, to observe microwear marks and the annuli wear stages for ontogeny and feature identification. Traditional morphology and landmarks will be used on the standard rodent macro features typical for geometric morphometric and morphological analysis. For the habitat model, wood hardness data covering the range of the North American beaver will be compiled from the many wood databases and peer-reviewed literature, similar in methods to a Swenson and Enquist study in 2007. This will allow me to generate a wood density index, which will be used to model the relationship between habitat and functional traits measured from the skull and dentition of beavers.","principal_investigator":"Jonathan Diamond","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0002-4776-090X","data_contact":"Email: jonathan.diamond@mail.mcgill.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9869,"title":"My graduate project","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-03 20:14:11 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-09 17:40:09 UTC","slug":"my-graduate-project","organisation_id":28,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"I will be looking at dynamics of multiple stressors in water quality, nutrient fluxes, and river metabolism along the river continuum of South Saskatchewan River (SSR) tributaries in Alberta. Alberta has a challenge of managing its water resources, not only from quality and quantity issues, but also with climate change that has resulted in relative water scarcity in the southern prairies. To look at how these challenges impacted water quality, I will study the dynamics of multiple stressors and nutrient fluxes in SSR tributaries in Alberta. Here, I will be using long term water quality data collected by the Alberta provincial government and Environment Canada, and I can use these data to look at temporal and spatial variation of multiple stressors in water quality and nutrient fluxes from upstream to downstream in SSR tributaries. Additionally, I will be looking at Synchrony of these dynamics across the sites, with land use patterns and climate of the region. Finally, to estimate the impacts of these water quality changes on river ecosystem health, I will analyses the river metabolism at selected sites in all three tributary rivers of SSR in Alberta. For this study, I will be collecting diurnal variation of Oxygen ( every 5 mins) for one year.  Dissolved oxygen data along with monthly measurements of river depth, discharge and photosynthetically active radiation (PAR), measurements like gross primary productivity GPP), ecosystem respiration (ER) and net ecosystem production (NEP) will be calculated and compared across sites. Finally, GPP, ER and NEP measurements with water quality variables, nutrient fluxes and climatic information will be used to develop a predictive model to understand how anthropogenic and climate changes affect the river ecosystem health in SSR tributaries of Alberta.  ","principal_investigator":"Sasindu Gunawardana","principal_investigator_identifier":"gunawardana@uleth.ca, https://orcid.org/0000-0003-1646-681X","data_contact":"sasindugunawardana@gmail.com ","funder_name":null},{"id":9870,"title":"Plasiticity of the lethal and sub-lethal upper thermal limits of the California mussel (Mytilus californianus)","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-11-03 22:44:51 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-07 20:45:48 UTC","slug":"plasiticity-of-the-lethal-and-sub-lethal-upper-thermal-limits-of-the-california-mussel-mytilus-californianus","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"The California mussel (Mytlius californianus) is an important foundation species in Northeast Pacific rocky intertidal zone habitats. As a sessile ectotherm, their body temperature and associated physiological rates are dependent on their environment, which can result in mass-mortality events when temperatures exceed physiological thresholds. My project looks to explore the relative plasticity of the upper thermal limit of M. californianus through a long-term acclimatization treatment exposure and subsequent acute physiological experiments. With three simulated 'low tide' treatments (22C, 28C, and 34C) applied over a 6-week period, followed by acute thermal experiments, we hope to answer the following questions:\r\n\r\n1.) Does acclimatization alter the thermal tolerance curves and LT50's of M. californianus?\r\n\r\n2.) Does acclimatization alter the critical temperature (Tcrit) of M. californianus, beyond which heart rates collapse with rising temperature?\r\n\r\nBetter understanding the plasticity of the upper thermal limit of M. californianus will provide insight into their resilience to extreme temperature events and heat waves, which are predicted to increase in intensity and frequency with human-driven climate warming.  ","principal_investigator":"Graham Brownlee","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Graham Brownlee, (250) 488-9606, brownlee@zoology.ubc.ca, https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2670-0406","funder_name":null},{"id":9871,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-04 05:26:04 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-04 05:26:04 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--3900","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Matthew Koristka","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9872,"title":"AID ","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-04 13:21:33 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-04 13:23:09 UTC","slug":"aid","organisation_id":13,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Samira Rahimi","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Neda Parinejad, neda.parinejadkhameneh@mcgill.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9874,"title":"Data Management Plan for Effects of Fragmentation on Mustelids","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-04 18:53:40 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-04 20:46:05 UTC","slug":"data-management-plan-for-effects-of-fragmentation-on-mustelids","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"This DMP is for a multi-year study of the effects of habitat fragmentation on mustelids (weasel family) in Eastern Ontario. Snow tracking and camera traps will be used to collect observations of mustelid species along transects in designated habitat patches comprising multiple forest landscapes. These data will address the following questions: Do mustelids experience edge effects, whether positive or negative? What is the effect of landscape-level habitat fragmentation on site-level mustelid abundance and diversity? What is the effect of landscape-level habitat fragmentation on landscape-level mustelid diversity?","principal_investigator":"Samantha Morin","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9875,"title":"EOS 525 DEMO Nov 4-2020  (UVic DMP Template)","dmptemplate_id":44,"created_at":"2020-11-04 19:38:18 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-04 20:01:23 UTC","slug":"eos-525-demo-nov-4-2020-uvic-dmp-template","organisation_id":21,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Research will be undertaken to attempt to identify, using available research data discovery tools, what data sets have been deposited, in a Data Repository, by UVic SEOS researchers,  between 2018-2020. The purpose of the research is to gather data on the scale and scope of research data deposited by SEOS researchers in this time period, and specifically to identify the types of data being deposited, and the data repositories chosen to host the data. Followup interviews will be conducted with identified researchers to explore best practices and challenges experienced. The data will be used to inform the Libraries Research Data Management support services. ","principal_investigator":"Kathleen  Matthews","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0561-5728","data_contact":"Kathleen Matthews","funder_name":null},{"id":9876,"title":"Test 1","dmptemplate_id":43,"created_at":"2020-11-04 20:23:52 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-04 20:24:32 UTC","slug":"test-1--4","organisation_id":32,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Joanie Tremblay","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9877,"title":"EOS 525 Sample Plan","dmptemplate_id":44,"created_at":"2020-11-04 21:46:47 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-04 23:25:24 UTC","slug":"eos-525-sample-plan","organisation_id":21,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Sample data management plan for EOS 525","principal_investigator":"Theron Finley","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0001-7359-5613","data_contact":"Theron Finley","funder_name":null},{"id":9878,"title":"My plan (UVic DMP Template)","dmptemplate_id":44,"created_at":"2020-11-04 22:32:52 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-04 22:32:52 UTC","slug":"my-plan-uvic-dmp-template--100","organisation_id":21,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Taizi Huang","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9879,"title":"Single versus successive heat wave effects on high intertidal communities","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-11-04 23:07:35 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-21 01:08:44 UTC","slug":"single-versus-successive-heat-wave-effects-on-high-intertidal-communities","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"This project is a two-year manipulative field experiment addressing how climate change, specifically increasing temperatures, affects high intertidal communities. Specifically, the project asks the following:\r\n\r\n- How do elevated temperatures affect the species composition and abundance of organisms in the high intertidal zone?\r\n- How do these same communities respond to single versus successive years of hot summers?\r\n\r\nThis experiment commenced in March 2019 at Ruckle Park, Saltspring Island, British Columbia, and is expected to end in March 2021. Temperature in the intertidal zone is manipulated passively through the use of experimental settlement tiles; each tile consists of a central non-toxic epoxy square suitable for organism settlement surrounded by an outer plastic ring that is either a) white (ambient temperature treatment) or b) black (elevated temperature treatment). At low tide, solar radiation heats the black tiles more than the white tiles, driving a significant temperature difference between each treatment. The temperature of the air or water at each tile's surface is recorded hourly by a data logger beneath the epoxy. Tiles are arrayed in six blocks along the shore consisting of 16 tiles each (initial n = 48 per treatment), with treatments distributed randomly within each block (n = 4 per block). This means each tile has a unique tile ID consisting of block (A-F) and number within block (1-16).\r\n\r\nFollowing the first summer of 2019, the temperature treatment of half the tiles were switched, with half of the black tiles converted to white tiles and vice versa. This manipulation was performed to test the effect of a single hot summer on communities (either immediately after disturbance or one year post-disturbance)  versus two successive hot or cool summers. Half of the tiles were destructively sampled in September 2020 to determine the immediate effect of summer temperature treatments on communities, while half will be collected in March 2021 to determine whether these effects carry over even once temperature differences between treatments ceases.\r\n\r\nThe recorded data consist of photographs of each tile through time, as well as abundance and diversity surveys for each tile at monthly (during summer) and bimonthly (during winter) intervals. Destructive sampling will allow for the diversity of infaunal barnacle bed communities to also be captured, along with size data of interesting taxa.","principal_investigator":"Amelia Hesketh","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0002-7344-8565","data_contact":"hesketh@zoology.ubc.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9880,"title":"My plan (UVic DMP Template)","dmptemplate_id":44,"created_at":"2020-11-04 23:23:52 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-04 23:23:52 UTC","slug":"my-plan-uvic-dmp-template--101","organisation_id":21,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Daniel Garduno","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9881,"title":"EOS 525 proposal DMP","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-04 23:25:10 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-05 18:02:22 UTC","slug":"eos-525-proposal-dmp","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Leah Cicon","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9882,"title":"MoronkeHarris_EOS525_ResearchProposalDMP_2020","dmptemplate_id":44,"created_at":"2020-11-04 23:26:29 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-04 23:54:45 UTC","slug":"moronkeharris_eos525_researchproposaldmp_2020","organisation_id":21,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Moronke K. Harris","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0002-9927-5543","data_contact":"moronke@uvic.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9883,"title":"My plan (UVic DMP Template)","dmptemplate_id":44,"created_at":"2020-11-04 23:30:02 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-04 23:30:02 UTC","slug":"my-plan-uvic-dmp-template--103","organisation_id":21,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Kathleen  Matthews","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9884,"title":"My plan (UVic DMP Template)","dmptemplate_id":44,"created_at":"2020-11-04 23:30:15 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-04 23:30:15 UTC","slug":"my-plan-uvic-dmp-template--104","organisation_id":21,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Emma Louis","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9885,"title":"My plan (UVic DMP Template)","dmptemplate_id":44,"created_at":"2020-11-04 23:32:20 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-04 23:32:20 UTC","slug":"my-plan-uvic-dmp-template--105","organisation_id":21,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Raj Deepak S. N.","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9886,"title":"My plan (UVic DMP Template)","dmptemplate_id":44,"created_at":"2020-11-04 23:41:26 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-04 23:41:26 UTC","slug":"my-plan-uvic-dmp-template--106","organisation_id":21,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Liam Hubbert","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":9887,"title":"EOS 525","dmptemplate_id":44,"created_at":"2020-11-04 23:48:13 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-22 11:22:25 UTC","slug":"eos-525","organisation_id":21,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Evaluating natural interannual variabilities of CO2 uptake in the North Atlantic subpolar region\r\nand possible correlations with the North Atlantic Oscillation.","principal_investigator":"Parsa Gooya","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0003-2539-263X","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":9888,"title":"My plan (UVic DMP Template)","dmptemplate_id":44,"created_at":"2020-11-04 23:56:00 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-04 23:58:26 UTC","slug":"my-plan-uvic-dmp-template--108","organisation_id":21,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Data management plan for the project  \"Identification of active faults on Vancouver Island forimproving seismic hazard estimates\" for the course EOS 525","principal_investigator":"Guy Salomon","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0002-9239-6449","data_contact":"EOS 525 Research Proposal","funder_name":null},{"id":9889,"title":"The incidence and spread Grapevine red blotch virus in the Okanagan valley","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-11-05 01:26:05 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-10 03:33:22 UTC","slug":"the-incidence-and-spread-grapevine-red-blotch-virus-in-the-okanagan-valley","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"","identifier":"Scopus: 7201807282","description":"This research aims to quantify the incidence of the newly emerging Grapevine red blotch virus (GRBV) in the Okanagan valley and to determine if the virus is naturally spreading. GRBV incidence is being determined through large-scale systematic sampling and testing of grapevines from many vineyards. Based on similar research in the United States, we expect GRBV to be minimally present or absent in most vineyards. These vineyards are also being monitored for symptoms of GRBV infection and mapped yearly to detect potential secondary spread. We suspect that spread will be observed, because although the only known insect vector of GRBV, the three-cornered alfalfa treehopper, is not present in the Okanagan, very closely related treehoppers are present, and may be vectors as well. The purpose of this research is to produce a clear picture of the status of GRBV in the Okanagan and to justify research on potential insect vectors of GRBV if natural spread is observed.","principal_investigator":"Dr. Tom Lowery, Dr. Miranda Hart","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"250.807.9398, miranda.hart@ubc.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9890,"title":"Warming temperatures effect on aquatic community","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-11-05 08:55:22 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-08 04:47:20 UTC","slug":"warming-temperatures-effect-on-aquatic-community","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"","identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0003-2207-840X","description":"My Master's project will examine how temperature affects aquatic algae as a food source for higher trophic levels. The project addresses the question: how does temperature warming and algal nutritional availability effect higher trophic levels? I will conduct a laboratory experiment looking at a tri-trophic food chain. I will grow microalgae populations at various temperatures to see if there are changes to their nutritional availability through fatty acid analysis. I will then see if these changes affect higher trophic levels by feeding the different temperature algae to zooplankton and then the zooplankton to midge larvae. I will look for changes in the growth and population size of these higher trophic levels to see if temperature-mediated changes to nutrient availability effects higher trophic levels.\r\n","principal_investigator":"Jihyun Kim","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"jihyun03@student.ubc.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9891,"title":"Evaluation of Cannabis Advanced Odour Management Technologies DMP","dmptemplate_id":45,"created_at":"2020-11-05 13:21:57 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-05 16:08:40 UTC","slug":"evaluation-of-cannabis-advanced-odour-management-technologies-dmp","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":"030567","identifier":"UG-T1-2020-100121 ","description":"This project will evaluate the performance of known odour removal technology as well as alternative technologies through in-situ demonstration.  The research is aimed at improving air quality both within the working environment inside the greenhouse and minimizing the odour impact from the greenhouse on adjacent properties.","principal_investigator":"Ed McBean","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Ed McBean, emcbean@uoguelph.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":9892,"title":"Masters Thesis Project","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-11-05 14:42:50 UTC","updated_at":"2020-11-10 17:18:40 UTC","slug":"masters-thesis-project","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Identifying the potential for toxic algal blooms across freshwater sources across Canada using DNA analysis methods to detect presence of toxin genes in Cyanobacteria communities.","principal_investigator":"Hadeel Abed","princ