-columbia-generic-template--640","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Erin Fields","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":10070,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-12-03 13:10:44 UTC","updated_at":"2021-01-16 13:53:16 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--4001","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"","identifier":"RES0053337","description":"This project aims to understand how the risk assessments related to project financing under the extreme-risk scenario posed by COVID-19 interacts with the specific challenges the pandemic also poses to advancing equity, diversity and inclusion. This particular data plan relates to Work Package One of the project. ","principal_investigator":"Deb Verhoeven, Amanada Coles, Ken Rogers","principal_investigator_identifier":"https://orcid.org/0000-0003-3680-3561","data_contact":"Erin Sanderman","funder_name":null},{"id":10071,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-12-03 14:25:01 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-03 14:25:01 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--4002","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Robyn Nicholson","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":10072,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-12-03 15:08:36 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-03 15:08:36 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--4003","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Jessica Ross","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":10073,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-12-03 17:13:27 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-03 17:13:27 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--4004","organisation_id":26,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Patricia Lara","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":10074,"title":"My plan (University of Manitoba )","dmptemplate_id":35,"created_at":"2020-12-04 11:00:15 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-04 11:00:15 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-manitoba--73","organisation_id":37,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Jacqueline Hay","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":10075,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-12-04 16:06:15 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-04 16:06:15 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--4005","organisation_id":23,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Eli Kinney-Lang","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":10076,"title":"M.Sc Research Project","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-12-04 16:30:59 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-04 16:34:51 UTC","slug":"m-sc-research-project","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Analyzing food web structure in Arctic coastal ecosystems in Northern Canada. Specifically Igloolik, Kinngait and Southampton. I will be analyzing invertebrates, zooplankton and fish using stable isotope analysis and looking to see if there is any relation between the food web structure and environmental gradients such as temperature, salinity and depth. This will help increase the understanding of Arctic food web structures in order for us to be able to predict future changes. Being able to predict future changes will help northern communities be able to determine which species they will be able to hunt for food in the future and it will help scientists be able to predict which species are more vulnerable to future climate induced changes. ","principal_investigator":"Madeleine Prater","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":10077,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-12-04 19:54:45 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-04 19:54:45 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--4007","organisation_id":28,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Sasindu Gunawardana","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":10078,"title":"Thesis data mangagement plan ","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-12-05 01:53:52 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-05 02:33:01 UTC","slug":"thesis-data-mangagement-plan","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Marissa  Z","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":10079,"title":"BMI Sampling 2020","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-12-05 15:29:08 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-05 15:36:30 UTC","slug":"bmi-sampling-2020","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"My research will follow up on upgrades made to the Kitchener and Waterloo wastewater treatment plants, using benthic macroinvertebrates (BMI) as a metric for stream health to assess the effectiveness of these upgrades. I will be collecting samples of BMI in the riverbed and preserving them for later subsampling, so it will be important for me to keep an inventory of all samples collected. Information like where they were collected, when, and how many bottles were needed to contain the sample are necessary for when I follow-up with my samples. ","principal_investigator":"Sean McLay","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":10080,"title":"My plan (University of British Columbia Generic Template)","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2020-12-06 17:18:32 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-06 17:18:32 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-british-columbia-generic-template--641","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Siobhan Schenk","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":10081,"title":"Tania Rodriguez-Cornejo's plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-12-07 07:03:15 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-09 15:16:58 UTC","slug":"tania-rodriguez-cornejo-s-plan-portage-template","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Study of the direct antimicrobial activity and immunostimulant properties of pituitary adenylate cyclase-activating polypeptide (PACAP) to treat and prevent microbial infections in rainbow trout (Oncorhynchus mykiss) aquaculture, to be used as an alternative to antibiotics.","principal_investigator":"Tania Rodriguez Cornejo","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":10082,"title":"COVID-19 and SNHL","dmptemplate_id":56,"created_at":"2020-12-07 12:34:33 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-07 12:42:30 UTC","slug":"covid-19-and-snhl","organisation_id":15,"grant_number":"","identifier":"2020-5185","description":"Objective: The goal of this research is to establish whether COVID-19 can cause sensorineural hearing loss (SNHL), and we will also explore the relationship between magnitude of hearing loss and the severity of the disease. \r\nBackground: The COVID-19 pandemic is adversely affecting populations around the world. COVID-19 is the infectious disease caused by the most recent novel coronavirus (nCOV) first identified in Wuhan, China in December 2019 (Hegarty, 2020), and belongs to the family of coronaviruses that cause common infections such as the cold to more severe infections such as Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS) and Middle East Respiratory Syndrome (MERS). Due to evidence of neuroinflammation, demyelination, and other neurotropic effects, researchers are monitoring sequelae to establish the short- and long-term effects and to better prepare for future viral pandemics. This research will determine whether COVID-19 causes SNHL in both symptomatic and asymptomatic patients, as a function of disease severity. SNHL is the loss or interruption of the transmission of sound from the inner ear to the brain, either due to damage to the sensorial organ (i.e., the inner ear or cochlea) or to subsequent neural dysfunction. Its primary causes in older adults are noise- and age-related changes to the inner ear. However, SNHL also occurs as a result of hypoxia and neurotropic effects (Cohen, Durstenfeld, & Roehm, 2014), both of which have been associated with COVID-19. This study will determine whether COVID-19 causes SNHL. \r\nEvidence: Several case studies report hearing issues as a symptom of COVID-19 (Cui et al., 2020; Fidan, 2020; Han et al., 2020; Sriwijitalai & Wiwanitkit, 2020). Unfortunately, these case reports are generally short and supply insufficient detail regarding type and extent of hearing loss. In a cross-sectional study, Freni et al., (2020) focussed on categorizing Ear, Nose, and Throat symptoms of COVID-19. They found that roughly 40% of patients (20/50) reported hearing loss during their convalescence. When re-tested 15 days after a negative result for COVID-19, about 18% still reported some degree of hearing loss. Mustafa et al. (2020) recruited 20 asymptomatic patients with confirmed positive COVID-19 as their test group and monitored them for two weeks. The researchers excluded patients with any history of hearing loss and restricted the age range to 20–50 years to avoid the inclusion of age-related hearing loss. The control group (N=20) had normal hearing and no history of hearing difficulties. The researchers found no significant hearing differences (p > 0.05) from 0.25 to 3 kHz, but significantly poorer higher frequency (4¬–8 kHz) hearing thresholds (p > 0.05) indicating possible COVID-19-related hearing loss. They also found significantly reduced transient evoked otoacoustic emission (TEOAE) amplitudes in the test group indicating possible dysfunction with the active processes of a healthy cochlea. In another multi-site questionnaire study in Europe, Lechien et al., (2020) examined 1,420 mild-to-moderate patients from 18 European hospitals with confirmed positive COVID-19 to better understand the symptomatology of the disease. About 25% of patients indicated they experienced ear pain during their convalescence. Of this group, about half still reported ear pain after recovery. The researchers did not investigate the cause of the pain and directed patients with ear pain to consult their hearing care specialist. Given the current absence of high-quality evidence for COVID-19 induced SNHL and the magnitude of the pandemic, research into this issue is critical, so that COVID-19 disease processes can be better understood and appropriate measures to prevent, treat and remediate any related hearing loss can be developed (Almufarrij, Uus, and Monroe,  2020).","principal_investigator":"Patricia Van Roon","principal_investigator_identifier":"B00763713","data_contact":"patricia.vanroon@dal.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":10083,"title":"IDG - Indigenous Social Mobility","dmptemplate_id":20,"created_at":"2020-12-07 14:23:08 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-07 14:24:11 UTC","slug":"idg-indigenous-social-mobility","organisation_id":16,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Rochelle Côté","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"rrcote@mun.ca; +1 709.864.3758","funder_name":null},{"id":10084,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-12-07 19:06:53 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-07 19:06:53 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--4011","organisation_id":1,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":10086,"title":"CAND3 workflow training","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-12-08 13:50:38 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-08 13:52:15 UTC","slug":"cand3-workflow-training","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"CAND3 DMP Assistant Demo","principal_investigator":"Grant Gibson","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":10087,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-12-08 16:40:52 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-08 16:40:52 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--4013","organisation_id":27,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Mike McCaffrey","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":10088,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-12-08 16:41:29 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-08 16:41:29 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--4014","organisation_id":45,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Mike McCaffrey","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":10089,"title":"The fall and spring energetic bottlenecks of M. lucifugus ","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-12-08 17:33:47 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-08 20:37:48 UTC","slug":"the-fall-and-spring-energetic-bottlenecks-of-m-lucifugus","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Hibernating mammals face a discrepancy between their energetic needs and the energetic resources available in both the fall and spring. This is referred to as an energetic bottleneck. \r\n\r\nBats are no exception to experiencing energetic bottlenecks. Temperate hibernating bats face declining temperatures and insect abundance in the fall, when they need to develop fat stores for hibernation. In the spring, they are immediately subjected to cold temperatures, inclement weather, and low insect availability when they need to begin restoring their body condition. This is particularly of relevance to female bats, which reproduce in the spring. \r\n\r\nThe energetic bottleneck they face in the spring is relatively understudied (compared to the fall). With the added challenge of the fungal disease white-nose syndrome (WNS), my thesis project focuses on bat fattening and foraging strategies in the fall and spring. \r\n\r\nThe types of challenges bats face directly before and after hibernation are largely relevant towards understanding the annual of bats. Therefore, this study will fill in two gaps. Firstly, how bats respond to the energetic challenges posed by the spring. Secondly, how bats have possibly changed their energetic strategies in the fall in the presence of a pathogenic fungus (potentially suggesting an adaptive response).","principal_investigator":"Gwynne Domashinski","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":10090,"title":"PACAP as an immunomodulator in aquatic invertebrates","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-12-08 19:15:23 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-08 19:18:24 UTC","slug":"pacap-as-an-immunomodulator-in-aquatic-invertebrates","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"This study focuses on the application of a highly conserved, multifunctional neuropeptide with antimicrobial properties – pituitary adenylate cyclase activating polypeptide (PACAP) – as an immunomodulator and antiviral agent in an invertebrate model. This research will help develop immune treatments that can reduce the use of antibiotics in shrimp aquaculture worldwide. worldwide","principal_investigator":"Emma  Monod","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"emonod@uwaterloo.ca","funder_name":null},{"id":10091,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2020-12-08 19:49:47 UTC","updated_at":"2020-12-08 19:49:47 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--4017","organisation_id":27,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Michael 