,"dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2021-01-28 01:32:06 UTC","updated_at":"2021-01-28 01:34:34 UTC","slug":"social-groups-and-crime","organisation_id":25,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Owen Gallupe","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":10206,"title":"Assessing the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on social and health outcomes among  young people: A mixed-method comparative analysis in Canada and France","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2021-01-28 03:46:48 UTC","updated_at":"2021-02-01 21:44:05 UTC","slug":"assessing-the-impact-of-the-covid-19-pandemic-on-social-and-health-outcomes-among-young-people-a-mixed-method-comparative-analysis-in-canada-and-france","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"Globally, young people are not generally prioritized as a key\r\npopulation within many of the social and economic\r\nresponses to COVID-19. However, the social, policy, and\r\npublic health responses and associated effects of COVID-19\r\n(e.g., physical distancing, job loss, isolation) will have\r\nsignificant individual- and population-level impacts on the\r\nsocial and health outcomes of youth, particularly among\r\nsocially disadvantaged sub-groups. The aim of this study is\r\nto generate new context-sensitive and population-specific\r\ndata through interviews with youth in order to document how\r\npolicy and program responses can be optimized to improve\r\nthe lives of youth in Canada and France.","principal_investigator":"Rod Knight","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"Naseeb Bolduc (naseeb.bolduc@bccsu.ubc.ca)","funder_name":null},{"id":10207,"title":"My plan (University of British Columbia Generic Template)","dmptemplate_id":11,"created_at":"2021-01-28 03:47:46 UTC","updated_at":"2021-01-28 03:47:46 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-british-columbia-generic-template--645","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Naseeb Bolduc","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":10208,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2021-01-28 03:49:06 UTC","updated_at":"2021-01-28 03:49:06 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--4074","organisation_id":7,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Naseeb Bolduc","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":10210,"title":"Mon plan (Modèle Portage)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2021-01-28 13:24:33 UTC","updated_at":"2021-01-28 13:24:33 UTC","slug":"mon-plan-modele-portage--588","organisation_id":44,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Émilie Fortin","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":10211,"title":"Arctic Seasonal Models - Data Management Plan","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2021-01-28 14:39:06 UTC","updated_at":"2021-01-28 19:53:58 UTC","slug":"arctic-seasonal-models-data-management-plan","organisation_id":null,"grant_number":"","identifier":"P12","description":"The Arctic is facing the highest rate of global warming on Earth and rapid industrial development. Major environmental transformations such as permafrost thawing or sea ice reduction are affecting wildlife. However, how ecosystems and the species that compose them will respond to multiple stressors (e.g. climate change, industrial shipping and resource extraction) is still poorly understood. In the Arctic, strong seasonality promotes multiple exchanges (e.g. energy, contaminants) among ecosystems (terrestrial and marine), including distant ones, due to wind, oceanic currents, and animal migrations. Understanding the complexity of arctic food webs in changing environments requires modeling interconnections between ecosystems and species interactions. At the same time, it is important to document changes occurring in northern environments and especially in animal abundance and distribution, using advanced technologies and by promoting community-based biodiversity monitoring. It is crucial to include such information in predictive models to evaluate how Arctic biodiversity is likely to be affected by environmental changes and anthropogenic activities and how these changes will impact ecosystem services and ultimately northern communities. Such models are helpful to guide future decisions to mitigate the effects of multiple stressors. More specifically, our project is 1) Developing new models of the tundra food-webs that incorporate seasonality, animal migration and interactions with marine and southern ecosystems; 2) monitoring key species and processes occurring during the winter period to fill important knowledge gaps in developing seasonal models; 3) Promoting and supporting community-based and citizen science programs with northern communities to address environmental issues that matter to Northerners in order to scale-up spatially and temporally (i.e. year-round) biodiversity monitoring; and 4) Maintaining long-term ecosystem-based monitoring programs to feed and test ecosystem models. In our models, existing data are combined to new field studies conducted on Bylot Island, around the community of Pond Inlet, and at Alert (Canadian Forces Station) on the abundance and movements of predators and migratory birds, and the interactions between wildlife, snow conditions, contaminants and diseases. Observations made by Northerners will complement data collected by scientists because Northern inhabitants are sentinels that can track changes in their environment, especially during winter. Our project is also contributing to capacity building in the North by training Northerners and graduate students.","principal_investigator":"Pierre Legagneux","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":10212,"title":"My plan (University of Manitoba )","dmptemplate_id":35,"created_at":"2021-01-28 16:08:31 UTC","updated_at":"2021-01-28 16:08:31 UTC","slug":"my-plan-university-of-manitoba--74","organisation_id":37,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Navjot Pachu","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":10213,"title":"DEMO Plan","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2021-01-28 17:18:52 UTC","updated_at":"2021-01-28 17:20:03 UTC","slug":"demo-plan--4","organisation_id":44,"grant_number":"","identifier":"","description":"","principal_investigator":"Etienne Godin","principal_investigator_identifier":"","data_contact":"","funder_name":null},{"id":10214,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2021-01-28 19:38:38 UTC","updated_at":"2021-01-28 19:38:38 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--4077","organisation_id":22,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Carly Huitema","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":10215,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2021-01-29 15:29:35 UTC","updated_at":"2021-01-29 15:29:35 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--4078","organisation_id":26,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Harsh Brahmbhatt","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":10216,"title":"My plan (Portage Template)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2021-01-29 15:30:47 UTC","updated_at":"2021-01-29 15:30:47 UTC","slug":"my-plan-portage-template--4079","organisation_id":8,"grant_number":null,"identifier":null,"description":null,"principal_investigator":"Harsh Brahmbhatt","principal_investigator_identifier":null,"data_contact":null,"funder_name":null},{"id":10217,"title":"Mon plan (Modèle Portage)","dmptemplate_id":12,"created_at":"2021-01-30 00:44:19 UTC","updated_at":"2021-